<FIRST>u w AM-Barry-Taxes     04-17 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Taxes,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Filed Federal Tax Returns Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry filed
his federal income tax returns late in the early 1980s even though
he had a refund coming each year, according to The Washington Post.
   The newspaper quoted an unnamed source as saying that Barry
waited until 1986 to file his 1982, 1983 and 1984 federal returns.
Other sources told the Post that Barry filed several returns in
1986 but could not confirm the years.
   Barry declined a request by the newspaper to be interviewed
about his tax returns. His press secretary, John C. White, released
a statement that Barry's returns are filed every year.
   ``First, my taxes are a personal matter between myself and the
federal and district governments. Second, my taxes are filed every
year by my accountant in the year in which they are due. Third, it
is a violation of law for someone to give out my tax returns other
than myself,'' Barry said in a statement.
   The mayor, who has refused to publicly release copies of his tax
returns since he was elected in 1978, filed late ``largely because
of procrastination,'' the Post, in its Tuesday editions, quoted one
of Barry's associates as saying.
   Failure to file a federal income tax return is a misdemeanor and
each count carries a possible one-year prison sentence.
   Although Barry's federal returns for 1982, 1983 and 1984 were
late, he apparently filed his D.C. returns on time for those years,
the Post said.
   D.C. records show that Barry filed his 1982, 1983 and 1984
returns in the year in which each return was due, according a
source familier with District tax records. Barry received D.C.
refunds for each of the years except 1982.
</TEXT>
