<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Victim     04-17 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Victim,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victim Wakes Screaming from Dreams of Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Philippines-Rights, Bjt ^By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAGAWE, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Her own screams wake Susan Aniban
from nightmares about military captors connecting wires to her
thumbs, toes and breasts and sending jolts of electricity through
her naked body.
   Miss Aniban, 26, a volunteer for the church-affiliated Task
Force Detainees, said she and a male colleague were arrested in
November and accused of being couriers for communist rebels. She
denies it.
   She said she was interrogated at three military camps in the
Baguio area, where they were arrested, and her captors tried to
rape her three times.
   ``They tied my toes, thumbs and nipples with electric wires and
then they plugged it into a socket,'' she said. ``They did it to me
repeatedly and I fainted so many times.
   ``They took off my clothes and made me sit on a wet bed. I had
my hands tied in the back and a pillow over my mouth. I screamed,
and I felt like a chicken being butchered.''
   After three days, Miss Aniban and her colleague were released.
She said they had signed statements saying they were rebels and
agreeing to serve as military informants.
   She said she did not file charges against her captors because
whe felt it would be useless.
   Last year, she convinced her younger brother Jesus to leave the
rebels and he was shot to death five months later. As she cradled
her dying brother in her arms, Miss Aniban said, he told her his
assailants were pro-government militiamen.
   The family filed charges with the government Commission on Human
Rights and a civil court, but no hearings have been held.
   Her experiences made her bitter. Although she works for a human
rights group organized to monitor abuses under Ferdinand E. Marcos,
the exiled former president, she now opposes Corazon Aquino, his
successor.
   ``I expected my work to be risky, but I did not expect it could
still happen under the new government,'' she said. ``Now, she is no
longer my president.''
</TEXT>
