<FIRST>r w PM-Speakers'Woes     04-17 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Speakers' Woes,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Echoes of a Speakers' Scandal Followed Blaine for
Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the morning of June 5, 1876, James G.
Blaine, the speaker of the House of Representatives, stood in the
well of the House and waved a packet of letters in the air.
   Blaine, one of the nation's foremost politicians, was in serious
trouble.
   And he was about to confound his accusers.
   Nearly 113 years later another speaker of the House _ Jim Wright
of Texas _ faces accusations of unethical behavior in office.
   Wright adamantly denies any wrongdoing. But he has been the
subject of the most prolonged and intense of the several
investigations conducted over the decades into the private and
public affairs of a speaker of the House.
   Speaker Blaine rode out his scandal, but echoes of it were to
follow him for the rest of his career.
   In the spring of 1876, Blaine was a frontrunner for the
Republican presidential nomination in the election that would
replace President Ulysses S. Grant's corruption-ridden
administration.
   Three years earlier Reps. Oakes Ames, R-Mass., and James Brooks,
D-Mass., had been censured by the House for involvement in the
so-called Credit Mobilier scandal in which railroad construction
stock had been given to selected members of Congress, allegedly for
favors received.
   Now Blaine became embroiled in the scandal, facing accusations
that the Union Pacific Railroad had paid the speaker an inflated
price for stock of a defunct and bankrupt rail line.
   An investigation was launched by the House Judiciary Committee
but it was sputtering when new evidence emerged.
   It took the form of a set of letters between Blaine and a
business partner which had come into the possession of a third man,
James Mulligan.
   Mulligan, in Washington to testify before the committee,
encountered an unexpected visitor at his hotel _ Speaker James G.
Blaine.
   According to Mulligan, an emotional session followed in which
Blaine fell to his hands and knees and begged for the letters,
threatening suicide if he did not receive them.
   Mulligan claimed Blaine obtained the letters by a pretext and
left the hotel.
   An uproar followed and Blaine came under intense pressure to
make the Mulligan letters public. He refused, claiming they were
private property.
   Instead, he obtained a statement from two lawyers who said they
had examined the letters and found nothing relevant to the
investigation.
   The uproar continued and Blaine set about to defuse it.
   On June 5 he appeared on the House floor and waved the packet
exclaiming, ``There they are. ... There are the original letters.''
   Blaine then read aloud what he said were the contents of each of
the letters. He said he had handed over ``every solitary scrap and
scrimption'' for inclusion in the Congressional Record.
   They had, he declared, ``no more to do with that investigation
than the North Pole.''
   But no one was ever shown the originals of the letters to verify
Blaine's reading of them.
   Events moved rapidly.
   Blaine collapsed outside his church suffering from a possible
heat stroke. The investigation was postponed for two weeks to await
his recovery. But before the committee could reconvene, the
governor of Maine appointed Blaine to fill a vacancy in the Senate.
   The investigation was postponed again, and eventually died.
   Blaine's political backers proceeded, in classical Washington
fashion, to make the best of a bad situation.
   In the 20th century it's called making lemonade out of a lemon.
   Blaine's name was placed in nomination at the Republican
National Convention by Robert G. Ingersoll on June 15, 1876, with
words that gave Blaine an enduring nickname: ``The plumed knight
from the state of Maine.''
   ``Like an armed warrior, like a plumed knight, James G. Blaine
marched down the halls of the American Congress and threw his
shining lance full and fair against the brazen forehead of every
traitor to his country and every maligner of his fair reputation.''
   Blaine never obtained the presidency.
   But he twice was appointed secretary of state.
   No House speaker has ever been ousted. But several have been
singed during the 200-year history of Congress.
   Henry Clay, who was elected speaker six times, drew accusations
of ``corrupt bargain'' when the close election of 1824 was thrown
into the House of Representatives.
   The choice was between Andrew Jackson and John Quincy Adams.
Clay and other members of the Kentucky delegation tipped the
balance in favor of Adams.
   The accusations flew after the victorious Adams named Clay as
his secretary of state.
   Speaker Samuel J. Randall, a Pennsylvania Democrat, promptly
called for his own investigation in 1879 after being accused of
favoritism toward a company which provided the paper for the bonds
and banknotes produced by the Bureau of Engraving.
   He was quickly cleared.
   In 1910 Speaker Joseph G. Cannon faced a rebellion against his
imperious and heavy handed rule of the House.
   Although not deposed, Cannon was stripped of much of his power.
   Speaker Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill, D-Mass., was named in the
so-called ``Koreagate'' influence peddling scandal in the 1970's
but was exonerated.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence L. Knutson covers Congress for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
