<FIRST>r w PM-ScandalTour Bjt   04-17 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scandal Tour, Bjt,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Scandal Tours' of Capital Are Hit Among Jaded Tourists</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Note contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leave the kids at home, skip the Lincoln
Memorial and take a ``scandal tour'' of Washington, a raunchy romp
through the ruins of political careers that takes ogling grownups
from the Watergate to Gary Hart's old townhouse.
   With a George Bush impersonator acting as host, the 75-minute
bus tour leaving on weekends from the posh Ritz-Carlton Hotel is
just the tonic for bored tourists willing to spend 20 bucks to
indulge their taste for the trashy.
   Careening through city streets in a red, white and blue bus, a
satirical comedy troupe called Gross National Product entertains
customers with a bawdy commentary on passing landmarks where some
of Washington's most prominent residents fell prey to sex, booze,
greed or lust for power. Mostly sex.
   Outside the White House, a Marilyn Monroe look-alike croons a
song to John F. Kennedy, the gentleman who supposedly preferred
blondes. ``In my eight years in office, there will be no sex in the
White House,'' vowed Bush, seizing the microphone.
   Past the Executive Office Building, where mock secretary Fawn
Hall sobs her admiration for Col. Oliver North _ ``the most
patriotic man in the universe'' _ and recalls their Iran-Contra
shredding parties. Passengers are given small plastic bags filled
with shredded paper and signed ``Love, Fawn.''
   On to the Tidal Basin, where an inebriated Wilbur Mills saw both
his congressional career and his companion, stripper Fanne Foxe,
sink beneath the waves. Then to the Capitol, where John and Rita
Jenrette enjoyed a congress of a different sort and where a
homosexual congressman ``let his fingers do the walking through the
House and Senate pages.''
   The bus screeched to a halt behind the Capitol Hill townhouse
where Hart was caught entertaining model Donna Rice, dooming his
1988 Democratic presidential hopes. It's still the highlight of the
tour.
   ``Everybody out for some fresh air and fresh smut,'' shouted a
female tour guide. ``You're going to get out of the bus, you're
going to see it, you're going to touch it, you'll be there.''
   The crowd clustered around the garage where ``Donna Rice made
her backdoor debut for the Miami Herald,'' then strolled to the
front of the house to pose for pictures. Back on the bus, the
tourists sighed happily.
   ``What makes the best scandal?'' the guide asked.
   ``Sex,'' someone replied.
   ``Illicit sex,'' corrected a woman sitting in the rear.
   As the bus forged ahead, a black-robed comic posing as former
Supreme Court nominee Douglas Ginsburg offered to sell nickel bags
of marijuana and ``crank up some George Carlin tapes.'' A mimic of
Vice President Dan Quayle promised to ``serve you like I served the
National Guard _ on weekends.''
   Rick London, the 34-year-old writer and producer who founded
``Scandal Tours'' last August, said he was inspired while escorting
friends and relatives from his native Hattiesburg, Miss., to the
city's usual monuments and historical sites.
   ``I'd take them to the Capitol or the White House and you could
see their eyes start to glaze over,'' he says. ``Sooner or later,
they'd ask, `Where's Gary Hart's townhouse?' and I'd take them.
Then I thought, I ought to charge for this.''
   The tours are especially popular with British tourists and
Japanese businessmen, London says. He's making plans to start
``scandal tours'' in London, where ``the Brits take the prize,''
and possibly Rome and Paris.
   John Simmons, who plays Bush on the tour, says Washington
provides a constant source of comedy material because of its
explosive mixture of power, money and sex. The result, he says, is
``bad things happening to people it is hard to feel sorry for.''
   London says the tour focuses on sex scandals because they're
``easier for people to understand'' than complicated affairs
involving financial wrongdoing.
   He says he's found that Republicans account for 90 percent of
Washington's money scandals, while Democrats are usually the
culprits in sex scandals.
   ``That means that Republicans are spending a lot of time making
money,'' he said, ``and you can guess the rest.''
</TEXT>
