<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-RitualSlayings-Bodies 3rdLd-Writethru a0424 04-17 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritual Slayings-Bodies, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0424,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two More Bodies Found Buried At Ranch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-9, `Acting on ...' with five grafs to UPDATE with
funeral home saying new victims killed by machete blows; CORRECT age of
man in 5th and 9th grafs to 72, sted 77.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities discovered two more bodies
Sunday buried on a collective farm two miles south of a ranch where
13 victims of a cult of human sacrifice were found last week.
   Investigators said they have evidence the male victims were
killed by the same drug smuggling cult suspected of performing
human sacrifices on the 13 males discovered Tuesday at Rancho Santa
Elena, about 20 miles west of Matamoros.
   Cameron County Sheriff Alex Perez said the victims found Sunday
were connected to the drug smuggling operations of the cult, but
were not victims of the cult's rites as were the other 13.
   Unlike the bodies uncovered at Rancho Santa Elena, the bodies
found on the farm were not mutilated, said Mexican federal police
group chief Martin Elias Salazar.
   Acting on a tip from some children, a 72-year-old man led police
Sunday to the common grave in a clearing in an orchard on the farm,
Ejido Santa Librada, Salazar told reporters.
   The dead were identified as Moises Castillo Vasquez, the son of
the man who led police to the site, and Hector de la Fuente, also
known as ``El Guero'', or ``The Blond.'' Both were killed by
machete chops to the back of the head, said Jose Degadillo, an
employee at Funerales Rosario. Some of the victims found on the
ranch last week also were killed by machete chops.
   ``It was a revenge type killing. It was a drug deal gone sour,''
Perez said. The sheriff said the men apparently died in May. He
said he knew about the men because of an ongoing investigation into
the drug smuggling ring.
   However, a spokeswoman for the federal judicial police in
Matamoros said the two men were farmhands who had been missing
since last May.
   The children told the 72-year-old man, Hidalgo Castillo, that
they had seen some people burying a body in an orchard last
October, Salazar said. Castillo's son, Moises, 52, disappeared last
May. Salazar said Castillo had discounted the children's tale until
the 13 bodies were dug up.
   The two bodies were stacked and appeared to be those of adults,
investigators said. Neither had been positively identified as of
Sunday night.
   Officials disinterred the second body just before sunset Sunday.
Salazar searched through the pockets of a pair of black pants found
on the second body and discovered 3,000 Mexican pesos and a $5 bill.
   Four suspects arrested in the slayings of the 13 discovered on
Rancho Santa Elena have told police they killed 13 or 14 people in
bizarre rites intended to protect a marijuana smuggling ring. Among
the victims were a 16-year-old boy and Mark Kilroy, missing since
March when he came here during spring break from the University of
Texas.
   Police said the suspects have been cooperative in pointing out
the bodies and had not mentioned burying anybody on Ejido Santa
Librada. Ejido means collective farm in Spanish.
   Officials said the group trafficked in drugs and believed the
human sacrifice would protect them from police. In Matamoros,
authorities found altars covered with black chicken feathers,
burned turtles, cigars and other occult offerings. The bodies had
been mutilated, some with their hearts or brains ripped out.
   Police in Mexico and the United States are seeking alleged
ringleader Adolfo Constanzo and three others, including Sara
Aldrete, a college student identified as the ``godmother'' of the
cult.
   In a related development, Notimex, the Mexican government news
agency, reported Saturday that a woman identifying herself as Sara
Aldrete Villareal called a local radio station threatening to
kidnap children as hostages and burn them if the four prisoners
were not released.
   The news agency said local police in Matamoros dismissed the
report as a hoax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
