<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--StatenIsland     04-17 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Staten Island,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Senate Approves Secession Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Senate approved a bill to let
Staten Island residents vote on whether to secede from New York
City.
   The bill was introduced after the U.S. Supreme Court's
declaration in March that the city's powerful Board of Estimate,
which rules on spending and projects, violated the principle of one
man, one vote.
   Staten Island, the city's smallest borough with about 400,000
residents, has an equal presence on the board as the other four
boroughs, including Brooklyn with 2.2 million residents.
   ``There are 41 nations in the United Nations with less people
than Staten Island,'' Sen. John Marchi said after Sunday night's
vote.
   ``Who could be against one man, one vote, but it has to
accommodate the human condition,'' said the Staten Island
Republican, who sponsored the bill.
   The measure was approved 34-1 without debate in the
Republican-controlled Senate. It is given little chance of approval
in the Assembly, which is dominated by Democrats from the city's
more populous boroughs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
