<FIRST>r a PM-BulletproofHalter     04-17 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bulletproof Halter,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wanted: Practical Use for Bullet-Proof Halter Top</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DC2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER MUNNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The halter created by design student
Beth Teggatz doesn't cover a lot of flesh, but it packs a lot of
protection.
   The top and matching knee-length pants and gauntlet-style gloves
are made of a bulletproof, fire-resistant material, Kevlar 29.
   ``I don't think there are any practical uses, unless Cher might
be interested, or maybe a punk rock group,'' said Teggatz, a senior
at Iowa State University.
   But practicality is beside the point. The halter will be among
many unusual items going on display next week at Focus, the
university's annual arts festival that prizes the creative over the
marketable.
   ``The idea is to show that at this highly technical institution
there are quite a few original ideas,'' said Pat Miller,
coordinator of the exhibit at the school known mainly for business,
engineering and agricultural studies.
   Ms. Teggatz, 22, says her halter will be displayed on a
mannequin, although real live models have given it a try. ``They
have laughed, but they've been pretty agreeable,'' she said.
   Ms. Teggatz also will display a wedding dress made from
radiation-resistant fabric.
   ``It's really quite sturdy,'' she said. ``The material is thin
like paper, but it doesn't rip. It's quite easy to work with.''
   The material, which like the Kevlar is made by Du Pont, is used
for garments worn by workers in nuclear plants. After exposure to
radiation, the garment is discarded.
   ``I've had people tell me that since the wedding dress is almost
a papery-like substance that would get thrown away after use, maybe
it could be used for all the disposable weddings in society
anymore,'' she said.
   Ms. Teggatz cherishes the opportunity to stretch her creativity
to bizarre extremes while she can.
   ``I'll have to settle down soon enough,'' she said. ``You can't
make money being too creative.''
</TEXT>
