<FIRST>r a PM-WinerySlayings-Chronology     04-17 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Winery Slayings-Chronology,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hour-By-Hour In Sonoma County Carnage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Winery Slayings, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN ELLEN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In one blood-drenched day, terror
struck the lush, rolling hills of this famous wine-producing region
as seven people were either shot to death, bludgeoned or had their
throats slashed.
   Ramon Salcido, 28, is being sought in the carnage that included
his wife and two young daughters, his mother-in-law and two of her
daughters, and a winery co-worker. One of his daughters, 3-year-old
Carmina Salcido, survived despite her throat being cut nearly
ear-to-ear.
   The search continued today for Salcido, whom authorities and
neighbors described as an insanely jealous, gun-toting drinker who
had problems at home and at work.
   Authorities still do not know the sequence of the killings, but
this is how the Sonoma County sheriff's department responded:
   _8:15 a.m. Friday: deputies received a 911 emergency call from
Kenneth Butti, 33, who reported that Salcido shot him in the
shoulder at his home in Kenwood.
   Butti, a bottling supervisor at the Grand Cru Winery, where
Salcido worked as a forklift operator, was treated at a hospital
and released.
   _9 a.m.: Officers who arrived at the winery near Butti's home
found Tracey Toovey, 35, an assistant winemaker, slumped halfway
out of the door of his car on a dirt access road to the winery,
dead of multiple gunshot wounds to his head.
   Other deputies were dispatched to Salcido's home a few miles
south in a lower middle-income neighborhood. They found Salcido's
wife, 24-year-old Angela, in a blood-splattered hallway. Deputies
said she had been shot a few times and beaten.
   _9:30 a.m.: Deputies were sent to the home of Salcido's in-laws
in Cotati, where they made the most grisly discovery yet. Amid more
blood-splattered walls and floors were three bodies. Marian Louise
Richards, 47, was dead in the hallway. Her 12-year-old daughter,
Ruth, was dead in the kitchen, and another daughter, 8-year-old
Marie, was dead in a bedroom. Both girls were sexually molested,
sodomized, and one of the children was nearly decapitated,
authorities said.
   Sonoma County Sheriff Dick Michaelsen called the scene ``a
slaughterhouse.''
   Neighbors reported hearing shouts of ``no, no'' coming from the
Richards' house, but no sound was heard after 7 a.m.
   Authorities launched a manhunt for Salcido, who was spotted in
his car with his own three children by a school bus driver. An
all-points bulletin was issued.
   _4 p.m.: The sheriff held a news conference and said he feared
for the lives of the girls, aged 1, 3 and 4. Salcido's ex-wife and
daughter in Fresno were alerted and taken into protective custody.
   Salcido reportedly was upset because he was served with child
support papers Tuesday from Frenso County Superior Court, ordering
him to pay $511 a month in child support payments and nearly $6,000
to the county for back support.
   _6 p.m.: Salcido's abandoned car was found in an industrial area
of San Rafael. Authorities found a .22-caliber semi-automatic
handgun inside.
   _2:30 p.m. Saturday: A man peering over an embankment at a
county dump southeast of Petaluma, spotted what he believed were
dolls _ until he noticed one of the figures moving. He alerted
police. Authorities found the bodies of two of Salcido's daughters,
Sofia, 4, and Teresa, 1. Carmina was alive.
   The girls' throats had been slashed. Michaelsen later disclosed
that Carmina said her father attacked the girls and left them for
dead.
   _5:30 p.m.: Carmina came out of two hours of surgery in serious
but stable condition.
   _Sunday, noon: Michaelsen said that although authorities had
been notified throughout the state, the search for Salcido was
centered on Sonoma County and San Rafael, where Salcido left his
car on Friday.
   ``We want him. We want him now,'' Michaelsen said. ``Anybody is
in danger at this point. He has the potential to take another life
without batting an eye.''
</TEXT>
