<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-17 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips; Stocks At New High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against the Japanese yen for
the third consecutive day today, while share prices rose to yet
another record high on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 131.83 yen, down 0.62 from Friday's close.
It opened at 131.75 yen and ranged between 131.55 yen and 131.88
yen. The dollar has fallen 1.02 yen in the last three trading days.
   Currency dealers said the prospect of U.S. interest rates
topping out worked against the dollar.
   ``Major U.S. economic indicators released last week were within
the market's anticipated range, but now dollar-denominated interest
rates such as (U.S.) Treasury bonds will be in a downward direction
in the long-term perspective,'' said a dealer at the Bank of Tokyo,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. Commerce Department said Friday the nation's trade
deficit in February widened to $10.50 billion, up from a revised
deficit of $8.68 billion for January. The U.S. Federal Reserve
Board said industrial production was unchanged in March from the
previous month. Both figures were largely in line with advance
estimates.
   Another dealer with a major Japanese bank said trading was
``relatively quiet'' ahead of the release of U.S. consumer price
figures in Washington Tuesday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, an 86.50-point gainer Friday, added 157.89 more
points, or 0.48 percent, closing at a record high 33,308.33 points.
   Dealers said some investors remained unenthusiastic because of
uncertainty over Japan's political situation, but heavy buying by
trust fund managers toward late afternoon lifted the Nikkei index.
   ``It is a difficult time for investors to make new orders,''
said a dealer with Nikko Securities Co. ``But the market's
fundamentals are not so bad.''
</TEXT>
