<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Titus     04-17 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Titus,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roy V. Titus, Cosmetics Executive, Dies at 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Valentine Titus, a philanthropist and former
chairman of the cosmetics company founded by his mother, Helena
Rubinstein, has died of complications from diabetes. He was 79.
   Titus died Sunday at the Rusk Institute of New York University
Medical Center.
   Titus was born in London, the elder of Mrs. Rubinstein's two
sons by her first husband, Edward W. Titus.
   Titus moved with his family to the United States in 1914. After
earning degrees from Oxford and the Harvard School of Business
Administration, he joined a British affiliate of the cosmetics
company and served as an executive of the business in New York
until he retired in 1974.
   Titus served as chairman of the Helena Rubinstein Foundation, on
the board of the Children's Blood Foundation and the Board of
Governors of the Tel Aviv Museum, and was a trustee of the Oil,
Chemical &amp; Atomic Workers Union-Industry Pension Fund.
   A film buff, Titus in 1976 gave $1 million to the Museum of
Modern Art, which was used in part to renovate its film auditorium.
The auditorium was later divided and named the Roy and Niuta Titus
Theatres.
   He is survived by his wife, Niuta; a daughter from a previous
marriage, Helena R. Titus; a stepson, Louis Slesin; a stepdaughter,
Suzanne Slesin Steinberg, and two grandchildren.
</TEXT>
