<FIRST>r i PM-China     04-17 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beijing, Shanghai Students Hold Marches To Honor Hu Yaobang</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of students in Beijing and Shanghai
marched today to mourn the death of former Communist Party chief Hu
Yaobang, an outspoken reformist toppled by conservatives two years
ago.
   ``Long live Hu Yaobang, long live democracy, long live freedom,
long live the rule of law!'' chanted more than 600 students from
Beijing's Political Science and Law College.
   Marching behind a huge red flag bearing their school's name, the
students laid wreaths in Hu's honor at the base of a monument to
Communist martyrs in Tiananmen Square, the symbolic seat of power
in China.
   Hu, who died Saturday at age 73 after suffering a heart attack,
was regarded by intellectuals as favoring greater artistic and
scholarly freedoms than other Chinese leaders.
   While a crowd of several thousand looked on, the students sang
the Internationale and chanted slogans for about half an hour
before dispersing.
   ``We just want to express our grief over Hu Yaobang's death
because he was a great leader and his death is a loss to the
nation,'' said one student. ``We aren't making any political
statement.''
   But another student, Wang Zhixun, said the students were
expressing ``an attitude'' of dissatisfaction with the failure of
China's leaders to institute democratic reforms.
   ``Hu Yaobang dared to speak out, and he said things we students
supported,'' Wang said.
   In Shanghai, more than 1,000 students marched late Sunday from
Fudan University to Tongji University, singing former odes to
revolutionary leader Mao Tse-tung but substituting Hu's name.
   The demonstration lasted more two hours and broke up early this
morning, said Jason Hurpado of Portland, Ore., who is teaching
English at Fudan.
   Students at three other schools in Beijing, including the
nation's leading school, Beijing University, put up hundreds of
posters on their campuses over the weekend to express sorrow over
Hu's death, demand that his ouster be reassessed and call for
greater democracy.
   Authorities in Beijing and Shanghai have made no efforts to
interfere with the student activities, the largest display of
student unrest since the student marches of 1986-87 that led to
Hu's ouster.
   In the late 1970s Hu supervised the party's rehabilitation of
thousands of people wrongly jailed during the far-left Cultural
Revolution, including many scholars.
   He was ousted as party chief in 1987 for allegedly encouraging
``bourgeois'' Western influences in China and failing to quash
nationwide student pro-democracy marches that year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
