<FIRST>r a PM-Dolphin-Meditation     04-17 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dolphin-Meditation,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Meditate To Commune With Dolphins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of dolphin-loving
environmentalists recline on the sand with eyes closed and
meditate, opening their minds to receive telepathic messages they
say the playful marine mammals send them.
   ``We're offering a true and profound experience with nature,''
said Bob Dennis, 28, who directs Project Delphinus Internaional
from his rented seaside home 50 miles southeast of Los Angeles.
   As a group of the intelligent sea mammals surfaces near kelp
beds visible from his window, Dennis lifts an 8-inch conch shell
and blows, sending a deep bellow across the water.
   Dennis says the unorthodox group set up shop to document
communication between dolphins and humans in hopes the information
will further their environmental goals.
   He said if people truly believe they can communicate with
dolphins they will treat the animals with greater respect.
   ``Once you do that, how can you throw a beer can on the beach,
or shoot a dolphin because he's eating your squid?'' Dennis asked.
   The project was founded in 1987 by Dennis and Greg Hurley with
the goal of filming a documentary on dolphins to help end their
slaughter by fishermen.
   Group activities include meditation sessions on the beach,
wilderness excursions and dolphin-watching boat trips and
environmental talks. They also send a quarterly newsletter to about
3,000 people statewide.
   Project members believe the rituals of Australian aborigines,
Polynesian natives and other ancient cultures can help modern man
reunite with nature.
   To honor those rites and pay homage to dolphins during boating
trips, group members sound the conch shell horns and beat drums
lined with goat bellies to duplicate the way some ancient tribes
called the seagoing mammals that are renowned for the grace and
intelligence.
</TEXT>
