<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Rebels 1stLd-Writethru a0468 04-17 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Cool To Rebel Offer Of Peace If US Bases Shut</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Aquino reaction. Picks up
5th pvs, ``They realize...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino today
brushed aside an offer by communist rebels to declare a cease-fire
if she pledges to close U.S. military bases, and the U.S.
ambassador called the proposal a bid to weaken her government.
   The rebel National Democratic Front offered Sunday to declare a
unilateral cease-fire in the 20-year insurgency and open peace
talks if Mrs. Aquino vows to close the six U.S. bases when their
lease expires in 1991.
   ``As I have said, if we want a cease-fire then let's have a
cease-fire first without any conditions,'' said Mrs. Aquino, who
has refused to say if she will support an extension of the lease.
   Mrs. Aquino also raised doubts about who really was authorized
to speak for the rebels: ``Until we can find out once and for all
who is the leader who can speak for all of them, it is really very
difficult to sit down with anybody.'' The rebel statement, which
was delivered to news organizations, was signed by Satur Ocampo,
one of two rebel negotiators in short-lived peace talks in 1986.
Ocampo made similar proposal in an interview last month.
   Jose Maria Sison, founder of the banned Communist Party of the
Philippines, also gave the same statement in a videotaped interview
from Utrecht, the Netherlands, where he has sought asylum. Sison's
interview was broadcast over local television two weeks ago.
   U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt said today that the rebel offer
was aimed at undermining U.S.-Philippine relations and weakening
the Aquino government.
   ``They realize that these bases and these facilities perform a
very important economic role, and they want to do anything they can
to weaken the government,'' Platt said in an interview with radio
station DZRH.
   ``And so they are working hard to try and arrange for this
relationship to end,'' he added. Platt said the United States would
close the bases if the Philippine government wants them out.
   The United States maintains Clark Air Base and Subic Bay Naval
Base, two of its largest facilities overseas, and four smaller
installations in the Philippines. More than 60,000 Filipinos are
employed at the bases, where about 40,000 U.S. troops and their
dependents are stationed.
   The rebel statement said that if the Aquino government were to
close the bases by 1991 and promise no further agreements for U.S.
bases, ``the National Democratic Front would not hesitate to
immediately declare a unilateral cease-fire and enter into
negotiations for a comprehensive political settlement and a
peaceful end to the civil war.''
   But if the government refuses, the rebels said they were
determined ``to make U.S. imperialism pay dearly for the continued
stay of its bases and its increasing intervention in our people's
affairs.''
</TEXT>
