<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     04-17 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls on Signs U.S. Economy Slowing, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against all major currencies in
early European trading today on growing signs that U.S. economic
growth is slowing, dealers said. Gold prices were also lower.
   ``The dollar is low and calm,'' said one Italian trader,
attributing the dollar's steep decline over the weekend to the
market's perception that U.S. interest rates have peaked.
   Last week's figures showing the growth rate in U.S. producer
prices slowed in March and the U.S. trade deficit widened in
February were interpreted as a signal for slower economic growth
and perhaps lower U.S. interest rates, dealers said.
   ``Major U.S. economic indicators released last week were within
the market's anticipated range, but now dollar-denominated interest
rates such as (U.S.) Treasury bonds will be in a downward direction
in the long-term perspective,'' said a dealer at the Bank of Tokyo
in the Japanese capital.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.62 yen to a closing 131.83. Later, in
London, it was quoted higher at 132.15 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday:
   _ 1.8595 West German marks, down from 1.8725
   _ 1.6405 Swiss francs, down from 1.6510
   _ 6.2910 French francs, down from 6.3350
   _ 2.09625 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1145
   _ 1,363.90 Italian lire, down from 1,374.25
   _ 1.1855 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1875
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7080, compared with
$1.7000 Friday.
   Bullion dealers said gold failed to get support from the weaker
dollar.
   ``Gold is in a bearish mood at the moment,'' one London dealer
commented. ``There is a lack of faith in the market after its
recent dismal performance.''
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $385.50 a troy ounce,
down from $386.50 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $385.15.
   In Zurich, gold was selling at a bid $385.20, down from $387.00
late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 71 cents to close at a bid
$386.74.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $5.81 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $5.87.
</TEXT>
