<FIRST>r i PM-Honduras-Bomb     04-17 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras-Bomb,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Outside U.S. Embassy Warehouse, Killing One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIAGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded outside a U.S.
Embassy warehouse, killing a man who apparently was trying to plant
it and injuring his companion, police said.
   Embassy spokesman Charles V. Barclay said the warehouse in
eastern Tegucigalpa, about a mile from the embassy, suffered no
damage but the explosion interupted power in the area for about 20
minutes.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for Sunday's
blast. There have been three attacks on U.S. personnel and
installations in the country so far this year.
   Officials said Miguel Aguilar Flores, 39, a Honduran driver for
a state company was killed in the blast. A second, unidentified man
was injured and taken to a local hospital for treatment.
   National Police sources told The Associated Press the two
apparently were planting the bomb when it exploded. They said the
two had been riding a motorcycle.
   Police said they discovered detonators, grenades and similar
explosive devices among the men's belongings.
   It was not immediately known what is stored in the warehouse. In
the past, it has been used to store embassy vehicles, furniture and
office supplies.
   The most recent attack against U.S. personnel or installation in
Honduras occurred last week when U.S. troops exchanged fire with
attackers in northern Honduras. No one was injured in that
incident, but one jeep was destroyed by a bomb.
</TEXT>
