<FIRST>r a PM-BentonExhibit     04-17 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Benton Exhibit,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centennial Exhibit Of Benton's Work Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 100th anniversary of the birth of
Thomas Hart Benton, whose work brought him fame but not acceptance
by the art world's elite, received a spirited celebration in his
home state.
   Benton's admirers cut cake and drank toasts Sunday on the lawn
of the Nelson Gallery, where a major retrospective opened.
   ``Benton is still speaking to a large crowd,'' curator Henry
Adams said as 4,000 to 5,000 people toured the exhibit of almost 90
paintings.
   ``This is a very bold show, in that it maintains that Benton was
a major force in American art that has been overlooked,'' Adams
said.
   The exhibit moves to Detroit, New York City and Los Angeles
after its run at the Nelson ends June 18.
   On Saturday, the actual birthdate, a show of 55 Benton
lithographs opened at four financial institutions in Neosho, a town
of about 9,000 people where the artist grew up. He was regarded
there as egotistical and left with no love lost at age 17.
   At Kelly's, a bar in Westport, Benton's passion for bourbon was
celebrated Sunday with the sixth annual Benton Birthday Bourbon &amp;
Brunch Bash, aimed at raising $10,000 for scholarships to the
Kansas City Art Institute.
