<FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea-Labor     04-17 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea-Labor,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Major Auto Maker Shuts In South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third auto maker halted production
today in response to a wave of strikes by workers seeking higher
wages. Officials said the job actions threaten the nation's economy.
   Daewoo Motor Co., a joint venture between the U.S.-based General
Motors Corp. and South Korea's Daewoo Group, stopped its assembly
line today after a walkout at its parts suppliers. Similar protests
forced two other car makers _ Hyundai Motor Co. and Kia Motor Corp.
_ to stop production last week.
   Government officials said the actions by the three manufacturers
will slash South Korea's auto exports, projected at 650,000 cars
this year.
   Also today, 5,000 taxi drivers rallied in a park to press
demands for higher wages and improved working conditions. The
drivers threatened to strike next week unless their demands are met.
   South Korea has been hit by 431 worker strikes for higher wages
and benefits so far this year and 133 are still in progress, the
Labor Ministry said today. Government officials said strikes were
spreading to nearly all manufacturing industries and small firms.
   Police raided offices of labor activists and dissidents today
and seized thousands of leaflets in a crackdown on strikes. About
50 labor activists have been arrested.
   Kim Kun, head of the state-run Bank of Korea, said South Korea
is unlikely to achieve its economic growth target of 8 percent this
year, partly because of the strikes.
   Average wages in South Korea increased by 20 percent in 1987 and
1988, harming the international competitiveness of Korean products,
he said.
   South Korea registered a trade surplus of $94 million for the
January-March period, far below $1.35 billion in the same period
last year. In March alone, imports exceeded exports by $1 million,
South Korea's first monthly trade deficit in 19 months.
   In the worst labor unrest this year, thousands of riot police
stormed Hyundai Heavy Industries Co., South Korea's largest
shipyard, on March 31 to end a 109-day strike. The police action in
the southeastern industrial city of Ulsan triggered violent
protests by angry workers that lasted about two weeks and left
hundreds of workers and policemen injured.
</TEXT>
