<FIRST>r a PM-MspiLegislature     04-17 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mspi Legislature,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Return For Special Session on Parole Board, Improvements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Roy Mabus called the Legislature back
to work today to take up a measure that would protect Parole Board
members from being sued for crimes committed by freed inmates.
   Lawmakers during the three-day special session will also
consider a $79 million building program.
   The two proposals died in the closing days of the 1989 regular
session, which ended two weeks ago.
   The new Parole Board would have five full-time members with
immunity from liability. The current board has four part-time
members and a full-time chairman who meet several days a month.
   Momentum for restructuring the board built after a state judge
last year ordered three members to pay $3 million to a banker shot
and paralyzed by a parolee. The judgment is being appealed.
   The restructuring measure died on the last day of the regular
session after Mabus threatened a veto if it included an amendment
barring appointment of anyone who contributed $500 or more to any
campaign of the appointing governor.
   A proposal to issue bonds for capital improvements and property
purchases failed partly because some legislators were reluctant to
add to the state's indebtedness.
</TEXT>
