<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Tax     04-17 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Tax,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Accepts California Tax Case on Multinationals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to settle some
key questions involving the ability of multinational corporations
to challenge state taxes in federal court.
   What the justices decide sometime next year in a California case
could carry big-money significance for most states and many big
businesses.
   The court, granting an appeal by California officials, said they
will review a ruling that allowed two multinational corporations to
challenge a state tax in federal court.
   In a 1984 ruling seen as a major victory for states, the
justices ruled that California may tax multinational corporations
based on the businesses' worldwide income.
   But that decision applied only to multinationals whose parent
company is located in the United States.
   The case acted on today involves multinationals whose parent
company is based in a foreign country.
   California's business tax _ the same levy upheld in the 1984
ruling _ was challenged by Alcan Aluminium Limited, a Canadian
corporation, and Imperial Chemical Industries PLC, a British
corporation.
   California taxed subsidiaries of the multinationals doing
business in the state.
   The California tax employs what is known as the unitary system.
The method bases the tax on a share of worldwide earnings, payroll
and property value of each multinational and its subsidiaries.
   At issue in the appeal acted on today is whether multinationals
based abroad have legal standing to challenge such unitary state
taxes in federal courts in the United States.
   Alcan and Imperial challenged the California tax in a federal
court in Chicago, where the California Franchise Tax Board has an
office.
   A federal judge threw out the suits on grounds that the parent
companies claimed they were injured only in their capacity as
shareholders of their subsidiaries _ and therefore lacked legal
standing.
   Generally, shareholders are barred from suing in such cases
unless they can demonstrate ``a direct and independent injury''
from the corporation.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last October overturned
the judge's decision againt Alcan and Imperial, reinstating their
suits. The appeals court said there is grounds for the parent
companies to assert a direct and independent injury.
   ``Shareholders with direct, personal interests in a cause of
action can bring suit even if the corporation's legal rights and
obligations are also implicated,'' the appeals court said.
   The asserted injuries to Alcan and Imperial are direct and
independent, the appeals court said, because ``the unitary tax
diminishes the attractiveness of owning American subsidiaries in
comparison with entering into contracts with independent companies
as a means of engaging in foreign commerce.''
   The appeals court added: ``The potential for the unitary tax to
penalize foreign ownership of American assets distinguishes'' it
from other forms of state regulation _ environmental or safety
rules, for example _ that ``would presumably affect foreign and
domestically owned operations fairly equally.''
   The appeals court said taxes like the one imposed by California
``have fueled a simmering trade controversy which has raised
concerns about foreign retaliation and the (United States') ability
to speak with one voice on matters of foreign commerce.''
   Most states and the Multistate Tax Commission joined in
supporting California's appeal.
   The commission said the 7th Circuit court ruling's effect is to
permit multinational corporations to ``forum shop'' around the
country for a sympathetic federal judge who will permit the
businesses to challenge the state taxes.
   The case is Franchise Tax Board vs. Alcan Aluminium, 88-1400.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
