<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Lawyers     04-17 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lawyers,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Rule on Washington Lawyer Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to study a
``strike'' by lawyers in the nation's capital who sought higher pay
to represent penniless criminal defendants.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by federal officials who
say the lawyers violated antitrust law.
   The Superior Court Trial Lawyers Association here organized a
boycott in 1983 to pressure the District of Columbia government to
increase hourly compensation the city pays attorneys who represent
indigent criminal defendants.
   Some 100 lawyers who represent most of the city's poor criminal
defendants had been receiving $30 an hour for time in court and $20
an hour for out-of-court work. They won a $25 per hour increase
after a two-week boycott in which nearly all them refused to accept
new cases.
   The boycott created a crisis for the city, swamping the the city
public defender's office with criminal cases. The city government
agreed to the higher hourly rate at an annual cost to taxpayers of
more than $4 million.
   The private lawyers who boycotted represent 85 percent of the
poor defendants. The remaining defendants are represented by the
public defender service, third-year law students or, in a small
number of cases, lawyers volunteering to work without pay.
   After the so-called strike, the Federal Trade Commission ruled
that the lawyers engaged in price-fixing and an illegal boycott.
The FTC ordered the lawyers not to engage in similar conduct in the
future.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here set aside the FTC
decision and ordered the agency to restudy the case to determine
whether the lawyers had exerted ``market power'' in their boycott.
   Alleged antitrust violators are considered to be exerting market
power if they are capable of exercising economic control over a
relevant market.
   The appeals court here said it was unclear whether the boycott
succeeded because the lawyers exercised market power or political
clout.
   ``Power of some sort was surely exercised,'' the appeals court
said. ``The city council approved a rate increase it had long
refused two weeks into a boycott that disrupted the court system
and generated significant publicity.''
   The appeals court said the lawyers may have succeeded, even
though they lacked market power, by changing public attitudes and
making it politically safe for the city council to raise their pay.
   The boycott may have succeeded because it was persuasive rather
than coercive, the appeals court added.
   Also, the appeals court said, the FTC must judge the lawyers
``with a special solicitude'' because free-expression rights
protected by the Constitution are involved.
   The lawyers said the boycott was an exercise of their First
Amendment rights to petition the government for a redress of
grievances.
   In appealing to the Supreme Court, the FTC said the appeals
court ruling sets a dangerous precedent.
   The ruling ``erects formidable new barriers against antitrust
challenges to publicly conducted price-fixing boycotts,'' the FTC
said. ``The tax-paying public, no less than private parties, is
entitled to have its monies spent in markets in which all
participants obey the laws of competition.''
   The cases are FTC vs. Superior Court Trial Lawyers Association,
88-1198, and Superior Court Trial Lawyers vs. FTC, 88-1393.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
