<DOCNO> AP890417-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-NationalGuard     04-17 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-National Guard,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Upholds Federal National Guard Training in Massachusetts
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to bar the
federal government from requiring certain peacetime training for
any state's National Guard troops without first getting the
governor's consent.
   The justices, without comment, left intact a 1986 federal law
prohibiting governors from withholding permission for such training
missions.
   The law had been challenged by Massachusetts officials.
   Today's action does not preclude the possibility that the issue
could some day return to the nation's highest court.
   Since 1933, each person joining the National Guard
simultaneously enlists in two distinct organizations _ the Army or
Air National Guard of a particular state and the Army or Air
National Guard of the United States.
   The first organization serves as the state's militia; the second
as a reserve component of the national armed forces.
   Congress in 1986 passed the so-called Montgomery Amendment after
several governors voiced opposition to the Reagan administration's
Central American policy and said they would withhold their consent
to National Guard training missions in that region.
   The 1986 law prohibits any governor from withholding consent to
a National Guard unit's active duty outside the country because of
an objection to the location, purpose or schedule of such duty.
   A National Guard unit in Massachusetts was designated to
participate in a Central America training mission in mid-1988, but
Gov. Michael Dukakis objected.
   State officials sued the Department of Defense in federal court,
alleging that the 1986 law is unconstitutional.
   U.S. District Judge Robert E. Keeton upheld the law, and the 1st
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed last Oct. 25.
   The dispute centered on seemingly competing provisions in the
Constitution.
   One enpowers Congress ``to raise and support armies,'' including
``calling forth the miltia.''
   The other leaves to individual states the ``training of the
militia.''
   Judge Keeton ruled that a state's authority to train National
Guard members must yield to ``the legitimately exercised power of
Congress to raise and support armies.''
   Keeton's ruling relied, in part, on a 1918 Supreme Court
decision that upheld Congress' authority to draft members of a
state militia into the national armed forces during World War I.
   The judge discounted arguments by Massachusetts authorities that
a state's authority to supervise the training of National Guard
members is absolute during peacetime, and can be taken over by the
federal government only in times of national emergency.
   A three-judge panel of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
declared the Montgomery Amendment unconstitutional after the law
was challenged by Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich.
   That ruling currently is under review by the entire 8th Circuit
court.
   Urging the justices to reject Massachusetts' appeal, Bush
administration lawyers said, ``It would be incongruous to hold that
the Constitution gives Congress the power to establish these
reserves as components of the national armed forces but ...
withholds (federal) authority ... to conduct their training.''
   The administration lawyers added, ``Such a view would not only
undercut the effectiveness of the national defense but would also
inject the states into matters of foreign policy that the
Constitution reserves to the federal government.''
   As of 1986, Army National Guard members provided 46 percent of
the Army's combat units and 28 percent of its support forces.
   For fiscal year 1987, the Air National Guard members provided 73
percent of the nation's air defense interceptor forces and 25
percent of its tactical fighter forces.
   The case is Massachusetts vs. Department of Defense, 88-1223.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-EnglishOnly     04-17 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-English Only,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Challenge to California English-Only Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ordered the dismissal
of a challenge to a rule that generally requires Los Angeles city
court employees to speak only English while at work.
   The justices instructed the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to
take such action after being told that the woman who challenged the
rule no longer works for the city court.
   The rule was adopted by the southeast judicial district of the
Los Angeles Municipal Court in 1984.
   The rule bars court employees from speaking any language other
than English, except when acting as translators or during breaks
and lunchtime.
   The regulation was challenged by Alva Gutierrez, a
Hispanic-American who was a deputy court clerk. Ms. Gutierrez is
bilingual, and one of her duties was to translate for
Spanish-speaking members of the public that have business before
the city court.
   She said the English-only rule discriminates against her and
other minority group members based on their race and national
origin.
   The 9th Circuit court last year upheld a federal judge's
injunction barring enforcement of the rule pending further
developments in Ms. Guitierrez' suit.
   The appeals court also rejected arguments that the city judges
who adopted the rule are immune from being sued.
   The appeals court said while some employees who speak only
English may feel threatened by conversations in Spanish between
other workers, that is no legitimate basis for a discriminatory
policy.
   ``Existing racial fears or prejudices and their effects cannot
justify a racial classification,'' the appeals court said. The
fears of people who do not understand Spanish do not amount to a
``business necessity'' warranting the ban, the appeals court said.
   It noted that the federal Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission properly has warned that barring workers from speaking
their native tongue on the job may contribute to racial tension.
   Acknowledging that the California Constitution has been amended
to recognize English as the state's official language, the appeals
court said the amendment is primarily symbolic and does not mandate
that English be the only language spoken by public employees.
   The case is Municipal Court of Los Angeles vs. Gutierrez,
88-1395.
</TEXT>
