<FIRST>r a PM-JailhouseLawyer     04-17 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jailhouse Lawyer,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jailhouse Lawyer Who Transformed Prison Set Free</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jailhouse lawyer whose litigation helped
transform the Idaho State Penitentiary is free after 21 years
behind bars.
   Walter ``Bud'' Balla was released from the prison south of Boise
on Friday. He was not scheduled for release until August, but
Corrections Director Richard Vernon said Balla had found a job and
a place to live, so officials let him go.
   In 1984, Balla, who had only a high school education, and fellow
inmate Dean Schwartzmiller won a federal court victory declaring
the 680-inmate prison overcrowded and lacking in basic services.
   The suit brought about improvements at the prison and
construction of a new maximum-security facility.
   American Civil Liberties Union lawyer Stephen Pevar in Denver
called the court-mandated reforms ``the single most important thing
that has happened'' to Idaho prisons.
   Corrections officials reluctantly agree, although they dismiss
most of Balla's prison-rights suits as frivolous.
   ``Every state has their Balla,'' Vernon said. ``He just happened
to be Idaho's.''
   Balla, 44, was sent to the penitentiary in 1968 for robbery. He
escaped and was recaptured three times and was serving time for
slashing a guard's throat during a breakout in 1978.
   Robert Gray, a Kodiak, Alaska, contractor who knew Balla when
they were teen-agers in Medford, Ore., told officials that the
inmate would have a job and a place to live if he came to Alaska,
and Balla was granted early release.
   Gray said he had forgotten Balla until a few months ago when he
read about an inmate complaining about the prison cable TV system
failing during the Super Bowl.
   ``He's got capabilities,'' Gray said. ``It's too bad he's spent
so much of his life wasting away in prison.''
   Between connecting flights in Seattle, Balla called The Idaho
Statesman to say, ``I'm free and I don't know how to act.''
   ``I've got an opportunity and I'm going to make it work,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
