<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0504 04-17 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fires Burn Out Of Control As Shelling Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs, meeting called by Arab League council. Picks
up 8th graf pvs ``The envoy's wife...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fires burned out of control in Beirut's
devastated streets today after artillery and rocket exchanges
between Christian and Moslem fighters killed 41 people in less than
48 hours.
   Police said 156 people were wounded in the bombardments that
began at dusk Saturday between army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's
largely Christian army units and his Syrian and Druse adversaries.
   Police said the bombardment was the heaviest since the battles
broke out March 8, plunging Lebanon into a fierce round of fighting
some fear may be the ``final battle'' in Lebanon's 14-year-old
civil war.
   Kuwait's foreign minister, Sheik Sabah al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, called
for an emergency meeting of the Arab League council to take
``urgent measures ... to stop the massacre in Lebanon.''
   The sheik, who heads an Arab League mediation committee on
Lebanon, called the meeting after three cease-fire appeals by his
six-man panel failed to curb the hostilities.
   The latest casualties raised the overall toll from 41 days of
almost non-stop bombardment by both sides to 258 killed and 913
wounded, by police count.
   Beirut was without electricity and the water-pumping system came
to a standstill after the capital's main power plants were shut
down at noon Sunday when they ran out of fuel.
   Among those killed during the weekend was Spain's ambassador,
Pedro Manuel de Aristegui. The 61-year-old diplomat died Sunday
along with his wife's Lebanese father and sister and a bodyguard
when his villa suffered a direct hit.
   The envoy's wife, Jomana, suffered severe head wounds when the
240mm shell struck their home in the Hadath suburb of Christian
east Beirut. She was hospitalized in critical condition.
   Beirut residents had hardly emerged from basements and bunkers
during a brief lull this morning when the guns and rocket launchers
thundered into action again, sending people scurrying back to their
shelters.
   A few bakeries opened today, but there was not enough bread for
residents who ventured out to replenish food supplies.
   Hundreds of burned-out cars lay smoldering on streets littered
with broken glass and severed power cables. Hundreds of shops and
other buildings were gutted.
   Fires burned out of control in several residential districts of
Christian east Beirut, where police said more than 1,200 autos were
destroyed by shellfire in the latest blitz. Many buildings burned
down because fire engines had no water to battle the fires.
   The nine-story Information Ministry building, which also houses
the state-run Radio Beirut station, was gutted by a barrage of 30
artillery shells. The station remained off the air for a second day.
   The smoke-blackened building is next door to the office of
acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads a mostly Moslem Cabinet
that is vying for legitimacy with a Christian military Cabinet
headed by Aoun.
   Hoss met today with France's visiting Minister for Humanitarian
Assistance, Bernard Kouchner, who is trying to arrange a mercy
mission to evacuate casualties and bring in fuel and medical
supplies.
   A source close to Hoss, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
a dozen Moslem victims of the fighting might be evacuated from west
Beirut to the French Navy hospital ship, Rance, at nightfall ``if
security conditions permit.''
   Fourteen Christians were ferried to the Rance on Friday.
   The fighting was touched off by a blockade Aoun clamped on
illegal militia-run ports that have cost the government about $100
million a year in lost customs revenue.
   The Druse Progressive Socialist Party retaliated by shelling the
Christian enclave.
   The Syrians, who maintain 40,000 troops in Lebanon's Moslem
areas under a 1976 Arab League mandate, soon joined the Druse in
fighting the Christians.
</TEXT>
