<FIRST>r i PM-Denmark-Fisheries     04-17 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Denmark-Fisheries,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Biologist Takes Over European Fisheries Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK POWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. biologist took over today as
general-secretary of The International Council for the Exploration
of the Sea, becoming the first American to head the world's oldest
intergovernmental organization.
   Emory Anderson of Kenmare, N.D., was elected to head the
18-nation organization for a six-year term. He previously was the
council's fisheries officer and statistician.
   The council was set up in 1902 to carry out marine and fishery
science, and advise European nations on fish stocks, quotas and
marine pollution.
   ``We try to keep out of politics and fisheries management,''
Anderson said. ``But we're sometimes the source of controversy.''
   He said the council's greatest challenge was ``making people
recognize their responsibility for common resources.''
   Prior to the mid-1970s, when countries extended their national
jurisdictions to 200 miles, there was virtual anarchy among fishing
nations, Anderson said. Nothing changed until fish stocks were
decimated, he said.
   Anderson said the North Sea, where cod and haddock are severely
depleted, was the most over-fished ocean in Europe. He said fishing
in North Sea waters should be cut by 80 percent to replenish stocks
to a sufficient level.
   Council members are Belgium, Canada, Denmark, East Germany, West
Germany, Finland, France, Iceland, Ireland, Netherlands, Norway,
Poland, Portugal, Spain, Sweden, Britain, United States and the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
