<FIRST>u w PM-CongressRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0432 04-17 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;Ls, Wright, Base Closings at Top of Congressional Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs grafs 4-6, The House ethics, with two grafs on release
of report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's slightly altered plan to
protect deposits in failed savings and loans will consume the
Senate's attention this week, while Speaker Jim Wright's troubles
and the recommended closing of 86 military bases dominate House
action.
   Bush's plan would cost a minimum of $157 billion, two-thirds of
it from taxpayers, over the next 10 years to shore up the
government's deposit insurance funds after raids on it by
often-fraudulent savings and loan operators.
   The S&amp;L insurance fund is at least $25 billion in the hole
because of overly speculative loans, insider deals and in some
cases outright thievery by thrift operators using federally
protected deposits.
   The House ethics committee charged today that Wright violated
official rules of conduct 69 times by not disclosing thousands of
dollars in alleged gifts and by skirting rules on speaking fees
through bulk book sales.
   The committee also cleared Wright of several allegations,
including one that he improperly intervened with S&amp;L regulators on
behalf of Texas thrift operators and friends.
   The House also is scheduled to vote Tuesday on a resolution by
New Jersey, California and Illinois lawmakers to reject a federal
commission's recommendation last year to close 86 military bases.
   Among the base closings that would begin in 1990 unless the
resolution is approved are the Army's Fort Dix and Presidio bases
in New Jersey and San Francisco and the Air Force's Chanute
training base in Illinois.
   Lawmakers hope to make this a shortened work week, taking off on
Thursday to mark Passover. But with the S&amp;L deficit growing by an
estimated $600 million to $1 billion a month, Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, has vowed to bring them back on
Friday if they do not complete action on Bush's package before the
holiday.
   Lawmakers and presidential candidates in both parties closed
their eyes to the problem during last year's election campaign
while the Federal Home Loan Bank Board was committing some $38
billion to close or merge more than 200 insolvent S&amp;Ls, half of
them in Texas.
   The bailout package before the Senate would come up with the
balance needed to pay for that, $50 billion more needed to handle
another 350 institutions now or near insolvency plus another $33
billion to cover losses of additional thrifts expected to go under
by 1999.
   Together, the costs _ none of which will ever be recovered _ are
more than double the amount of aid, repaid loans and loan
guarantees that the government put up for the Marshall Plan to
rebuild Europe after World War II and the Chrysler, Lockheed, New
York City and Penn Central bailouts combined.
   Toward Bush's stated goal of ``never again,'' the president's
plan also would require S&amp;Ls effectively to double _ from $3 to $6
_ their own capital at risk for every $100 they lend as an
inducement to be more prudent.
   The legislation also replaces the independent and traditionally
industry-friendly Home Loan Bank Board with the stricter
bank-insuring Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and a new Treasury
office as the industry's regulators.
   The Senate Banking Committee last week weakened Bush's reform
proposals somewhat by continuing to allow a variety of non-owner
assets to count as capital through government-approved though
widely criticized accounting practices.
   M. Danny Wall, the bank board's chairman, would keep his job
under Bush's proposal and the Senate committee's bill, but likely
would lose it in a version moving through the House.
   Challenges to Wall's continuance in office and Bush's financing
plan, and an effort to set aside for poor and low-income families
some of the housing that has fallen into the government's hands
through S&amp;L loan defaults, may surface on the Senate floor this
week.
   Under Bush's plan, the bailout will be financed with $50 billion
raised through 30-year bonds to be issued by a new quasi-government
corporation. This lets Bush avoid having to include the costs in
his federal deficit calculations, while taxpayers pick up about $5
billion and the S&amp;L industry $300 million of the annual interest
costs of the bonds.
   An on-budget, up-front financing plan by House Banking Chairman
Don Riegle, D-Mich., was defeated in committee last week despite
Riegle's contention that it would have saved taxpayers $4.5 billion
in interest costs over the next 30 years.
</TEXT>
