<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Smuggler 1st-LdWritethru a0537 04-17 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Smuggler, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0537,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Decide Whether U.S. Officials Need Warrant for Foreign Searches</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf pvs with 5 grafs new material to insert other
actions, picks up 7th graf pvs: Verdugo was xxx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case involving a
notorious Mexican drug-smuggling operation, today agreed to decide
whether U.S. law enforcement agents need a warrant before searching
on foreign soil someone who is not an American citizen.
   The court said it will hear Bush administration arguments that
U.S. agents did not violate the Constitution when, without a
warrant, they searched the home of a suspected Mexican drug
smuggler.
   Rene Verdugo Urquidez was convicted in California last year of
taking part in the 1985 kidnapping, torture and murder of Drug
Enforcement Administration Agent Enrique Camarena and his pilot,
Alfredo Zavala Avelar.
   Verdugo, identified as a top lieutenant to Mexican drug kingpin
Rafael Caro Quintero, is serving a sentence of 240 years plus life.
He is not eligible for parole for 59 years, when he would be 96.
   Verdugo's conviction and sentence in the murders is not at issue
in the case the Supreme Court acted on today. His appeal centered
on a separate drug-smuggling conviction.
   In other cases acted on the court:
   _Agreed to decide whether states may tax television evangelists'
sales of religious books, tapes and other merchandise. The justices
said they will review rulings that forced the Louisiana-based Jimmy
Swaggart Ministries to pay California $183,000 in back taxes and
interest for the years 1974 through 1981.
   -Refused to bar the federal government from requiring certain
peacetime training for any state's National Guard troops without
first getting the governor's consent. The justices left intact a
1986 federal law prohibiting governors from withholding permission
for such training missions. The law had been challenged by
Massachusetts officials.
   -Asked the Bush administration for its view on whether U.S.
banks with branch offices overseas must pay depositors after
foreign governments seize or freeze those accounts. The court
invited Justice Department lawyers to comment on rulings that
required Citibank to pay depositors.
   At issue in the Verdugo case is whether the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals properly suppressed evidence obtained by the DEA
in its search of Verdugo's Mexicali, Mexico, home in 1988.
   Verdugo was arrested by Mexican police in 1986 and was turned
over to U.S. authorities in California.
   While he was awaiting trial, the DEA got permission from Mexican
authorities to search the home. The agents seized a tally sheet
they said shows the quantities of marijuana smuggled into the
United States by Verdugo.
   A federal judge in California ruled that the evidence is
inadmissible because the U.S. agents failed to obtain a warrant in
a U.S. court. The judge also said the search was unreasonable
because it was too general, occurred after midnight and the DEA
failed to leave an inventory in Verdugo's home of the evidence
seized.
   The 9th Circuit court upheld the judge's ruling.
   The appeals court said the agents had a legitimate goal and
praised them for ``aggressive and laudable pursuit'' of drug
smugglers.
   But the appeals court said the agents are not free to ignore the
Constitution's Fourth Amendment, which generally requires a court
warrant before any government search of a home is conducted.
   While Verdugo is a foreign citizen who lived outside the United
States ``he is being prosecuted for alleged violations of United
States law in a United States court,'' the appeals court said. ``We
can discern no conceivable reason why he should be denied the
protection of the Fourth Amendment.''
   The appeals court acknowledged that a search warrant issued by a
judge in this country has no legal authority in Mexico.
Nonetheless, the appeals court said, ``We cannot relieve the
government from its obligation to obtain a search warrant simply
because the place to be searched ... is outside this country.''
   A search warrant issued by a judge in the United States
demonstrates that an impartial magistrate believed there was
probable cause to conduct the search, the appeals court said.
   Justice Department lawyers said the DEA agents received
assurances from Mexican government officials that the search was
lawful there without a warrant.
   The government's appeal said the 9th Circuit court ruling could
have serious consequences for U.S. law enforcement efforts on
foreign soil.
   The DEA has offices in 45 nations, and last year helped in
investigations that led to 1,200 arrests of suspected drug
smugglers in foreign countries.
   The case is U.S. vs. Verdugo-Urquidez, 88-1353.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
