<FIRST>u w BC-Wright-Glance     04-17 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wright-Glance,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Wright, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, is a rundown on the 69
instances of ethics violations which the House Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct alleged Monday against House Speaker
Jim Wright:
   _That Wright's friend and business partner, Fort Worth, Texas,
real estate developer and investor George Mallick, improperly
provided $145,000 worth of gifts over a 10-year period. The
committee found that Mallick had a direct interest in legislation
before the Congress, making it a violation of House rules for
Wright to accept more than $100 in gifts in a calendar year.
   _That Wright failed to report the benefits he received from
Mallick as gifts on his annual financial disclosure forms. The
items deemed ``gifts'' by the ethics committee included free
housing from 1979 through 1984 in Fort Worth, valued at $31,698;
cut-rate housing from 1985 through 1988, valued at $21,790; an
$18,000-a-year salary paid to Wright's wife, Betty, from 1981
through 1984, totaling $72,000; and the use and maintenance of a
1979 Cadillac from 1983 through 1988, valued at $19,391.
   _That Wright had ``an overall scheme'' to evade House limits on
outside earned income by, in seven instances, selling bulk
quantities of his book ``Reflections of a Public Man'' to groups to
which he had delivered speeches. The panel said that action, in
effect, converted money that should have been speaking fees _
limited under House rules _ into book royalties, which are not
under the limits. In an eighth instance, the panel said, Wright
received an undisclosed gift because books paid for by a private
individual were not delivered.
   Of the 116 total allegations of rules violations originally
raised by the committee's outside counsel, Chicago attorney Richard
Phelan, 47 were dismissed. Those involved Wright's alleged lobbying
on behalf of a constituent with whom he had an interest in oil and
gas wells, lobbying of federal savings and loan regulators, using
congressional staff members to produce his book, use of campaign
funds to pay for the book's publication and loan transactions
involving Mrs. Wright and Mallick's wife, Marlene.
</TEXT>
