<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia-President     04-17 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia-President,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>President-Elect Says Democracy Is Inevitable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LJUBLJANA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Janez Drnovsek said
today the spread of democracy in this communist nation cannot be
stopped and suggested the country could join a west European trade
organization within five years.
   Drnovsek, a 38-year-old economist elected in Yugoslavia's first
Western-style election, said a suggestion Yugoslavia join the
European Economic Community was ``not realistic'' now. The call
came from the official Communist youth union last week.
   But he said he could envisage membership in the European Free
Trade Association, whose members are Austria, Finland, Iceland,
Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
   Yugoslavia could adapt its terms of trade to those of the
six-nation grouping over a five-year period, said Drnovsek.
   In a 90-minute meeting with reporters, Drnovsek took a largely
conciliatory but anti-Serbian stance when answering questions about
how to solve ethnic tensions and an economic and political crisis.
   Serbia, under its communist leader Slobodan Milosevic, wants to
maintain a centralized, one-party system, measures it says will
bring down the 400 percent inflation and a $21 billion foreign debt.
   In contrast, Drnovsek stressed that ``the concentration of
economic power ... should not be confused with political
centralization.''
   He also spoke out against ``nationalist tendenices''
complicating the situation in the Serbian province of Kosovo, where
riots killed at least 24 people last month.
   Drnovsek said his direct election as Slovenia's representative
to the nine-member collective presidency shows democratization
``has begun and will not stop.''
   The spread of democracy ``may stop for a short while in one
place or another ... but it cannot be halted altogether,'' he
emphasized.
   ``I am convinced that very soon we will arrive at a more liberal
development in Yugoslavia. Anything else is unacceptable and could
have tragic consequences.''
   Yugoslavia hopes new liberal laws will encourage foreign
investment, but Drnovsek said the country will continue trying to
reschedule or write off debt repayments. He blamed the U.S. budget
deficit for high interest rates that he said complicate repayments.
   Drnovsek and the new representative from Yugoslavia's smallest
republic, Montenegro, were the only people directly elected to the
collective presidency in Western-style elections.
   In Serbia and Croatia, representatives were named by the party
and approved in rubber-stamp legislatures.
   The country's other two republics, Bosnia-Herzegovina and
Macedonia, still are considering how to elect their
representatives, who sit for five years.
   Drnovsek will serve one year as president.
</TEXT>
