<FIRST>r a PM-InmateReturns     04-17 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inmate Returns,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Escaped Convict Returns After 28-Year Absence</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP ) _ An inmate who escaped from prison 28
years ago and lived under his father's name has returned to serve
out his term.
   ``When I die, I want my own name on my tombstone,'' Sylvan
Carter, 61, said in an interview in today's The Columbus Dispatch.
   Carter surrendered at a Cincinnati TV station last week and is
being held at the London Correction Institution pending further
action, Tessa Unwin, a spokeswoman for the Department of
Rehabilitation and Correction, said today.
   Carter, convicted of possession of a burglary tool _ a crowbar _
in 1960, was sentenced to one to five years in prison. He walked
away from an honor farm at the London prison 30 miles west of
Columbus in 1961.
   If convicted of escape, he could receive three years in jail.
   Carter said he has lived in New Orleans and Houston since his
escape and was known as Willie Edward Carter. But after the death
of his brother and his wife, he decided to turn himself in.
   ``What I really wanted to do was wait until the corn around
London got 6 foot high and go into the cornfield and come out at
the prison and tell everyone I got lost (for 28 years). But I
thought better of that idea,'' he said.
</TEXT>
