<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Wrenn     04-17 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Wrenn,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Bars New York Man from Pauper Appeals in Ohio Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For only the second time in its history, the
Supreme Court today permanently barred someone from appealing to it
as a pauper after ruling that he failed to prove he cannot afford
the filing fees.
   The justices, by a 6-3 vote, ruled that Curtis Wrenn of Fort
Drum, N.Y., may never again submit a so-called pauper's petition _
unless he can show his financial circumstances have changed
significantly for the worse.
   Unless granted pauper status, anyone who appeals to the high
court must pay $200 in filing fees plus significant printing costs.
   The court, in a four-page, unsigned opinion, noted that Wrenn
has filed 22 appeals to the court since 1986 and the court has
denied him pauper's status 19 times. One one occasion, Wrenn paid
the $200 fee.
   Wrenn, who is black and works in the Army's Wilcox Medical
Clinic, said he was a victim of racial discrimination by the
Toledo, Ohio, Mental Health Center and the Ohio Mental Health
Department.
   Wrenn said Ohio officials first refused to hire him as an
assistant programs superintendent in 1978. Later, he was hired but
said he then was fired in 1980 because of racial bias.
   In legal papers accompanying his appeal to the Supreme Court,
Wrenn said his yearly salary is $27,700 and he is $60,000 in debt.
   The court once before issued a similar previous opinion, on Feb.
21 denying pauper status to a man who had appealed to the justices
73 times since 1971.
   The justices said today they have a responsibility to allocate
the court's limited resources in the interest of justice for all.
   ``We do not think justice is served if the court continues to
process (Wrenn's) requests to proceed (as a pauper) when his
financial condition has not changed from that reflected in a
previous filing,'' the court said.
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens said the
court was wasting more time by preparing and enforcing the order
resticting Wrenn's ability to appeal than would be ``consumed by
the routine denial of frivolous'' appeals.
   Also dissenting were Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood
Marshall. They repeated past concerns that denying pauper status
could be a dangerous precedent that cuts off worthy appeals.
   The court receives some 2,300 appeals a year by people who say
they are too poor to afford the filing fees.
   The cases are Wrenn vs. Benson, 88-6494, and Wrenn vs.
Department of Mental Health, 88-6497.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     04-17 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Marks Anniversary of Day It Took Control of Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Khmer Rouge commemorated today as
the 14th anniversary of the date it took power in Cambodia, and the
communist guerrilla group also pledged to keep fighting Vietnamese
invaders who later ousted it.
   Fears of a return to power by the Khmer Rouge, which killed
hundreds of thousands of people during its three-year reign, have
heightened since Vietnam announced this month it will pull out its
50,000 troops by Sept. 30.
   ``Today ... our entire people put on their best clothes and
joyously celebrate their national day ... with the firm conviction
that their struggle will score final victory against the Vietnamese
enemy aggressors,'' Khmer Rouge radio said Sunday. The text of its
broadcast was available today in Bangkok.
   Vietnam ousted the Khmer Rouge when it invaded in late 1978 and
installed a new communist government in Phnom Penh.
   That government also marked the anniversary _ but not as a Khmer
Rouge triumph. Instead, Phnom Penh radio called the day a
``historic victory over the U.S. imperialists and their lackeys''
in a broadcast monitored in Bangkok.
   It went on to say that Khmer Rouge leaders betrayed this victory
and ``plunged the Cambodian motherland into a deep ravine of deat.''
   The Khmer Rouge entered the capital, Phnom Penh, on April 17,
1975, toppling the U.S.-backed government of Lon Nol. Today, the
United States and China are key supporters of the Cambodia
resistance, which unites the Khmer Rouge with two non-communist
factions.
   After entering the capital, the Khmer Rouge dragged many
residents to labor camps in the countryside. It eventually killed
hundreds of thousands of Cambodians in its attempt to create a
model agrarian society.
   In its broadcast, the Khmer Rouge station said Vietnam should
bow to guerrilla demands and allow the United Nations to monitor
its withdrawal. The guerrillas have said the Vietnamese-installed
government should step down.
   The station said Hanoi's pledge to remove its troops was merely
an attempt to deflect international criticism. It claimed Vietnam
is hiding thousands of troops in Cambodia by dressing them as
Cambodian soldiers.
   Nguyen Van Linh, chief of Vietnam's ruling Communist Party, will
go to Moscow on Thursday for talks with President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev on Vietnam's pullout from Cambodia, Japan's Kyodo news
service reported today in a dispatch from Hanoi. The Soviet Union
is the main backer of Vietnam.
   In a letter today, about 1,000 survivors of the Khmer Rouge's
labor camps and torture chambers asked leaders of the warring
factions to incorporate human rights provisions into any peace
settlement. They said pledges are needed to ensure the Khmer Rouge
horror is not repeated.
   The letter was sent to Hun Sen, prime minister of the
Vietnamese-backed government in Cambodia; and to the two leaders of
the non-communist guerrilla groups, Prince Norodom Sihanouk and Son
Sann.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
