<DOCNO> AP890417-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Wright-Spouses 1stLd-Writethru a0444 04-17 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-Spouses, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright's Use of Wife in Defense Powerful Argument for Colleagues</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf, A major change, to change attribution to committee
report released today sted of congressional sources; SUBS 14th graf, A
random, to CORRECT that Dingell's wife works for General Motors but is
not a lobbyist.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In using his wife's career as a line of
defense against ethics charges, House Speaker Jim Wright has struck
a sensitive chord among his colleagues who fear they could be
subject to the same scrutiny.
   ``Every member who has a spouse that works'' is concerned, says
House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif.
   A major charge leveled by the 12-member House ethics committee
against Wright is that he accepted improper gifts from a business
partner with interest in legislation, according to the committee's
report released today.
   The panel viewed the $18,000 a year that Wright's wife, Betty,
received from a Fort Worth business partner, George Mallick, not as
a salary for part-time investment advice but as a gift. House rules
prohibit members from accepting more than $100 a year in gifts from
anyone with direct interest in legislation.
   In a counterattack last week, Wright described his wife's
lengthy career, including her job with the House Public Works
Committee, and cited the scores of other congressional spouses who
work.
   ``Some members' wives are attorneys. Some of them sell real
estate. Some of them teach school. Some of them work for local
school boards and local units of government. Some work for the
executive branch of government. Some work for other members of
Congress,'' said the Texas Democrat.
   Wright raised the specter of Congress examining spouses' work,
and the concern among members was evident.
   ``I think that saying any money to a spouse is a gift, as a
woman that offends me. Most spouses I know that work, work,'' said
Rep. Pat Schroeder, D-Colo. ``I do think that spouses' income is
something that we need a very clear guideline. But I am offended
that anybody would make the supposition that any income to a spouse
is a gift.''
   Mary Regula, wife of Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, and president of
the Congressional Club made up of House and Senate spouses,
wondered whether it was possible to set definite rules.
   ``How could you limit the life of another person's career?''
Regula said in a telephone interview from her home in Ohio. ``How
could you even put together a bill without getting into
constitutional rights?''
   The Congressional Club has not conducted an official survey on
whether member spouses work, but Regula estimates about 70 percent
are employed either part-time or full-time.
   Careers cover a wide range of fields and Regula wondered why the
emphasis was on wives rather than husbands.
   ``Pat Schroeder's husband practices law. He has a lucrative
practice. No one has checked his client list,'' Regula said. ``Lynn
Martin is married to a federal judge and Congress votes on their
salaries.''
   A random check of other members found that Stewart Boxer,
husband of Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., is a partner in an Oakland
law firm that has handled a number of workers' compensation cases.
Deborah Dingell, wife of Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., works for
General Motors. Pamela Kostmayer, wife of Rep. Peter Kostmayer,
D-Pa., runs a public relations firm.
   Washington also is filled with high profile, two-career couples.
Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., serves as minority Leader while his wife,
Elizabeth, is the labor secretary. Lynn Cheney is the head of the
National Endowment for the Humanities while her husband, Dick, a
former congressman from Wyoming is defense secretary.
   Back in 1977, Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., the primary author of a
set of rules revisions, said examination of spouse's income is a
responsibility of the IRS, not Congress.
   Wright alluded to that this past week in defending his wife's
career.
   ``A far as I know, it never has been suggested nor contemplated
in the rules that the Congress would seek to question the
appropriateness of a wife's or a spouse's engagement in personal or
private professional business,'' Wright said.
   Betty Wright served as an administrative assistant on the House
Public Works Committee in the early 1970s and was paid $23,884
annually, putting her 26th on the salary list of the 87-member
committee staff.
   She then went to work for Mallick, providing investment advice.
But according to the House ethics committee's outside counsel, Mrs.
Wright only worked a total of 12 days from 1980 to 1984.
   Mallick has said he can find a number of witnesses who will
attest that Mrs. Wright worked for the money she was paid.
   Wright is not the first member of Congress to have his spouse's
career raise questions. Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., came under
close scrutiny when his wife, Antoinette, received $55,000 from
Greek businessman Basil Tsakos.
   Hatfield said the payments were for his wife's real estate
services and had nothing to do with his support of a trans-Africa
oil pipeline promoted by Tsakos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
