<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Two Teen-agers, Arab Sources Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with higher toll of deaths, wounded,
details; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers today shot and killed a
13-year-old girl and a 14-year-old boy in clashes with
stone-throwing Palestinian protesters, Arab hospital officials said.
   The teen-agers both died in violence in the occupied territories
stemming from funerals for victims of earlier clashes. The girl was
killed in the occupied West Bank, the boy in the occupied Gaza
Strip.
   The boy was shot as Palestinians threw stones and set fires
during a funeral for a 50-year-old man from the Gaza Strip who died
earlier in the day of a reported beating March 27 by Israeli
soldiers.
   The army confirmed the death of the man without giving its
cause, and a spokesmen said they were checking the other reports.
   Arab reports also said six Palestinians were wounded during
today's clashes. The victims included a 9-year-old boy shot in the
leg at the Faraa refugee camp in the West Bank, the reports said.
   With today's deaths, 438 Palestinians have been killed in the
16-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories. Eighteen
Israelis also have died.
   Today's killing in the West Bank occurred at the Dheishe refugee
camp outside Bethlehem, where several hundred angry youths, some
carrying outlawed PLO flags, burned tires and stoned Israeli cars
at the end of a burial ceremony. They were mourning a 17-year-old
killed Sunday in a clash with soldiers.
   Israeli soldiers responded by opening fire, shooting 13-year-old
Rafideh Khalili Ahmad Abu Laban in the forehead, Arab reporters
said. They said she died en route to a hospital.
   Hospital officials identified the 14-year-old boy who was killed
as Kayed Mousa Salama. They said he died at Shifa hospital in Gaza
City after a bullet sliced an artery in his leg when soldiers
opened fire in the nearby Jabaliya refugee camp.
   Arab reports said the troops fired on youths who rioted during a
funeral for Faris Said Falha, who died earlier in the day. Arab
sources said he had been beaten by troops during a search in the
camp.
   Protests also occurred today in the Golan Heights, which Israel
annexed after seizing it from Syria during the 1967 war. About 500
Druse Arabs demonstrated in the town of Majdal Shams, shouting
pro-Syrian and pro-PLO slogans and burning tires in honor of Syrian
Independence Day, witnesses said.
</TEXT>
