<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     04-17 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Suspends Rackets Case Against Ailing Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today separated Ferdinand Marcos
from a $100 million racketeering case because of ill health,
leaving his wife to stand trial without him.
   Prosecutors reversed themselves earlier this month and conceded
the 71-year-old deposed Philippine president was too sick to stand
trial for the forseeable future.
   Marcos has been hospitalized since Jan. 15 in Honolulu, where he
has lived in exile since his ouster in 1986. He suffers from heart,
kidney and lung problems.
   Prosecutors withdrew their objection to separating Marcos from
the case April 6 after a government doctor examined him for the
second time.
   U.S. District Judge John F. Keenan signed an order placing the
case against Marcos in limbo. Keenan did not dismiss the charges.
The judge noted that the government could resume its case against
Marcos if his health improved.
   Most people close to the case say a recovery is unlikely.
   No trial date has been set for his wife, Imelda.
   The Marcoses, eight others and the California Overseas Bank are
accused of siphoning more than $100 million from the Philippine
treasury and funneling it into this country for the purchase of New
York real estate and art.
   Mrs. Marcos and the bank are the only defendants that have been
arraigned on the charges. The others, except Marcos, are fugitives.
</TEXT>
