<FIRST>r a PM-LTVFire     04-17 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LTV Fire,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coke Plant Fire Injures Eight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire erupted at an LTV Steel Co. coke plant,
injuring nine people, three seriously, police said today.
   The blaze broke out around 9 a.m. in a building that handles
combustible gas produced in the baking of coal into coke, which is
used in making iron, said LTV spokeswoman Debbie Kuvalich.
   Flames flared above the plant for more that 3{ hours after the
accident. Health officials suggested that people with breathing
problems remain indoors because of the smoke.
   Five people were burned and four had other injuries, said police
spokeswoman Margaret Rizza. They were taken to four hospitals.
   An undetermined amont of oil was discharged into the Monongahela
River, and city and company crews spread booms to try to collect
it, Ms. Rizza said.
   The plant, which employs about 900 workers, was shut down. It is
one of four operated by Cleveland-based LTV and is a major source
of coke for blast furnaces in Cleveland and East Chicago, Ms.
Kuvalish said.
