<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-BombExplosion 3rdLd-Writethru a0559 04-17 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Bomb Explosion, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0559,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Bomb Kills One, Injures Another at Police Headquarters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs with death of one officer. Picks up 3rd graf
pvs ``Brunhilde Spies-Mohr...'' SUBS 6th graf pvs ``The blast occurred...''
to conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radio bomb confiscated from
suspected Palestinian terrorists exploded at federal police
headquarters today as experts tried to defuse it, killing one
officer and critically injuring another.
   A similar bomb disguised as a radio is believed to have caused
the explosion that blew Pan Am Flight 103 out of the sky Dec. 21
over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people.
   The Federal Police Bureau initially reported two officers were
critically injured in today's explosion. Bundeskriminalamt
spokesman Arno Falk said later that one of policemen had died.
   Brunhilde Spies-Mohr, a spokeswoman for the federal police
bureau or Bundeskriminalamt, said in Wiesbaden:
   ``During investigation of a suspicious device suspected of
containing explosives, a detonation occurred.
   ``The material that exploded was a device obtained during
investigation of Palestinian terrorists.'' The explosives were
hidden in a radio receiver, she added.
   The blast occurred in a basement room of the federal police
headquarters, Ms. Spies-Mohr said.
   Part of the Bundeskriminalamt building was evacuated after the
explosion while bomb disposal experts disarmed a second device, she
said.
   An identical radio-bomb containing plastic explosives and an air
pressure-sensitive detonator was seized during an Oct. 26 raid on
an apartment used by suspected Paletinian terrorists in the city of
Neuss.
   It was not immediately clear where the bomb that exploded in the
federal police headquarters came from.
   One unofficial source who did not want to be identified said it
was the same bomb confiscated in the Neuss raid. But that device
has been handled repeatedly by West German and foreign
investigators in their probe of the Pan Am crash, and was presumed
disarmed long ago.
</TEXT>
