<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Poland-Chronology     04-17 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland-Chronology,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Dates in Solidarity History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key events in the history of Solidarity:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1980</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 14 _ Electrician Lech Walesa leads occupation strike at
Gdansk's Lenin Shipyard and starts worker revolt against communist
state.
   Aug. 31 _ Authorities agree to make Solidarity the Soviet bloc's
only legal independent union. During its 16 months of legal
activity, Solidarity membership grows to an estimated 10 million
and a sense of renewal sweeps the nation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1981</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 13 _ With a general strike threatened, Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski declares martial law, suppressing Solidarity activities
and interning thousands of members, including Walesa.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1982</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 8 _ Solidarity is banned and an official trade union
alliance created to take its place. The United States expands
economic sanctions against Poland.
   Nov. 11 _ Walesa freed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1983</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   July 22 _ Jaruzelski lifts martial law but leaves many
restrictive edicts.
   Oct. 5 _ Walesa wins Nobel Peace Prize.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1984</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   July 21 _ Amnesty is approved for political prisoners, including
11 prominent Solidarity leaders jailed after martial law.
   Oct. 19 _ Popular pro-Solidarity priest, the Rev. Jerzy
Popieluszko, is slain. Four state security police will be tried and
convicted.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1985</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 31 _ Walesa accuses government of presiding over a
political, economic and cultural disaster as supporters nationwide
mark fifth anniversary of Solidarity's birth.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1986</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 11 _ The government releases 225 political prisoners,
including all senior Solidarity leaders.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 19 _ Last of U.S. sanctions against Poland lifted.
   Nov. 29 _ Poles vote in first referendum in 41 years, but deny
government support for economic reform package.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   April 24-May 10 _ Strikes hit steel mills, shipyards and other
plants across Poland. Police break up one strike, others gradually
die out.
   Aug. 16 _ Workers declare a strike at July Manifesto coal mine.
Strikes spread, creating Poland's worst labor strife in seven years.
   Aug. 26 _ Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak proposes
negotiations between the communist government and the
Solidarity-led opposition.
   Aug. 31 _ Walesa holds first meeting with government officials
in six years and appeals to workers to end strikes.
   Sept. 3 _ Strikes end as Walesa asks for time to talk with the
government.
   Oct. 25 _ Talks postponed as government objects to opposition
participants.
   Nov. 30 _ Walesa and Alfred Miodowicz, head of the official
union alliance, hold live television debate. Walesa's convincing
performance rekindles plans for talks.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 17 _ Communist Party leadership decides Solidarity can be
legalized under certain conditions, meeting Solidarity's
prerequisite for talks.
   Feb. 6 _ The ``round-table'' negotiations begin with the
government seeking opposition participation in the
communist-dominated political system in exchange for trade union
freedoms.
   April 5 _ Walesa and Kiszczak conclude the historic
deliberations by endorsing a new ``social contract'' for Poland's
future.
   The political and economic reforms include a new senate, which
will be the East bloc's first freely elected legislative body, and
the post of president, the right to have more than one union at a
workplace, opposition access to the printed and electronic media,
and price-wage indexation.
   April 13 _ First elections to include opposition candidates are
set for June 4.
   Monday _ Solidarity is formally registered again as a trade
union operating independently of the Polish government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Poll-Abortion Bjt   04-17 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poll-Abortion, Bjt,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll: Abortion Ban Won't Stop Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though a sizable minority of adults oppose
abortions, Americans overwhelmingly believe that banning them would
do little to curtail them, a Media General-Associated Press survey
has found.
   With the U.S. Supreme Court poised to reconsider the issue next
week, the national poll found support for legal abortion ranging
from 50 percent to 65 percent of the 1,108 adults polled, depending
on the question posed.
   Fifty-three percent, for example, were in favor of the court's
1973 ruling legalizing abortion in the first three months of
pregnancy. And if the court reversed itself and let each state make
its own abortion law, 57 percent would want abortion legal in their
state.
   Moreover, large majorities said outlawing abortion would fail to
prevent it from occurring _ an argument used by those who argue
many women would have unsafe illegal abortions if the operation
were banned.
   The poll asked: ``If abortion were illegal in your state, do you
think that would stop most women there who want abortions from
having them, or would most of them go to another state where it was
legal?'' Eighty-seven percent said the women would go to another
state.
   The survey next asked if making abortions illegal nationwide
would stop most women from having them, or if those women would
have illegal abortions or go to a country where abortion is legal.
Seventy-three percent said most women would find a way to have
abortions.
   The survey nonetheless found its closest split on the question
of a constitutional amendment to make abortions illegal except in
cases of rape, incest or to save the life of the mother: Fifty
percent were opposed and 44 percent in favor, a division within the
poll's margin of error.
   No amendment with those provisions is before Congress, but they
are the terms President Bush has said he would support.
   Because the wording of questions on such a sensitive issue can
affect the results, the poll posed the matter in a variety of ways.
The findings on basic attitudes toward abortion were similar in
other recent surveys.
   One question asked: ``Should abortion be legal as it is now;
legal only in such cases as rape, incest, or to save the life of
the mother; or should it not be permitted at all?'' Fifty percent
said legal as now, 39 percent said legal in some cases, 7 percent
wanted it banned and the rest were unsure.
   CBS News and The New York Times have asked the same poll
question since 1985, tracking a slight increase in support for
current law. Depending on the questions, though, other polls have
found slight declines in support for legal abortion, and others
still have found no change.
   In another question, outside the legal context, the poll asked:
``If a woman wants to have an abortion and her doctor agrees to it,
should she be allowed to have an abortion, or not?'' Sixty-five
percent said yes, 25 percent said no and the remaining 10 percent
had no opinion. The CBS-Times poll has found a similar response to
that same question.
   Opposition to abortion was greatest among older, less wealthy
and less educated respondents, and Republicans and conservatives.
There was no significant division in opinion between men and women.
   The federal Centers for Disease Control say 1.3 million
abortions are performed annually in the United States, making it
one of the nation's most common surgical procedures. Next week, the
Supreme Court is to hear a case that could enable it to review its
1973 ruling legalizing abortion, with a decision expected later in
the year.
   On related issues, the Media General-AP survey found:
   _ Widespread opposition to protests by Operation Rescue, the
anti-abortion group whose members have been blocking entrances to
abortion clinics around the country. Sixty-seven percent opposed
those demonstrations, 22 percent supported them and 11 percent were
unsure.
   _ Narrow opposition to the use of federal funds to help poor
women with their medical bills if they want an abortion. Forty-nine
percent opposed such spending, 41 percent were in favor. The rest
did not answer.
   _ Fifty-one percent support for legalization in the United
States of RU486, a drug developed in France that stops very early
pregnancy by preventing the fertilized egg from being implanted in
the uterine wall.
   Anti-abortion groups call the drug an abortion pill and threaten
boycotts against any drug company that produces it. Supporters call
it simpler and safer than surgical abortion. In the poll, 51
percent said it should be legal here, 24 percent said not and 25
percent were unsure.
   The poll was conducted March 6-15. Media General Inc., a
communications company based in Richmond, Va., publishes the
Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News Leader, the Tampa (Fla.)
Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.) Journal, and operates TV
stations WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in Charleston, S.C., and WJKS in
Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Poll-AbortionMethod     04-17 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poll-Abortion Method,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll on Abortion Reached 1,108 Nationwide</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poll-Abortion Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews March 6 to 15 with 1,108 adults in
the continental United States. Phone numbers were selected randomly
and interviews were conducted with the adult who had the most
recent birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning that if
every adult American were asked the same questions, the results
theoretically would be the within 3 points of the poll's results,
19 times out of 20. The error margin is larger for subgroups.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and
responses in this poll; because of rounding, sums may not total 100:
   1. If a woman wants to have an abortion and her doctor agrees to
it, should she be allowed to have an abortion, or not? Yes: 65
percent. No: 25 percent. Don't know or no answer: 10 percent.
   2. Should abortion be legal as it is now; legal only in such
cases as rape, incest, or to save the life of the mother; or should
it not be permitted at all? As now: 50. In cases: 39. Not at all:
7. DK-NA: 4.
   3. Would you favor or oppose a constitutional amendment that
would make abortions illegal except in cases of rape, incest or to
save the life of the mother? Favor: 44. Oppose: 50. DK-NA: 5.
   4. The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in 1973 that states cannot
prevent a woman from having an abortion if she wants one at any
time during the first three months of pregnancy. Do you favor or
oppose that ruling? Favor: 53. Oppose: 41. DK-NA: 6.
   5. If the Supreme Court reversed its 1973 ruling and let each
state make its own abortion laws, abortion could become legal in
some states and illegal in others. Would you want abortion to be
legal or illegal in your state? Legal: 57. Illegal: 37. DK-NA: 7.
   6. If abortion was illegal in your state, do you think that
would stop most women there who want abortions from having them, or
would most of them go to another state where it was legal? Stop: 7.
Go: 87. DK-NA: 6.
   7. If abortion was illegal in every state, do you think that
would stop most women who want abortions from having them, or would
most of them have illegal abortions or go to another country for
abortions? Stop: 20. Go: 73. DK-NA: 7.
   8. A group that opposes abortion has been holding demonstrations
where its members block the entrances to abortion clinics until the
police arrest them and carry them off. How do you feel about these
demonstrations _ support them strongly, support them, oppose them,
or oppose them strongly? Support strongly: 4. Support: 18. Oppose:
37. Oppose strongly: 30. DK-NA: 11.
   9. A pill is now available in France that stops pregnancy by
preventing the fertilized egg from becoming implanted in the
uterine wall. Do you think this drug should be legal in the United
States, or not? Yes: 51. No: 24. DK-NA: 25.
   10. I'd like to ask your opinion on this statement: The
government should help a poor woman with her medical bills if she
wants an abortion. Please tell me whether you agree or disagree.
Agree: 41. Disagree: 49. DK-NA: 11.
</TEXT>
