<DOCNO> AP890417-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-Scotus-Glance 580   04-17 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scotus-Glance, 580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Actions at a Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, is a rundown of Monday's
major actions by the Supreme Court.
   
   DRUG SEARCH WARRANT
   
   The court, in a case involving a notorious Mexican
drug-smuggling operation, agreed to decide whether U.S. law
enforcement agents need a warrant before searching on foreign soil
someone who is not an American citizen.
   The court said it will hear Bush administration arguments that
U.S. agents did not violate the Constitution when, without a
warrant, they searched the home of a suspected Mexican drug
smuggler.
   Rene Verdugo Urquidez was convicted in California last year of
taking part in the 1985 kidnapping, torture and murder of Drug
Enforcement Administration Agent Enrique Camarena and his pilot,
Alfredo Zavala Avelar.
   Verdugo's conviction and sentence in the murders is not at issue
in the case the Supreme Court acted on Monday. His appeal centered
on a separate drug-smuggling conviction.
   The case is U.S. vs. Verdugo-Urquidez, 88-1353.
   
   NATIONAL GUARD - GOVERNORS
   
   The court refused to bar the federal government from requiring
certain peacetime training for any state's National Guard troops
without first getting the governor's consent.
   The justices, without comment, left intact a 1986 federal law
prohibiting governors from withholding permission for such training
missions.
   The law had been challenged by Massachusetts officials.
   Congress in 1986 passed the so-called Montgomery Amendment after
several governors voiced opposition to the Reagan administration's
Central American policy and said they would withhold their consent
to National Guard training missions in that region.
   The case is Massachusetts vs. Department of Defense, 88-1223.
   
   EVANGELISTS - TAXES
   
   The court agreed to decide whether states may tax television
evangelists' sales of religious books, tapes and other merchandise.
   The justices said they will review rulings that forced the
Louisiana-based Jimmy Swaggart Ministries to pay California
$183,000 in back taxes and interest for the years 1974 through 1981.
   Lawyers for Swaggart's organization argue that the California
tax, as applied, violates religious freedom.
   The case is Jimmy Swaggart Ministries vs. Board of Equalization,
88-1374.
   
   MURDER CONFESSION
   
   The court agreed to consider reinstating the murder conviction
of a New York City man who confessed to killing his former
girlfriend after police illegally arrested him at his home.
   The court said it will review a ruling that threw out Bernard
Harris' conviction because his confession was used as evidence
against him.
   The ruling is being appealed by Bronx prosecutors.
   The New York State Court of Appeals last October ruled that
Harris is entitled to a new trial on charges stemming from the
stabbing death of Thelma Staton.
   The case is New York vs. Harris, 88-1000.
   
   PAUPER APPEAL
   
   For only the second time in its history, the Supreme Court
permanently barred someone from appealing to it as a pauper after
ruling that he failed to prove he cannot afford the filing fees.
   The justices, by a 6-3 vote, ruled that Curtis Wrenn of Fort
Drum, N.Y., may never again submit a so-called pauper's petition _
unless he can show his financial circumstances have changed
significantly for the worse.
   Unless granted pauper status, anyone who appeals to the high
court must pay $200 in filing fees plus significant printing costs.
   The court, in a four-page, unsigned opinion, noted that Wrenn
has filed 22 appeals to the court since 1986 and the court has
denied him pauper's status 19 times. One one occasion, Wrenn paid
the $200 fee.
   The cases are Wrenn vs. Benson, 88-6494, and Wrenn vs.
Department of Mental Health, 88-6497.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-StadiumDisaster 5thLd-Writethru a0543 04-17 0884</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stadium Disaster, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0543,0909</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gatekeeper Says Police Overruled Him, Allowed Fans Into Stadium</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New grafs 12-23, beginning, ``Paul Middup...'' to UPDATE with
police defense, Hurd announcing inquiry, CORRECT one victim's age, royals
visiting, editing to tighten. Pickup 23rd graf pvs, ``South Yorkshire...''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   '
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By ROBERT BARR</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SHEFFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gatekeeper said today he refused
police orders to open an outer gate and allow thousands of late
arrivals to pour into a soccer stadium where 94 fans were crushed
to death. Fans and officials said police opened the barrier.
   South Yorkshire police, who were in charge of Saturday's club
semifinal at Hillsborough stadium, came under mounting attack as
Liverpool ordered a week of mourning for victims who came to watch
the city's team play play Nottingham Forest.
   Fans and officials said officers responded inadequately and far
too slowly when spectators were crushed against a steel anti-riot
fence in a standing-room-only area.
   Gatekeeper Jack Stone told the Yorkshire Post he refused police
orders to open a 16-foot-wide outer gate. Survivors said about
4,000 fans outside were pushing at turnstiles.
   Stone would not confirm survivors' reports that police officers
opened the concertina gate. But he told the newspaper: ``You know
as well as anyone whose fault it was.''
   Liverpool fan Stephen Mitton told British Broadcasting Corp.
television: ``The steward put his hand on the gate and said, `Don't
open it.' The police said, `Open the gate. There's going to be a
crush.' Then two police officers opened the gate.''
   New arrivals poured in, pressing those inside against the
10-foot fence. Mounted police herded them into the overcrowded
center terrace, some fans said today.
   The crush was so great, Mitton said, that fans fell on the floor
and people climbed over them. ``All the police were doing was
standing up saying `get back, get back.' There was already people
dead then. I climbed on them to get over the fence.''
   South Yorkshire's Chief Constable Peter Wright said Saturday a
senior officer decided to open the gates ``to save people's lives
and to relieve the crush outside.''
   He said he was not aware of any connection between the gate
being opened and the surge on the standing section, where many
victims died.
   One of those being trapped in the front of the terrace, Stephen
Hendry, 19, said: ``People were screaming at the police to open the
gate (at the front of the terrace) and three fans managed to climb
over the fence, but no sooner had they got out than one of them was
thrown back over by a copper.''
   Paul Middup, a Police Federation representative, said today the
growing public criticism of police actions was ``grossly unfair.''
   ``They were faced with a situation for which no amount of
training could prepare them,'' he said.
   In Parliament today, Home Secretary Douglas Hurd announced an
independent inquiry to determine the cause of what Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher called ``a disaster of immense proportions.''
   Hurd said major soccer clubs may be told to replace
standing-room terraces with seats _ as lawmakers and sports
officials are demanding.
   ``We owe a duty to these passionate supporters of football
(soccer) to examine urgently and thoroughly the causes and
background and to do all in our power to prevent such a thing
happening again,'' Hurd said. ``We have to set our sights high and
find a better way for British football.''
   Lord Justice Taylor will lead the inquiry starting Tuesday, he
said.
   Police released the names of all 94 victims today, ranging from
a 10-year-old boy who was trampled and the 67-year-old brother of a
former Liverpool soccer player to two sisters who died before their
father's eyes.
   Businessman Trevor Hicks, 43, tried to resuscitate his two
daughters, Sarah, 19, and Victoria, 15, after they were pulled from
the crush of bodies.
   ``Football was the one thing we did as a family and now we are
not a family anymore,'' he said.
   All the victims were British. Thirty-four were teen-agers and 33
were in their 20s. Seven were women.
   Of the 170 injured, 47 remained hospitalized today, including 17
in intensive care.
   Liverpool soccer team members visited some of the injured fans,
as did Prince Charles and his wife, Princess Diana.
   South Yorkshire police, whose crowd-control measures will be at
the core of the inquiry, handed over the police investigation to
neighboring West Midlands police.
   Authorities will want to determine why thousands of fans still
were outside as the match began and examine charges that many
entered the sold-out stadium, which has a capacity of 54,000, with
forged tickets or no tickets at all.
   Sir Harry Livermore, a Liverpool lawyer and former Lord Mayor of
Liverpool, released a statement from a policeman whom he refused to
identify calling the police operation disorganized, ``pathetic''
and ``amateurish.''
   The Liverpool city council today called an official week of
mourning and discussed ways of helping the bereaved and injured.
   It was the third major soccer tragedy in four years involving
English teams, which have been barred from European soccer
competition since a May 29, 1985, rampage by Liverpool fans at
Heysel stadium in Brussels that killed 39 people.
   Europe's soccer authority last week lifted the ban on English
clubs playing in Europe in the 1990-91 season, pending a review
next April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
