<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-IRA Bjt   04-17 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-IRA, Bjt,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty Report Revives Questions About Gibraltar Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 8:01 p.m. EDT _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The inquest jury that exonerated British soldiers
in the killing of three alleged Irish terrorists in Gibraltar was
acting on incomplete evidence and sometimes conflicting testimony,
Amnesty International says.
   In a report published Tuesday that is likely to refuel the
controversy over the killings on March 6, 1988, the human rights
movement renewed its demand for a judicial inquiry, saying the
inquest failed to allay suspicions of ``an official policy of
deliberate planned killings of suspected members of armed
opposition groups.''
   It said the inquest was conducted properly, but believed that
the verdict, although reached fairly, was based on ``evidence which
from the outset was incomplete.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's office said it had seen the
report. ``As far as we are concerned the whole matter has been
fully considered (by the inquest) and we see no grounds for opening
up a fresh inquiry,'' said a spokesman, requesting anonymity.
   The government has faced persistent questions over the killing
of Mairead Farrell, Daniel McCann and Sean Savage by a
secrecy-shrouded military unit believed to have been flown in from
Britain.
   The government said it acted on intelligence the three were
armed and plotting to detonate a car bomb in the tourist-packed
center of the British colony on the southern Spanish coast. The
Irish Republican Army acknowledged the three were members sent to
Gibraltar ``on active service.''
   But it quickly emerged the three were unarmed and that their car
contained no bomb, and witnesses later said at least two of the
suspects appeared to be trying to surrender to the plainclothes
officers confronting them.
   The government said it feared they might have remote-control
devices to detonate the explosives if they were given too much time
to surrender.
   Angrily rejecting Amnesty International's call for an inquiry,
Mrs. Thatcher said an inquest would answer the questions. Seven
months later, the inquest jury ruled 9-2 that the killings were
lawful.
   Amnesty International sent three observers to the inquest, led
by Stephen Owen, a lawyer and ombudsman of the Canadian province of
British Columbia.
   Its report comes two weeks after a British trial lawyer, Hilary
Kitchin, who also observed the inquest, wrote that it fell short of
international legal standards and raised questions about the
legality of the killings.
   Amnesty International's report said: ``Details about government
policy, the planning of the operation, and the quality of the
intelligence were not revealed.''
   It said Spanish police, who had been involved in tracking the
three to the Gibraltar border, did not testify.
   Spanish testimony could have helped establish whether they were
known to be without guns or explosives. The absence of this
testimony also made the evidence incomplete, the report said.
   It said much forensic evidence was destroyed ``because standard
procedures were not followed,'' while the state pathologist was
denied adequate post-mortem facilities and ballistics reports.
   ``Most of the key independent civilian eye witnesses were
discovered by media journalists and not by the police,'' said
Amnesty International.
   ``The organization is also concerned that discrepancies between
witnesses' testimonies had not been resolved and that many
questions remained unanswered such as, for example, from what exact
position the soldiers had fired, and whether the suspects had made
attempts to surrender,'' the report said.
   Recalling past shootings in Northern Ireland in which police
were accused of killing when they could have made arrests, it said:
``The inquest has again failed to alleviate public concern that
these suspects were killed rather than arrested.''
   In an interview, Owen said Britain faced the challenge of
``keeping its composure in the face of sometimes intolerable
violence.''
   He said he was not accusing the British of stepping beyond the
law. ``I'm saying doubt remains that has to be resolved ... and
doubt is potentially very damaging to a representative democracy.''
   The IRA is fighting to rid Northern Ireland of British rule and
unite it with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
