<FIRST>r a AM-People-Wiesenthal     04-17 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Wiesenthal,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nazi Hunter Gives Nod to Biographical Script, Casting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nazi hunter Simon Wiesenthal, who for years
rejected Hollywood offers to do his story, says he signed with Home
Box Office because his contract allowed him to consult on the
script, draft by draft.
   Wiesenthal also said, in an interview for the April 22 TV Guide
magazine, that he was pleased by HBO's choice of Ben Kingsley to
play him in the movie to be broadcast Sunday, called ``Murderers
Among Us: The Simon Wiesenthal Story.''
   The movie is based on Wiesenthal's 1967 book of the same title.
Wiesenthal, credited with finding more than 1,100 war criminals,
said producers were after him for years for the movie rights, but
offered deals that would have left him helpless if he felt the
script diverged from the truth.
   In 1984, executive producer Robert Cooper offered a contract
that gave Wiesenthal no veto power, but required that he be
consulted by the writers on each draft as they worked toward the
final script.
   ``Now I am confident that the spirit of my story will be
properly represented,'' Wiesenthal said.
   Kingsley, who won a best-actor Oscar for the title role in
``Ghandi,'' told the magazine he read three of Wiesenthal's books
before meeting him in Vienna, Austria.
   ``We clicked immediately,'' the British actor said, and
Wiesenthal had both of them crying within 10 minutes.
   ``He told me a story about liberation day on the 5th of May
(1945) and how some of his fellow Jews were dying as the GIs came
in,'' Kingsley said.
</TEXT>
