<DOCNO> AP890417-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PolishPackage     04-17 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polish Package,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highlights of President's Initiative of Incentives</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMTRAMCK, Mich (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the major features of the
package President Bush unveiled Monday to reward Poland for its
recent steps toward democracy and to encourage further political
and economic reforms.
   _Trade concessions.
   The administration will submit to Congress legislation to lower
U.S. tariffs on a variety of Polish goods. This would be
accomplished by putting Poland under the Generalized System of
Preferences, which gives this form of trade relief to selected
countries with low per-capita incomes.
   The administration estimates the value to Poland at $3.5 million
to $25 million annually, depending on what products benefit from
tariff reductions and how aggressively Poland reacts to the lowered
tariffs.
   _Old loans.
   Bush called for other wealthy western nations to join the United
States in giving Poland easier terms for paying back its $38
billion foreign debt, only $2.4 billion of which is owed to the
United States. But the debt stretch-out would be conditioned on
economic reforms by the Warsaw government.
   Administration sources said the step could lead to the
rescheduling of up to $700 million in existing debt.
   _New loans.
   The administration said it would support conditional new loans
to Poland from the International Monetary Fund, but suggested they
should be tied to movement toward ``market-oriented economic
policies.'' The White House did not put a dollar value on the IMF
loans.
   Some official sources have suggested the IMF loans could total
$300 million if Poland meets all the requirements, followed perhaps
by $250 million more from the World Bank.
   _Business investment.
   The package provides a variety of incentives to encourage more
U.S. business investment in Poland, along with joint ventures with
Polish businesses. These overtures would be made conditional on
Poland's progress in carrying out the political and labor reforms
it has promised, including recognizing Solidarity and holding free
and open parlimentary elections.
   _Debt-equity swaps.
   The government proposed that Poland be permitted to reduce some
of its international debt by giving U.S. banks or other investors
shares in Polish enterprises in exchange.
</TEXT>
