<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MinimumWage     04-17 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Raises Rhetoric In Minimum Wage Battle; Asks Labor To Confront
Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell on
Monday told a union conference ``the president is against us'' in
efforts to raise the minimum wage and urged the delegates to
confront President Bush when he speaks to them Tuesday.
   ``Maybe you can ask him this question,'' Mitchell told about
3,000 delegates of the AFL-CIO Building and Construction Trades
national conference. ``How is it that the president can propose a
tax cut of $30,000 a year for the very richest Americans and yet at
the same time say that 30 cents an hour for the poorest Americans
is too much? I say that is wrong and that is unfair.''
   Mitchell, D-Maine, was referring to Bush's proposal to cut
capital gains taxes and the 30 cents an hour difference between
Bush's offer to raise the hourly minimum wage to $4.25 by 1992 and
the $4.55 target contained in legislation passed by both the House
and Senate.
   The White House and congressional proposals also differ on
whether employers should be able to pay newly hired workers a
subminimum wage. Bush has said he will not sign any increase unless
there is a six-month ``training wage'' covering all new employees,
while both the House and Senate bills include a two-month training
period with significant eligibility restrictions.
   A conference committee is resolving differences between the
House and Senate bills before the measure can be given final
passage and be sent to Bush, who has promised to veto it.
   The president appears to have enough votes to sustain a veto,
but Democrats have decided on a vigorous campaign in favor of the
bill in hopes of gaining a political edge should Bush hold fast to
his veto threats.
   ``We're going to fight,'' Mitchell said. ``The president is
against us.''
   Mitchell delivered a lengthy defense of the Democratic Party and
questioned Bush's campaign call for a ``kinder, gentler'' nation.
   ``We've made mistakes,'' Mitchell said of the Democrats. ``We've
gone too far in some cases. But if this is a kind and gentle nation
it is Democrats who made it so, and if it is to become kinder and
gentler it is Democrats who will make it so.''
   Mitchell also said that ``with or without'' Bush the Democrats
planned to move forward with their domestic agenda, including
programs for the homeless, environment, health care and
infrastructure.
   ``We've got a public agenda that won't wait and we're not going
to wait,'' Mitchell said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
