<FIRST>r w AM-TaxOverpayments     04-17 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Overpayments,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bentsen Wants IRS to Notify Taxpayers Who Overpaid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, introduced legislation Monday that would require
the Internal Revenue Service to notify taxpayers when they overpay
their taxes.
   ``The IRS should be honest with taxpayers _ not try to hide from
them that they have paid more than they rightfully owe,'' Bentsen,
a Texas Democrat, said in a Senate speech. ``We expect taxpayers to
pay their fair share, but not an extra share.''
   The bill grew out of a disclosure last month that the IRS
instructed employees matching tax returns with income forms, such
as the W-2 for wages and the 1099 for interest and pension
payments, to keep quiet when such examination disclosed
overpayment. The overpayment usually resulted when a taxpayer
failed to subtract taxes withheld from taxes owed.
   After an IRS employee in Memphis complained to Sen. Albert Gore
Jr., D-Tenn., IRS Acting Commissioner Michael J. Murphy ordered the
policy discontinued.
   Bentsen's bill would write that change into law.
</TEXT>
