<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Wright-Defense     04-17 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright-Defense,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright's Lawyer Calls Charges ``Outrageous ... Doublespeak''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Wright's attorney predicted Monday the
House ethics committee will find no rules violations when it
considers whether ``clear and convincing'' evidence exists of
improper conduct by the speaker.
   Lawyer William C. Oldaker, rebutting all the charges in the
committee's statement of alleged violations, said they were based
on ``a mischaracterization of facts...outrageous readings of
legislative history ... retroactive writing of the rules
...doublespeak.''
   Oldaker commented after committee chairman Julian C. Dixon,
D-Calif., announced the panel was charging the Texas Democrat with
69 violations of House rules.
   In a lengthy statement, the panel found ``reason to believe''
Wright had broken rules requiring reporting of gifts, barring
acceptance of gifts from persons with a direct interest in
legislation and limiting outside earned income.
   Both Oldaker and Dixon emphasized the committee's allegations
were based only on a ``reason to believe'' that rules were
violated. In order for the panel to declare actual violations took
place and to recommend punishment by the full House, it must find
``clear and convincing evidence,''
   ``I am confident they will find no rules violations clearly and
convincingly proved,'' said Oldaker, who particularly criticized
the committee's special outside counsel, Richard J. Phelan of
Chicago, for its report Monday.
   The Committee on Standards of Official Conduct, the panel's
formal name, charged that Wright's friend and business partner,
Fort Worth, Texas, real estate developer and investor George
Mallick, improperly provided $145,000 worth of gifts over a 10-year
period.
   The committee found that Mallick had a direct interest in
legislation before Congress, making it a violation of House rules
for Wright to accept more than $100 in gifts in a calendar year.
   Oldaker called the allegation that Mallick had a direct interest
in legislation ``one of the most outrageous readings of legislative
history.''
   He called Mallick ``a close personal friend'' of Wright who had
``interest in oil and an interest in real estate. That covers
everyone in the country.''
   The attorney said Mallick ``never asked the speaker to do
anything for himself or anyone else.''
   The committee charged Wright with failing to report the benefits
he received from Mallick as gifts on his annual financial
disclosure forms.
   The items deemed ``gifts'' by the ethics committee included free
housing from 1979 through 1984 in Fort Worth, valued at $31,698;
cut-rate housing from 1985 through 1988, valued at $21,790; an
$18,000-a-year salary paid to Wright's wife, Betty, from 1981
through 1984, totaling $72,000, and the use and maintenance of a
1979 Cadillac from 1983 through 1988, valued at $19,391.
   According to Oldaker, it was Mallick's practice ``to have
employees live for free'' in the same Fort Worth condominium
complex he let the Wright's use.
   Oldaker said Phelan wrongly implied that Wright's wife, Betty,
was incompetent when she worked for the investment company founded
by Wright, Mallick and their wives.
   Wright's lawyer said former colleagues of Mrs. Wright told the
committee she worked five to seven days a month, when she ``went
out and looked at various investments and talked to people.'' He
said Mrs. Wright was not successful in the ventures and left no
written record of her work.
   The car was owned by the Wright-Mallick firm, and ``the speaker
never believed the car was a gift,'' Oldaker said.
   Wright was accused by the committee of having ``an overall
scheme'' to evade House limits on outside earned income by, in
seven instances, selling bulk quantities of his book ``Reflections
of a Public Man'' to groups to which he had delivered speeches.
   The panel said that action, in effect, converted money that
should have been speaking fees _ limited under House rules _ into
book royalties, which are not under the limits. In an eighth
instance, the panel said, Wright received an undisclosed gift
because books paid for by a private individual were not delivered.
   Oldaker said the committee found problems with only seven
speeches during a three-year period when Wright gave 750 talks.
   On the disclosure question, Oldaker said, ``Public disclosure
was made, which is the essence of everything. Betty Wright's salary
was disclosed. The book royalties were disclosed. There was a lot
of noise, a lot of clamoring, but very little substance.''
</TEXT>
