<FIRST>r a AM-ILoveNY     04-17 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-I Love NY,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>State to Charge for Use of `I Love New York' Logo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of loving is going up.
   New York, after years of allowing manufacturers free use of the
``I Love New York'' logo, will start charging royalties this year.
   People who print the logo on sweatshirts, key chains, pens or
other consumer goods will be forced to give New York state 6
percent to 10 percent of the money they make, said Stephen Morello,
a state deputy commissioner for economic development.
   The state has spent more than $100 million advertising itself to
tourists since launching the ``I Love New York'' advertising
campaign in 1977, he said.
   The state registered the motto with a red heart symbol in place
of the word ``love.'' Though the symbol has been adapted for a
variety of bumper stickers and other uses, the state only holds the
trademark for loving New York.
   ``We think this is one modest way to begin recapturing some of
the investment without negatively impacting the motto's
effectiveness,'' Morello said.
   State officials have watched with great interest the success of
the California raisins advertising campaign, which has branched off
into lucrative records, touring cartoon characters and other
products, he said.
   A licensing agent will be hired to help market the logo, which
tourism officials refer to in news releases as ``legendary.''
   Up until now, the state has allowed manufacturers to include ``I
Love New York'' in anything deemed appropriate, figuring it's
helping the state advertise itself, he said.
   Manufacturers who already use the logo will be allowed a certain
period of time to sell off their inventory before they have to
start paying, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
