<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Reax     04-17 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Reax,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poles React to Solidarity Registration with Delight, Doubt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poles reacted with delight Monday to news
that Solidarity was legal again, but some seemed doubtful that even
the legalization of the independent union can solve the country's
economic woes.
   Many Poles had not heard by afternoon that the Warsaw Regional
Court had approved registration of the union that had energized the
nation before being banned in the wake of the December 1981
martial-law crackdown.
   ``I didn't know. It's great. It should have happened a long time
ago,'' said Gregorz Maracewicz, a Solidarity supporter who works in
the science office of the Roza Luksemburg light-bulb factory.
   ``We will have to see what they (Solidarity) will do, but it
will make a great difference for all of us,'' he said before
heading home in a driving spring snowstorm after his shift.
   ``It's a good thing. It should change things, but it's hard to
say whether Solidarity can do it all by itself,'' said a factory
employee and former Solidarity member who declined to give her name.
   At the Institute for Professional Training, near where the
Warsaw branch of Solidarity had its offices during its first 16
months of legality, employees welcomed the decision.
   ``I am very happy. I really think it's a historic moment. I
think registration was the first condition of all the changes which
are going to improve things when there is more democracy,'' said
sociologist Krystyna Lewinska.
   ``I don't give interviews,'' said another institute employee who
walked away and smiled. He then turned his head and added, ``But I
am very happy.''
   Most of those interviewed who were members of the union during
its legal phase in 1980-81 said they would join again.
   ``That's obvious,'' said Alina Jablonska, an employee in a
design office now on maternity leave, when asked if she would
become a member again.
   ``We are full of hope. The whole society, at least my community,
believes our life problems should disappear, perhaps not so soon,
but in the long term,'' she said.
   An elderly woman, who like Jablonska was standing in line for
meat at the Hala Mirowska market, disagreed.
   ``It doesn't matter who rules. What matters is that things
should be good in this country so that I shouldn't have to stand in
line for a piece of meat,'' said the woman, a retired factory
worker who was a member of Solidarity in 1980-81.
   ``I don't think anything will change,'' she added, declining to
give her name.
   Authorities and the opposition hope the legalization of
Solidarity will provide social calm needed for economic reforms to
take effect.
   Chronic consumer shortages and the failure of wages to keep pace
with inflation sparked two crippling waves of strikes in May and
August 1988. Service on Poland's $38 billion debt eats up hard
currency needed for investments to modernize industry.
   In light of such problems, some Poles want to wait and see what
the union can do before joining. The union once boasted 10 million
members out of the 18 million-member workforce, but Walesa has said
he expects 5 million to 7 million in the new Solidarity.
   Others demonstrated their commitment to Solidarity even before
the decision to register the union was officially announced.
   ``We organized when Solidarity was illegal, underground, so we
are not used to this new situation. We represent committees already
organized in our region. The big difference will be our freedom of
action,'' said Roman Jarosz.
   The 26-year-old construction worker and three of his friends
took the overnight train from their home in Gorzow Wielkopolski in
western Poland so they could hold up a Solidarity banner in the
courtroom where the decision was read.
</TEXT>
