<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NSA-ComputerChips     04-17 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NSA-Computer Chips,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spy Agency to Build Computer Chip Plant to Make Sure of Secure Supply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Security Agency's decision to
build its own top secret computer-chip plant was spurred by the
threat of sensitive technology falling ``into the wrong hands,''
according to American electronics specialists.
   The NSA, the nation's biggest intelligence agency, says the $85
million microelectronics plant being built at Fort Meade, Md.,
represents a ``unique capability within the U.S. government.''
   The move comes amid increasing concern about erosion of American
chip-making expertise and manufacturing capacity in the face of
stiff competition from Japan, South Korea and other countries.
   The National Security Agency's main missions are eavesdropping
on communications around the globe, encoding U.S. communications
and cracking foreign codes, as well as safeguarding the security of
U.S. military computers and communications systems.
   To carry out those missions, the Defense Department agency makes
heavy use of sophisticated, powerful computers. Author James
Bamford, an authority on the agency has reported that computers
cover more than 5{ acres at its headquarters complex at Fort Meade.
   According to Bamford, the NSA has a work force topping 60,000
employees _ more than all other U.S. spy agencies combined _ and a
budget estimated at more than $10 billion a year.
   The NSA's public affairs office said that in September 1988 the
agency signed an $85 million contract with National Semiconductor
Corp. of Santa Clara, Calif., ``to instrument and train the
government to operate a state-of-the-art microelectronics
fabrication facility.''
   Construction of 60,000 square feet of building space to house
the chip-making plant was started in January 1986 by the U.S. Army
Corps of Engineers and completed in October 1988, it said.
   ``Now National Semiconductor is outfitting the six-inch silicon
wafer fabrication line,'' the NSA statement said. ``Operations are
scheduled to begin in 1991, and National Semiconductor will train
NSA personnel in the operation of the new facility over a period of
18 months.''
   The agency said that ``building such a facility at Fort Meade
will enable NSA to have direct control over the production process
and the security procedures necessary for safeguarding the plant.
This facility represents a unique capability within the U.S.
government.''
   Paul Hazan, a computer scientist at the Johns Hopkins University
Applied Physics Laboratory in Laurel, Md., said the NSA plant was
aimed at dealing with the threat of ``reverse engineering'' _
efforts to figure out the functioning of a computer system by
scrutinizing its key components.
   ``That is why they don't want to have a process made elsewhere.
... You have coding and so on, and if that falls into the wrong
hands, the other side could find out what your code is. That's why
they want to keep control of it in-house,'' he said.
   Hazan, chairman of the Defense Research and Development
Committee of the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers,
a 300,000-member professional association, said that ``we are
losing the commercial semiconductor competition.''
   ``Since that, in turn, is what is driving the technology, we
rapidly find ourselves where in defense, if you want to build
defense systems, you won't have the capability here. You have to go
overseas and hope that Japan or Korea or somebody else is willing
to apply the resources to that, as opposed to something else,'' he
said.
   Hazan added that ``if you do that, then it's a (commercial)
market _ presumably they'll sell it to anybody who has the need. So
it's potentially a very tricky situation.''
   Larry Sumney, president of Semiconductor Research Corp., an
electronics company in Research Triangle Park, N.C., said that in
1982, while he was on the Pentagon staff, he chaired a Defense
Science Board task force on development of very high-speed
integrated circuits.
   The task force recommended to the science board that the
government ``give some consideration to putting together a facility
to provide state-of-the-art integrated circuits for classified
applications,'' he said.
   Sumney noted that another Defense Science Board task force study
in 1987 also ``called attention to the fact that the government
couldn't put itself in a position of being dependent on foreign
sources.''
   Asked about the NSA's decision to build its own chip plant,
Sumney said, ``I would think that now it's even more supportable,
because we've continued to erode in our ability to be competitive
in world markets for integrated circuits.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0126 </DOCNO>
