<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Slaying     04-17 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Slaying,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Filed in June Slaying of Solidarity Sociologist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were charged Monday in the June
robbery and slaying of a sociologist who served as an adviser to
the Solidarity trade union, according to the state-run news agency.
   Marek Tomasz Marzec, 19, was charged with murder, and Krzysztof
Chrobocinski, 25, was charged with robbery and assault, the PAP
news agency said. No trial date was set.
   Jan Strzelecki, 69, died nearly three weeks after he was found
lying unconscious near the Vistula River in Warsaw. He had been
dragged from his car, robbed and thrown down an embankment, police
said at the time.
   Strzelecki was not a prominent member of Solidarity, but he was
an active supporter of the union. He was an associate professor at
the Polish Academy of Sciences.
</TEXT>
