<DOCNO> AP890417-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Madagascar     04-17 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Madagascar,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot Follows Meeting of Opposition Parties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rioters burned cars and smashed
shop windows after opposition leaders met to discuss alleged
government fraud in the March presidential elections, state-run
radio said.
   Police used tear gas to break up the disturbances Sunday in
which 13 people were injured and 20 arrested, the radio said. It
did not say how many people participated or where the riots began.
   Leaders of the three opposition parties met to challenge the
March 12 vote in which Presdient Didier Ratsiraka was elected to a
third term. He won the election with 62 percent of the vote and is
to be sworn in Thursday.
   The opposition said the voting was rigged and challenged the
outcome in a petition to the island nation's Supreme Court.
Opposition leaders asked that the election be overturned and a
provisional government be set up pending new voting.
   Ratsirka, 52, who was chosen president by the ruling military in
1975, won his first term with more than 98 percent of the vote. In
1982, he received 80 percent of the vote against a single opponent.
   In this year's election, the central issue was the economic
decline of the island off southeastern Africa.
   When he took office, Ratsirka broke many ties with France, the
former ruling colonial power, and with other Western nations. He
nationalized foreign-owned industries and set the nation on a
socialist course. But natural disasters ranging from cyclones to
droughts beset the island and with the economy near bankruptcy in
1982, Ratsirka began restoring economic ties with the West.
</TEXT>
