<FIRST>r w AM-BRF-WinemakersAlcoholism     04-17 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-Winemakers Alcoholism,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winemakers Against Alcoholism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winemakers from California announced on Monday
the formation of a ``National Wine Coalition'' to make clear their
opposition to alcoholism.
   ``With the plethora of warning labels, signs and unsubtantiated
claims by an assortment of reform-minded organizations, the
consumer has a right to know the values and pleasures of wine when
used intelligently and in moderation,'' said John De Luca,
president of the Wine Institute, a trade association.
   Allied industries, such as restaurants and hotels are invited to
join the new organization, as well as groups opposed to the abuse
of alcohol.
   He was asked if it would cooperate with other countries that
produce wine.
   ``We don't intend to be negative about anyone,'' he replied. He
made it clear that would include manufacturers of spirits.
   A statement issued by the group said the new coalition would
promote programs linking wine with food and encouraging its use on
social occasions, would inform the media on positive aspects of
wine and set up a network of consumers ``who embrace the principles
of moderate consumoption.''
   It may also do some lobbying in Washington, the statement added.
</TEXT>
