<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Moslems     04-17 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Moslems,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egyptian Official Says About 1,000 Extremists Detained in Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's top law enforcer said in
remarks distributed Monday that about 1,000 Moslem extremists were
detained this month in a nationwide sweep prompted by a riot
outside a provincial mosque.
   Security sources said earlier that only about 100 people were
rounded up.
   Interior Minister Zaki Badr, whose ministry oversees domestic
order, gave the new figure Sunday night during a speech at Cairo's
National Sporting Club. The state-run Middle East News Agency
distributed a summary of his remarks on Monday.
   The fundamentalist rioting, which left four people wounded,
broke out April 7 in the southern city of Fayoum immediately after
Friday prayers at a mosque. The government has accused, Sheik Omar
Abdel-Rahman, a charismatic blind preacher, of inciting his
followers to violence.
   He was arrested on the day of the riots.
   The government contends that Abdel-Rahman is spiritual leader of
an underground extremist group called Jihad. It blames the group
for the 1981 assassination of President Anwar Sadat and a later
coup attempt.
   Abdel-Rahman was tried twice after Sadat's slaying for
involvement with Jihad but was acquitted both times.
   Although Badr said about 1,000 extremists were detained in the
sweep since the riots, he did not say how many remained in custody
and on what charges.
   The emergency law that allows the detentions also lets
authorities hold people for virtually as long as they like without
charge.
   Badr, a practicing Moslem, said he would continue to crack down
on Moslem extremists ``with the utmost firmness.''
   Fayoum rioters demanded that the government impose Islam's legal
and social code known as Sharia. The rules include harsh criminal
penalties, like limb amputation and flogging.
   The government says most Egyptian laws already conform to
Sharia, but they do not include the code's corporal punishments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
