<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Strike     04-17 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Strike,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Keeps Ports Functioning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's 125,000 dockworkers went on
strike for higher wages Monday and the military stepped in to keep
ports functioning, news reports said.
   Year-long negotiations with the government over a pay raise
reached a stalemate Sunday.
   Navy personnel unloaded oil tankers and other vessels at the
nation's 11 ports, a Shipping Ministry spokesman said. The army
sent engineers to Bombay port, the nation's largest, to run control
rooms and berth ships, the United News of India reported.
   The strike also cut imports to Nepal, said M. Kar Gupta,
chairman of the Calcutta Port. India earlier this month suspended
trade with Nepal in a treaty dispute and the land-locked Himalayan
kingdom has depended on supplies from other countries routed
through Calcutta Port.
   Workers were striking for a 25 percent pay increase, scaled down
from an initial 66 percent increase demanded a year ago, the news
agency said. The government has offered dock workers a 15 percent
raise.
   An Indian longshoreman earns between $90 and $180 per month.
</TEXT>
