<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ThirdWorldDebt     04-17 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Third World Debt,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Don't Expect Immediate Results, Brady Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The author of President Bush's new plan for
encouraging commerical banks to voluntarily reduce Third World debt
told Congress on Monday not to expect immediate results.
   Despite a $3.6 billion package put together last week by the
International Monetary Fund to support economic reform in Mexico,
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady said it is too optimistic to
assume that commercial banks will immediately agree on how much to
cut Mexico's debt to them.
   Mexican Finance Minister Pedro Aspe was scheduled to begin
negotiations this week with a consortium of 13 U.S. commercial
banks holding a large portion of Mexico's $100 billion debt.
   Brady told members of the House Approporations Committee that
the $1.3 billion first-year portion of the IMF package would depend
on Mexico negotiating debt reductions from the commercial banks.
However, he said he expects negotiations to be ``lengthy'' before
any agreement is announced.
   ``To be dead honest with you, I think you ought to be prepared
to wait longer,'' he said. ``Let's not try to make the first of
these transactions so big that it scares everybody to death. We
don't have to throttle the train up to a 100 miles per hour when
we're first getting started.''
   But Rep. Thomas Coleman, R-Mo., said there is a ``short time
span'' for the commercial banks to step forward.
   The Treasury secretary said he was ``disappointed'' that the IMF
package announced last week did not include provisions for
so-called debt-equity swaps.
   In those deals, a bank will forgive a portion of the principle
or interest on a loan in exchange for an investment share in newly
privatized enterprises that formerly were operated by the debtor
country's government.
   Without naming them, Brady said he knew of two countries
negotiating deals to write down by 20 percent loans for electric
power stations that would be converted from public to private
ownership.
   The parties involved, he said, believe that amount of money will
be returned to the countries in the form of native capital that had
earlier fled it.
   Brady attempted to dispel fears that taxpayers will end up
bailing out banks with Third World loans through arrangement by
government-funded multilateral lending agencies like the IMF and
World Bank to guarantee that commercial banks that reduce the loans
will be paid the remaining balance.
   ``I don't think anybody's going to be involved in putting more
money into it than we're already putting into it,'' he said.
   But because countries can leverage money from the IMF and World
Bank and the loans held by commerical banks are being sold for only
25 to 60 percent of their face value, he said, the plan would allow
countries to buy back a face value amount equal to 10 times the
seed money, he said.
   ``You can get a $10 reduction for every dollar you spend on the
process,'' Brady said. In addition, he said, $9 in procurement
``comes back our way'' for every dollar of U.S. taxpayer funds
funneled to debtor countries through the IMF and World Bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
