<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Wright'sDenial 1stLd-Writethru a0646 04-17 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright's Denial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0646,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speaker Has Friendly Audience for Denial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS ``certainly'' to ``surely'' in 4th graf, But unlike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright chose a friendly
audience Monday to deny violating House rules in his financial
dealings and to call for a swift resolution so Congress could tend
to its business.
   ``I know in my heart I have not violated any rules of that
institution,'' Wright told 3,000 delegates to an AFL-CIO Building
and Construction Trades Department conference. ``I love that
institution.''
   Those comments were similar to the denial he issued last week in
advance of the House ethics committee's report alleging 69
violations of House rules.
   But unlike last week, Wright did not give a detailed answer to
each of the charges against him. Instead he delivered a lengthy
defense of Democratic Party ideals and his career and asked that
the committee allow him to come before it to counter the charges
immediately, ``surely within a week.''
   ``We cannot delay and be bogged down in acrimony,'' Wright said.
``Life is too short for that. Our problems are too big for that.''
   The Texas Democrat said he was ``prepared to live up to'' the
ultimate outcome of the investigation and then said, ``As long as I
live I'm going to be working for the kind of country that doesn't
accept second best as good enough.''
   It appeared that he had ended his brief discussion of the ethics
charges and was moving on to other topics when he suddenly added:
``Sometimes assertive and bold leadership draws the ire of powerful
forces in this country.''
   At the outset of the speech it was not clear whether Wright
would address the charges at all.
   He entered to a standing ovation that lasted several minutes and
a warm introduction from Robert A. Georgine, president of the
Building and Construction Trades Department, who saluted Wright as
``a man of honor and a man of integrity.''
   ``He's now under bombardment by the same right-wing element that
for years has bombarded us,'' Georgine said. On a huge screeen
behind Georgine was the picture of Wright used on the cover of a
book that figures prominently in the allegations of ethics
violations.
   Wright opened his speech with a few jokes, flashing his wide
grin and saying the lengthy applause had ``almost embarrassed me,
but not quite.''
   There were more jokes about the welcoming.
   ``There are two kinds of people in this world who appreciate
flattery _ men and women.''
   Then came stories about how building trades unions had helped
him in his 18 elections to Congress.
   ``I feel at home here,'' Wright said to more applause.
   He listed Democratic programs from the Great Depression to the
last session of Congress, and promised more in the year to come.
   And, before turning to the subject that had brought a dozen
television cameras to the basement ballroom of a Washington hotel,
Wright talked a bit about himself.
   ``I am 66 years of age,'' he told the hushe audience. ``I have
had the great privilege ... of serving more than half my life in
the Congress of the United States. Thanks to the friendship and the
confidence of my colleagues I was elected speaker of the House. I
think it is the greatest honor that can come to any lawmaker.''
</TEXT>
