<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Psychiatry     04-17 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Psychiatry,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatric Expert Admits Abuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Soviet psychiatric expert said Monday that
authorities in the past had abused the legal rights of mental
patients in the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet Union pulled out of the World Psychiatric Association
in 1983 after reports that political dissidents were held in Soviet
psychiatric hospitals. The reports probably would have caused the
Soviets to be expelled from the association.
   The organization's executive committee voted at a meeting in
Madrid, Spain, on March 29 to re-admit the Soviets, a decision yet
to be ratified by the association's general assembly.
   ``Abuses have been committed in our psychiatry during the recent
decades,'' the official Tass news agency quoted Alexander Karpov,
the chief psychiatric expert in the Ministry of Public Health, as
saying. ``The way psychiatric patients were treated was not always
correct.''
   Karpov spoke at the opening of a three-day symposium on the law
and mental health attended by psychiatrists and lawyers from a
dozen countries.
   Karpov, without mentioning the treatment of dissidents, said
denying legal rights to psychiatric patients must be eliminated.
   ``This is why a decree was issued in the U.S.S.R. last year,
laying down new rules of psychiatric treatment,'' Tass quoted him
as saying.
   ``It gives the patients definite legal guarantees, showing that
they are no longer rightless in the eyes of public health organs,''
Karpov said. ``They now have the right to call in a lawyer, to
complain to the prosecutor or the court of justice.''
   The symposium is being attended by psychiatrists and lawyers
specializing in psychiatric cases from the United States, Canada,
the Netherlands, Switzerland, Denmark, West Germany, East Germany,
Bulgaria, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, Poland and Cuba, Tass said.
   In early March, a team of U.S. psychiatrists and lawyers were
allowed to interview 27 patients in an unprecedented two-week tour
of Soviet mental hospitals.
   After the tour, a group spokesman praised the Soviet Union for
its openness but said it was still impossible to tell whether
patients were being held for their political views, an abuse of
psychiatry the Soviets have pledged to end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
