<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Medicare     04-17 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Stepping Up Efforts to Spot Private Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is planning to increase its
efforts to assure that the Medicare program does not pay medical
bills for which private insurance carriers are liable.
   The secretary of health and human services, Louis Sullivan,
asked Office of Management and Budget Director Richard Darman in a
letter Friday to release $7.5 million to begin the stepped-up
enforcement plan.
   The HHS contingency funds would be used to make revisions in the
contracts with Medicare claims processors to require them to match
their private insurance records with their Medicare rolls, Sullivan
said. This would enable them to identify claims where private
policies are liable for the bill.
   The coverage issue stems from an overlap between Medicare and
private health plans for elderly people who continue to work.
   Under the law, Medicare is liable only for charges not covered
by the elderly employee's private health plan.
   Current efforts by the Health Care Financing Administration
results in annual Medicare savings of more than $1.8 billion, but
``HCFA has known for some time that there is potential for even
greater savings,'' Sullivan said.
   Sullivan said the department, which includes HCFA, would again
propose legislation that would require all health insurers to
provide information identifying those enrolled in their plans who
may be eligible for Medicare.
   ``Although our efforts to convince the Office of Management and
Budget of the need for this legislation have been unsuccessful,''
recent findings of an HHS task force as well as news reports of
potential savings and possibile fraud highlight the need for
greater efforts, Sullivan said.
   The Justice Department has said it is reviewing a number of
cases referred by HHS in which authorities believe Medicare paid
medical bills for which private carriers were liable.
   The department's civil division recently filed lawsuits against
two private insurance companies to recover money the government
claims should not have been paid by Medicare.
   The Wall Street Journal reported earlier this month that its
investigation of HCFA records shows as much as $10 billion may have
been misspent over the last six years because the agency has failed
to correct the billing problem.
   Medicare currently is paying about $67 million this year to 88
commercial insurance companies that serve as claims processors to
identify claims where private insurance carriers _ sometimes their
own _ are liable.
   HHS Inspector General Richard Kusserow and others have said they
are concerned about a possible conflict of interest in these
companies' roles as a Medicare contractor and commercial insurance
carrier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
