<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--LeaningTower     04-17 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Leaning Tower,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pisa's Tower to be Measured at the End of Each Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PISA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Leaning Tower of Pisa will be measured
every three months instead of just once a year to see if seasonal
change affects the landmark, scientists said Monday.
   Since 1913, the angle of the 800-year-old tower's lean has been
measured every year in June. This year a reading was taken in
March, and other measurements will be taken in June, September and
December.
   ``There is no particular cause for alarm,'' said Brunetto Palla,
a professor at the University of Pisa. ``We are curious to see
whether the change of seasons has an affect on the tower.''
   The collapse of a 900-year-old tower in Pavia on March 17 has
raised concerns over the stability and safety of Italy's monuments.
Four people were killed.
   The March measurements showed no notable variation from June
1988, Palla said.
   The monument began to lean shortly after its construction in
1173 when the soil beneath the 180-foot marble monument shifted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
