<DOCNO> AP890417-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mandela     04-17 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandela,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Botha Asks Mandela To Promote Peaceful Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha said Monday
the government will ``react with magnanimity'' if jailed black
leader Nelson Mandela offers to promote a peaceful settlement in
South Africa.
   Botha's speech in Parliament appeared no different from previous
government offers to free the 70-year-old African National Congress
leader on condition he renounces his guerrilla organization's use
of violence. Mandela has refused.
   It would be futile for the government to release Mandela if his
freedom led to heightened conflict or if he was re-arrested, Botha
said.
   He cautioned he could not take any steps that may lead to ``the
rejection of democratic principles and the destruction of private
initiative and free enterprise.'' This appeared to be his view of
what South Africa would be like under the ANC, which espouses
socialism.
   ``For these reasons, the case of Mr. Mandela is being treated
with circumspection,'' said Botha, 73, who plans to retire after
elections expected by mid-September.
   Mandela, considered by many South African blacks as their
paramount leader, has been imprisoned since 1962 on a life sentence
for plotting to sabotage the white-minority government. He has been
living in a staff house at a prison farm near Cape Town since he
recovered from a bout of tuberculosis last year.
   If Mandela shows he is willing to contribute to a peaceful
settlement in South Africa, ``the government will react with
magnanimity,'' Botha said.
   On another topic, the South African leader acknowledged he has
had differences recently with members of his National Party, but
said he will ensure the disputes do not become ``unbridgeable
divisions.''
   ``There should not be attempts to drive a wedge between us,'' he
said.
   Botha suffered a stroke in January, and shortly after resigned
as party leader. Several Nationalist officials and newspapers then
urged Botha to step down as president in favor of the new party
leader, Education Minister F.W. de Klerk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
