<FIRST>r w AM-BaseClosings     04-17 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Base Closings,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suit Filed to Halt Base Closings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An organization representing federal employees
filed suit Monday to prevent the closing of U.S. military bases,
charging that the law creating the federal commission that
recommends base closings is unconstitutional.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court by the National
Federation of Federal Employees against the United States, said the
Base Closure and Realignment Act violates the Constitution ``by
improperly delegating the important legislative function of
regulating the disposition of government property, to the unelected
secretary of defense, and to the unelected members of the
commission.''
   The suit also said that the Constitution requires that Congress
provide for the nation's defense. The base closure law calls for
the commission's recommendations to be accepted in their entirety
and denies Congress the right to determine ``the logistical
arrangements for the U.S. military forces in the 21st century,''
the suit said.
   The union represents 5,000 employees at George Air Force Base
and Norton Air Force Base in California, and Chanute Air Force Base
in Illinois. All are scheduled to be closed.
   Congress approved legislation in October 1988 requiring the
defense secretary to close and realign bases according to the
panel's report. Two months later, the commission recommended
closing 86 bases, partly closing five more and changing the mission
of 54 others.
   Former Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci approved the
commission's report in January.
   The House is scheduled to vote Tuesday on a resolution to
disapprove the base closing recommendations. Last month, the House
Armed Services Committee, by a vote of 43-4, supported the
recommendations; the full House is expected to do the same.
   James M. Peirce, president of the union, said the commission
based its decision on ``erroneous and out-of-date information. To
put it simply, the commission blew it and it doesn't appear as if
the majority of Congress gives a damn.''
   The union is seeking a declaratory judgment from the courts on
whether the Base Closure and Realignment Act is unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
