<FIRST>r a AM-BarbaraBush     04-17 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Lauds Volunteer Effort in Literacy Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush, saying nearly all of society's
benefits flow from literacy, praised a young woman Monday who
learned to read and broke free from the welfare cycle.
   Addressing more than 3,000 volunteer leaders at a United Way
national conference, the first lady said: ``You are at the heart of
virtually every worthy cause there is.''
   Mrs. Bush praised United Way for its help and funding of such
organizations as Red Cross and the Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts and
causes as diverse as combatting child abuse and comforting young
AIDS patients.
   Then, turning to the cause that has been the focus of her own
volunteer leadership, Mrs. Bush said as many as 25 percent of
Americans struggle with literacy.
   ``Literacy is everybody's business,'' she said. ``The need for
literacy is linked to every other important need in society ...
housing, nutrition, health ... employment.''
   To illustrate the point, Mrs. Bush's address was followed by a
videotape about Evelyn Vega, a 29-year-old Stamford, Conn.,
resident and mother of three children, who broke 11 years of
welfare dependence by learning to read and getting a job.
   Mrs. Vega dropped out of high school during her first pregnancy
and was the third generation of her family to live on public
assistance. The film showed her receiving reading lessons from
United Way volunteer Paige Oristano and working as the assistant
manager at a fast-food restaurant.
   After the film, Mrs. Vega, who since has become a United Way
volunteer, read from a letter she had written Mrs. Bush to thank
her for supporting literacy programs.
   ``It is hard and scary to get off welfare. You cannot do it by
yourself. People like me need someone out there to teach them how
to make that dream come true because it is all new to them. ... I
still feel scared,'' she said, her voice choking with tears.
   Mrs. Vega presented the first lady with a copy of the letter and
the two women hugged briefly as the gathering rose to its feet and
applauded. Overcome with emotion, Mrs. Vega kissed Mrs. Bush's
cheek.
   Later Monday, Mrs. Bush traveled to the Museum of Science and
Industry on the South Side, where she officially opened an exhibit
on the brain and learning disabilities.
   The permanent exhibit, called ``Learning and Learning
Disabilties: Explorations of the Human Brain,'' is the first of its
kind in the nation.
   `This is truly an exhibit of hope,'' the first lady said. ``I
applaud the museum for addressing this misunderstood subject in a
public forum.''
   The exhibit uses touch screens, video monitors, mannequins and
giant brain models to show how the brain changes as it learns and
how disabilties alter that process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
