<FIRST>r i AM-France-ElderlyMurders     04-17 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Elderly Murders,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Killing 18 Elderly Women Dies of AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who confessed to the serial murders of 18
elderly Parisian women died Monday of AIDS while awaiting trial,
prison officials said.
   Thierry Paulin, a 26-year-old native of Martinique, was arrested
Dec. 1, 1987, after a three-year manhunt for the killer of a large
group of elderly women between October 1984 and January 1986.
   The women all were between 60 and 83 years of age, and nearly
all were strangled, stabbed or smothered in their homes after being
severely beaten. Paulin told police that he stalked the women and
forced his way into their homes.
   Paulin had a record of arrests for thefts and drugs, but police
said the killings did not seem to be linked exclusively to money.
They said that during the interrogation, Paulin ``had trouble
distinguishing between all the attacks he had committed.''
   Paulin's fingerprints were found in the homes of at least seven
murder victims, police said at the time.
   Prison authorities, who declined to be identified in keeping
with prison policy, said Paulin tested positive for AIDS in 1986
and last year began suffering symptoms of the disease that attacks
and destroys the body's immune system.
   Paulin fell into a coma several days ago and was admitted to the
intensive care unit of Fresnes prison hospital over the weekend. He
died early Monday, authorities said without providing any other
details.
   Before his death, Paulin blamed several of the murders on his
accomplice, Jean-Thierry Mathuin, who was arrested shortly after
Paulin and remains in custody.
   AIDS is most often transmitted through sexual contact. Other
means of transmission include transfusions of tainted blood or
blood products, and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles
or syringes by drug abusers.
</TEXT>
