<FIRST>u i AM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0638 04-17 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Cancels Talks to Protest Dissident's Arrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with demonstrations, political scandal,
labor unrest. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea canceled two negotiating
sessions, saying Monday that South Korea's arrest of a dissident
who visited the communist nation was part of a plan to undermine
efforts for better relations.
   Two letters from Pyongyang called off talks set for Tuesday on a
possible joint team for the 1990 Asian Games in Beijing, and an
April 26 session on arranging a meeting of the two prime ministers.
   The action appeared to threaten future negotiations between
South Korea and North Korea on easing their bitter rivalry in a
land divided since World War II.
   North Korea proposed the talks resume in July, but Seoul
officials said continuing the dialogue would have to be considered.
They spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Both messages from North Korea were delivered at Panmunjom, the
truce village at the border, and released by the government of
President Roh Tae-woo in Seoul.
   They criticized South Korea for arresting the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan
for his visit last month to Pyongyang, where he discussed
reunification of the peninsula with President Kim Il Sung.
   Moon was arrested Thursday on his return to Seoul via Japan, and
charged with aiding anti-state groups and making an illegal visit
to North Korea.
   About 10,000 war veterans and supporters, shouting
anti-communist slogans, demonstrated Monday in Puchon, about 12
miles west of Seoul, denouncing Moon's trip and ``leftists trying
to destroy freedom and peace through revolution,'' according to the
South Korean news agency Yonhap.
   Thousands of radical students in Seoul and elsewhere fought riot
police or rallied to demand Moon's release, Yonhap said. No
injuries or arrests were reported.
   North Korea said Moon's arrest proved Seoul did not want to
improve relations. It is illegal for South Koreans to visit North
Korea without government permission.
   Paik Nam Jun, a senior North Korean official, said in the letter
suspending political talks that the charge against Moon of dealing
with an ``anti-state organization'' could only refer to North Korea.
   As a result, he said, ``the smooth conduct of the north-south
talks has been made impossible.'' Paik said North Korea hoped the
``atmosphere would improve'' and meetings could resume in July.
   The two nations have tried to improve relations through a series
of talks that began in 1988, but with little success.
   When Moon went to Pyongyang, the Seoul government cracked down
on dissidents and said Moon wanted to help North Korea seize
control of the entire peninsula. South Korea says talks with the
North may be conducted only by the government.
   Dissidents in the South have held violent protests demanding the
downfall of Roh's government, but they have little public support
and Moon's visit to North Korea appears to have damaged their cause.
   Many South Koreans who fear North Korea were infuriated by the
visit. Television showed Moon embracing Kim, who ordered the 1950
invasion that started the Korean War.
   The two Koreas technically remain at war because no peace treaty
was signed after the war ended in 1953.
   In other Korean developments Monday:
   _Daewoo Motor Co., a joint venture between the U.S.-based
General Motors Corp. and South Korea's Daewoo Group, halted
production in response to a wave of strikes by workers seeking
higher wages. Similar walkouts forced carmakers Hyundai Motor Co.
and Kia Motor Corp. to stop production last week. Officials said
the job actions threaten South Korea's economy. Also Monday, 5,000
taxi drivers threatened to strike for higher wages and improved
working conditions.
   _Eight senior lawmakers of South Korea's second largest
opposition party, the Reunification Democratic Party led by Kim
Young-sam, offered to resign over a scandal involving a party
lawmaker who bribed a rival candidate to drop out of a National
Assembly election. It was not clear if Kim would accept the
resignations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
