<FIRST>r a AM-CruseSentencing     04-17 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruse Sentencing,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Weighs Sentence for Shopping Center Killer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of slaying six people at a
shopping center wept as relatives testifying at his sentencing
described how he cared for his mother and ailing wife.
   It was the first public display of emotion by William Bryan
Cruse during the long trial and numerous court appearances for the
shooting rampage in Palm Bay two years ago that claimed the lives
of two police officers and four other people.
   Cruse, 61, was convicted April 5 on 32 counts of murder,
attempted murder and kidnapping. The jury that found him guilty
must recommend to Circuit Judge John Antoon whether Cruse should be
sentenced to death or life in prison.
   Cruse cried when his niece, Rebbeca J. Thompson of Lexington,
Ky., told jurors that he doted on his wife, who had Parkinson's
disease.
   ``He was always there for her,'' Mrs. Thompson said. ``They
never had children, but they had each other.''
   She said her uncle visited his mother every day in a nursing
home until her death in 1980.
   Joyce K. Cruse, widow of the convicted man's brother, said the
defendant ``took good care of his mother. He would come over and
fix her breakfast. If she was ill, he would stay all night. ... We
all loved him and still do.''
   Earlier, Assistant State Attorney Chris White said Cruse should
be put to death because he committed the murders in a ``cold,
calculated, premeditated fashion.''
   But Assistant Public Defender Paul Arlt said witnesses would
show Cruse was severely mentally disturbed at the time of the
crime, had a reduced capacity to realize the consequences of his
actions, did not realize he had hurt anyone and that his mental
condition was aggravated by alcohol.
</TEXT>
