<FIRST>u i AM-Uruguay     04-17 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uruguay,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sanguinetti Says Referendum Settles Amnesty Question</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Julio M. Sanguinetti said
Monday the question of amnesty for human rights abuses under
military rule has been settled by voter approval of the amnesty law
his government passed in 1986.
   With 7,037 of 7,072 districts reporting in Sunday's referendum,
the vote was 1,013,554 for amnesty, or 52.62 percent, and 771,942 _
40.08 percent _ who wanted the law discarded.
   Sanguinetti, a 52-year-old lawyer, told reporters Monday: ``Now
the discussion has ended.''
   When asked whether his government would consider a compromise
with opponents of amnesty, since they got nearly 41 percent of the
vote, he replied:
   ``They were the ones who chose this way. They were the ones who
submitted the law to a majority vote. ... National peace is to
accept the verdict of the ballot box.''
   Blank or invalid ballots, and others classed as questionable
that may or may not be counted, totaled 140,703, or 7.3 percent of
the votes cast. About 85 percent of eligible voters participated.
   The amnesty law forbids prosecution of about 180 soldiers and
police accused of torture, murder and other crimes in 1973-85, when
the military ruled Uruguay and conducted what it called a war on
leftist subversion.
   It was passed by the new civilian government in December 1986,
after officers made clear they would not answer charges in the
courts.
   Three military uprisings have occurred in neighboring Argentina
during the past two years because of the same issue. Argentina
returned to civilian government in 1983 after nearly eight years of
military rule and has tried many officers, including former junta
members.
   Uruguayans voted on amnesty because the National Commission for
a Referendum gathered 634,000 petition signatures during 1987, more
than the required 25 percent of registered voters.
   Sanguinetti said his goal was to consolidate democracy in this
nation of 3 million people, which was an example of representative
government to Latin America before 1973, and ``in this case, peace
is justice.''
   He told the news conference amnesty does not excuse or justify
military abuses, which included the executions of about 150
Uruguayans, arrests and disappearances of 200 more and the torture
of several thousand.
   It must be remembered, he said, that military intervention
followed years of terrorism and economic chaos. Sanguinetti said
leftist Tupamaro guerrillas were released from prison in 1985 and
the military amnesty ``is on the same line.''
   ``There is no sense of triumph'' in the referendum's result, he
said, and added: ``The most important aspect in all this is that
the country was able to do it'' by popular vote. ``Yesterday at
7:30 p.m., when the ballot boxes were closed, Uruguay completed its
transition'' to democracy.
   The National Commission for a Referendum, and the human rights
and leftist political groups that supported the referendum,
apparently accepted the outcome.
   Only the small Communist Party said the vote was not fair,
claiming the government intimidated voters by hinting of trouble if
the amnesty was overturned.
   Matilde Rodriguez Larreta de Gutierrez, co-president of the
referendum commission, said: ``in accordance with the results of
the referendum, the amnesty has been confirmed. Without doubt, the
decision of the electorate should be accepted.''
</TEXT>
