<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Seizure     04-17 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Seizure,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Eastern Jet Seized With Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the relatively few Eastern Airlines jets
flying since the beginning of a strike against the carrier was
seized Monday by Customs after inspectors found 75 pounds of
cocaine in a mail bag in the cargo hold.
   It was the 14th seizure of cocaine on an Eastern plane since
September, and eight of those shipments were found in the mail, or
courier, bags.
   The Boeing 727 seized Monday landed in Miami after a flight from
Asuncion, Paraguay, that stopped in Bolivia, Peru and Panama, said
Customs spokesman Michael Sheehan.
   Customs imposed a $1.2 million fine on Eastern and demanded a
letter of credit from the strike-hobbled airline before releasing
the plane.
   ``We hate to kick an airline while it's down, but we will not
allow illegal drugs into the country,'' Sheehan said.
   Because of Eastern's financial problems, Customs has decided to
cash in three previous credit letters worth about $3 million, he
said. The letters are usually held until Customs and the airline
negotiate an agreement on the fine.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said Customs will have to go
to bankruptcy court to get its money. ``We don't think that fining
airlines and seizing their aircraft is the way to stop drug
trafficking,'' said Ms. Ceremsak.
   She said the airline spent $3 million on security last year, an
amount that was not decreased this year even though Eastern has had
to severely shrink its schedule following the March 4 Machinists'
strike that was supported by pilots and flight attendants.
   But Sheehan said Eastern apparently wasn't doing the job, even
though smugglers were using the same method time after time.
   ``Due to the fact that over half of the seizure have been in
courier bags, we find it difficult to understand why courier bags
do not receive extra attention,'' Sheehan said. ``There shouldn't
be a courier bag on Eastern Airlines that isn't gone over with a
fine-toothed comb.''
   The bright blue and green bag, of a type used to carry mail, was
found during a routine inspection Monday by the Customs Contraband
Enforcement Team.
   It was not on the plane manifest, and authorities did not know
where it was put aboard the plane.
   No destination was listed on the bag, suggesting that someone
planned to remove it from the cargo hold in Miami, Sheehan said.
   Meanwhile, eight men who were Eastern baggage handlers at the
time of their 1986 indictment went on trial Monday in a smuggling
scheme. They are charged with conspiracy to import cocaine and
conspiracy to possess cocaine with intent to distribute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
