<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     04-17 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighting Poses Logistical Problems For U.N. Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. spokesman said Monday that the
fierce combat that broke out in northern Namibia at the outset of
the independence process has created severe logistical problems for
the U.N. monitoring force.
   Cedric Thornberry, second-in-command of the U.N. contingent that
is to oversee Namibia's transition to independence, said U.N.
personnel had planned to use vacated South African military
facilities.
   But because of clashes between security forces and guerrillas of
the South-West Africa People's Organization, South African troop
withdrawal has been delayed, he said. This has created ``enormous
competition'' for accommodation and other facilities in the
relatively underdeveloped northern region of Ovambo.
   Thornberry said the United Nations planned to start deploying
police monitors in Ovambo this week who will check actions of the
South African-led territorial police force. But he said it was hard
to find offices for monitors that were easily accessible to
civilians who might want to file complaints.
   The world body has urged civilians to report allegations of
harassment or intimidation by the security forces or SWAPO
supporters.
   At U.N. headquarters in New York, SWAPO Foreign Secretary
Theo-Ben Gurirab said Monday that Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar should visit Namibia to restore public confidence in the
United Nations.
   Gurirab said a visit by the U.N. chief would help restore the
``tarnished'' image of the United Nations in the eyes of Namibians.
   He blamed the world organization for not stationing U.N.
peacekeepers in northern Namibia by April 1, the day a cease-fire
was supposed to take effect at the start of a yearlong transition
to independence but instead the day that SWAPO guerrillas fought
gun battles with South African-led security forces.
   Territorial officials say 278 guerrillas and 27 security force
members have been killed and 28 guerrillas captured.
   Thornberry said 2,662 members of the planned 4,650-member U.N.
military force were in Namibia by Monday, with 410 Kenyan
infantrymen due by Tuesday.
   South Africa said about 1,600 guerrillas crossed the border from
Angola in violation of an agreement that they stay at bases at
least 100 miles inside Angola. Up to 380 guerrillas returned to
Angola after withdrawal orders from their exiled leader, and about
900 remain in Namibia, South African offficials say.
   As of Monday, only seven guerrillas reported to U.N. checkpoints
established as part of a plan to give guerrillas safe passage back
to Angola. The others who withdrew did so on their own.
   Officials expressed doubt that guerrillas would venture near the
assembly points because of the heavy concentration of police and
soldiers around each area.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I. In December,
it agreed to allow independence in exchange for Cuba's withdrawing
its estimated 50,000 troops from Angola.
   SWAPO has fought South African rule since 1966 and is favored to
get the most votes in pre-independence elections scheduled for
November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
