</TEXT>
<NOTE>B. Wright's Efforts on Behalf of Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corporation</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In September 1979, Wright co-signed a letter to Secretary of the
Interior, Cecil D. Andrus, on behalf of Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corporation
(``TXO''). The letter provided Andrus with background information
on TXO and its dispute with the Arkla Exploration Company over
mineral exploration leases on land in Arkansas.
   Wright held no interest in TXO at any relevant time. As
discussed in Section III. A. of this Report, from February 1979
until March 1984 Wright held an interest in the Whatley well, an
east-Texas natural gas well drilled and operated by TXO. However,
as an investor in the well, Wright's financial return was
determined only by the productivity of the well and could not have
been affected by TXO's success or failure with respect to the
Arkansas leases. Wright's letter did not comment upon the merits of
the dispute between TXO and Arkla. Therefore, it is not a
prohibited ex parte communication under the Government in the
Sunshine Act, Pub. L. 94-409, 4, Stat. 1241, 1246, 5 U.S.C. 557(d).
   The letter was the only communication on the subject between
Wright or his staff and Andrus or his staff. Therefore, the letter
was not an exercise of undue influence by Wright. Furthermore,
Andrus and undersecretary James A. Joseph both stated that the
letter made no demand or request that they deemed unusual or
improper. Nor did the letter affect the decision made by the
department with respect to the leases.
   As discussed in full in Section III. B. of this Report, Wright's
communication with the Secretary of the Interior on behalf of TXO
violated no law or standard of conduct.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<NOTE>C. Wright's Publication and Marketing of ``Reflections of a Public</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Man''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In early 1984, Wright and his close friend William Carlos Moore
discussed producing a book of Wright's earlier speeches, poems and
writings which Wright and Moore testified would be sold at low cost
to a very broad audience including college students and ``average
citizens.'' Wright told the Committee he wanted to give people an
idea of what his personal feelings were on a number of subjects so
that they could get to know the Majority Leader and next Speaker of
the House.
   Wright also discussed the book with his staff. Matthew
Cossolotto, Wright's congressional staff researcher and speech
writer, testified that Wright first raised the subject of the book
at a staff breakfast in February 1984. Wright asked the staff to
think about ways to market the book and suggested that when he gave
a speech to a trade association or other group, he could sell the
group books instead of taking an honorarium. Cossolotto testified
that Wright explained to the staff that unlike honoraria, book
royalties are exempt from the 30 percent maximum limit on outside
earned income.
   Throughout 1984, Wright had members of his staff collecting his
old speeches and compiling, editing, typing and proofreading the
manuscript for his book. Wright's staff obtained celebrity
endorsements of the book for the back cover and selected a
photograph of Wright for the front cover.
   Carlos Moore formed the Madison Publishing company in 1984 as a
division of Madison Systems Corporation, Moore's political
consulting firm, for the purpose of publishing Wright's book,
``Reflections of a Public Man.'' However, Madison Publishing did
not ``publish'' Wright's book. Nor has it published any other book.
   Madison Publishing designed the layout and printed the cover for
Wright's book. Moore sent the book itself to be printed and
assembled by The Printing Center in Fort Worth because, as he
testified, Madison Publishing did not have the capacity to print
20,000 copies. The Printing Center actually printed 19,068 books
and reduced the charge to Madison Publishing accordingly. The final
product was completed in early December 1984 and delivered in two
installments on December 6 and 18, 1984.
   Wright himself applied for and secured copyright protection for
the book and hired a Fort Worth real estate attorney to draft a
``royalty'' agreement between Wright and Madison Publishing
Company. Wright supplied the attorney with specific provisions to
be included in the agreement including the provisions for a 55
percent ``royalty.'' The agreement was executed on December 12,
1984, after 2,160 copies of the completed books had already been
delivered to Moore.
</TEXT>
