<FIRST>u w AM-Wright-Analysis Bjt   04-17 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright-Analysis, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Reports Gives Opponents Ammunition, but Doesn't Strike Fatal
Blow</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public airing of the ethics committee report
on House Speaker Jim Wright provides his opponents with reams of
political ammunition, but does not in itself strike a fatal blow.
   Democrats must move to quickly mold public opinion if the
speaker is going to keep his leadership post, and Wright's allies
say having the facts on the table can help.
   The Committee on Standards of Official Conduct released a
voluminous report by its special counsel and charged the speaker
with 69 instances of violating House rules.
   The report provides sometimes embarrassing details of the
financial benefits he received from friendships with two Fort Worth
businessmen.
   One, Carlos Moore, gave Wright unusually high royalties he
published the speaker's book, ``Reflections of a Public Man.'' With
fifty-five cents of every dollar going to Wright, the committee
said it appeared that the speaker was using bulk sales of the
paperback to evade House limits on outside income from speeches.
   The second friend, George Mallick, had a business partnership
with the speaker. Wright and his wife, Betty, benefited from the
free use of a condominium and a car, and an $18,000 annual salary
to Mrs. Wright.
   House members are looking at the committee report on two
political levels: within the institution and in their home
districts.
   Within the House, release of the report Monday caused members to
begin focusing on their own situations.
   ``We have to deal with it on a very specific level,'' said
Martin Frost, D-Texas, a Wright ally who contends lawmakers will
make independent judgments despite pressure at home. ``I think
members don't want to be stampeded on this, one way or another,''
he said.
   Frost said members confronted with the committee's findings will
find them troubling because of their broad implications. For
example, it decided that Mallick had an interest in legislation
using a standard so broad that anyone with wealth would fall in the
same category, he contended, a situation that could snare many
lawmakers.
   ``I think members will look at this in a serious way and say,
`Is this fair?''' he said.
   Outside of the House, Democrats must persuade the public that
the violations Wright is accused of are mostly technical and not
really unethical. They can't afford to wait for the committee to
render a verdict on whether Wright should be found guilty and
punished.
   The initial rush of publicity was seen by virtually everyone as
negative for Wright, but Democratic leaders argued that as they
rebut the specific charges the public will come to believe that
Wright is being held to an unjust standard.
   Rep. Beryl Anthony of Arkansas, chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, said that ``once people clearly
understand ... then you get an entirely different feel and
reaction.''
   Wright himself must also be convincing.
   ``If the speaker is well received in the country, and what he
says is resonant with the American public, he improves his
chances,'' said Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C.
   Further, the report itself is not a conviction. That could only
be done by the full House and even if that were to occur, it would
be up to the Democrats who elected him to decide whether Wright has
become an unsupportable political liability.
   With few exceptions, Republicans greeted the release with sounds
of deference and respect to the process set up to investigate a
fellow member. Despite the fact that the campaign to investigate
Wright's finances was kicked off by one of their own, Rep. Newt
Gingrich of Georgia, the Republicans tried to portray themselves as
above the fray.
   A key element in their strategy to wrest control of the House
away from the Democrats is to portray the Democrats as the party of
corruption and themselves as its enemy.
   ``The best politics for Republicans is no evidence of politics
at all,'' said Rep. Jerry Lewis of California, chairman of the
House Republican Conference.
   Some Democrats scoffed at the GOP tactic.
   It was ``bipartisan, non-partisan garbage,'' said Rep. James
Traficant, D-Ohio. ``Let there be no mistake, today in Washington,
D.C. the party lines are being drawn in indelible ink.''
   The verdict on Wright from the ethics committee may be technical
and not so clear as the party lines. But when that comes, some
weeks down the road, the public verdict may have already come in.
   ``We'll be opening our own mail for a while,'' said Rep. Pat
Williams, D-Mont.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE: Steven Komarow has been covering Congress and</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   politics for The Associated Press since 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
