<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0611 04-17 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,0887</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Calls for Rebuilding Newly Legalized Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Walesa comments on Bush, arrival
in Warsaw. EDITS thereafter to trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa on Monday urged Poles to
rebuild Solidarity ``skillfully and quickly'' hours after a court
declared the independent union legal again and ended seven years of
government suppression.
   Walesa also praised President Bush for announcing an aid package
for Poland's economy.
   Walesa was expected to follow up restoration of his union's
legal status with a meeting Tuesday with his longtime antagonist,
Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, and a trip to Rome on
Wednesday to meet Polish-born Pope John Paul II at the Vatican.
   Looking relaxed despite what he said was a case of pneumonia,
Walesa arrived by train in Warsaw on Monday night and told
reporters Bush was ``a brilliant politician.''
   ``Bush is a great man and he knows the Polish situation very
well,'' he said. He called the proposal for U.S. aid ``quite big.''
   Walesa was accompanied to Warsaw by key adviser Adam Michnik and
was welcomed at the station by a handful of other Solidarity
advisers.
   He said he could not confirm or deny he had a planned meeting
with Jaruzelski.
   ``I appeal to all workers and supporters of our union to form
factory organizations as soon as possible where they still don't
exist and to report their membership in Solidarity or to join it,''
said Walesa, in a statement read in Warsaw by union spokesman
Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
   Onyszkiewicz said an independent union press should begin
operating by the end of the month and that Solidarity should get
new national headquarters in Gdansk by Tuesday.
   ``Our effort, devotion and suffering have not been in vain,''
Walesa said in his statement. ``We defended our workers' rights,
together we are paving a road to a fully democratic and sovereign
Poland.''
   But he cautioned the ``day of success'' came in hard economic
times.
   ``The Polish nation is facing tasks which are much more complex
than in 1980. Now we must undertake a trial of real and deep
economic reform and democratic restructuring of the state,'' he
said.
   The Warsaw provincial court registered the reborn Solidarity in
the same room where its original charter was approved in November
1980.
   Onyszkiewicz said Walesa stayed away from the hearing in part
because the union always regarded itself as legal, so the session
had ``a technical rather than symbolic nature.''
   Nevertheless, there was thunderous applause when the verdict was
complete, sealing an about-face approved earlier by Communist Party
leaders.
   As the court session ended, hundreds of hands lifted in the
``V'' for victory sign and chants of ``Solidarnosc! Solidarnosc!''
filled the room. Solidarity leaders beamed, supporters waved
bouquets of yellow daffodils, and judges shook hands with the
participants.
   Then there were cheers of ``Lech Walesa! Lech Walesa!'' and the
singing of the national anthem.
   ``The spirit of history was with us,'' said Solidarity supporter
Krzysztof Sliwinski.
   Two Solidarity banners were held aloft during the hearing before
Presiding Judge Danuta Widawska and two other judges. About a dozen
Solidarity leaders and advisers and 300 sympathizers jammed the
narrow courtroom with yellow walls and crimson curtains. Another
100 waited in the corridor.
   ``Polish society puts enormous hopes in the honest operation of
all trade unions in the area of the rights and interests of the
working people and the realization of their material and cultural
needs,'' Ms. Widawska said after the verdict, in which she
registered Solidarity as a legal trade union.
   Jaruzelski tried to dissolve Solidarity in a December 1981
martial-law crackdown, but now seeks the movement's help to pull
Poland out of economic crisis.
   Party and government officials also admit that by legalizing the
union they hope to encourage the West to provide economic help to
Poland, burdened by a $38 billion foreign debt.
   President Bush on Monday announced an aid package to help
Poland's economy. He told a Polish-American crowd in Hamtramck,
Mich., that continued aid would depend on consistent moves by the
communist government toward reform.
   The concessions could open the way for up to $1 billion in new
loans, loan rescheduling and trade and investment relief, according
to administration and international monetary sources.
   The last step in the long bid for restoration of Solidarity
followed unprecedented negotiations between communist authorities
and opposition representatives led by Walesa.
   The talks reached accords on legalizing Solidarity, creating the
first freely elected legislative chamber in the Soviet bloc and
other economic and political reforms.
   Solidarity members, who predict the union will grow to 5 million
to 7 million members and hold its first congress later this year,
face the tasks of organizing the union and the election campaign.
   The movement was 10 million strong and so popular it threatened
to topple the communists' monopoly on power when martial law was
imposed.
   Although thousands of its activists including Walesa were locked
up, the union continued to function _ first as an underground
organization staging rallies and putting out clandestine
newspapers, and then more openly in factories and offices after a
1986 political amnesty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-Wright-Phelan 2ndadd   04-17 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wright-Phelan, 2nd add,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: to Moore.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The agreement provided that Wright would receive $3.25 (nearly
55 percent) of the $5.95 list price on all retail sales of the
book. Moore would receive $2.70 from which he would pay all
printing and marketing expenses. Such ``royalty'' payments are
unheard of in the publishing industry. In fact, Wright's previous
royalty contracts with three major publishers provided for standard
industry royalties ranging from 10 percent to 15 percent, depending
upon sales. Morton Janklow, an expert on the publishing industry,
testified that no rational publisher would agree to a 55 percent
royalty on list price because it could not make a profit. Janklow
also testified that in his opinion as literary agent for Nancy
Reagan, Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, Helmut Schmidt, Sidney Sheldon and
Danielle Steele, Wright's book was not commercially publishable.
   Although the agreement also provided that Madison Publishing
would publish and market the book, in fact, Wright and his staff
provided many of the ordinary services of a publisher and made the
most significant contribution to marketing efforts. ...
   In this instance, Moore designed the layout and printed the
cover of the book. He hired others to typeset and print the book
itself. All other aspects of book production were performed by
Wright or his staff. Moore also sent out 300 to 500 letters
soliciting orders for the book and employed 12 to 15 people for
four hours a day during one week to make telephone solicitations
from voter registration lists. Moore arranged an autograph party,
one or two newspaper advertisements and an appearance by Wright on
the Larry King Show. Moore's marketing efforts resulted in precious
few sales to ``average citizens.'' In fact, Moore testified that he
never intended to sell the book to bookstores where average people
could buy them because bookstores would only purchase at the
discount price of $3.00 per copy. ``That doesn't leave you much
room.''
   The real focus of the marketing effort for ``Reflections of a
Public Man'' was on bulk sales to trade associations and other
groups. Almost 98 percent of all sales of ``Reflections of a Public
Man'' were bulk sales of 15 or more books. In some instances,
Wright's staff informed various groups Wright spoke to that because
he had already reached the maximum limit on outside earned income
for that year, he would not be able to keep an honoraium offered to
him. The staff then recommended that instead of paying Wright an
honorarium, the organization could purchase books for the same
amount.
   For example, Wright gave a lecture in October 1984 at Southwest
Texas State University. The University paid Wright an honorarium of
$3,000 in addition to his expenses, but was subsequently informed
by Wright's staff that he would be unable to accept the honorarium.
Wright's staff suggested that the University purchase 504 books for
$3,000 in lieu of the honorarium. The University purchased the
books and distributed most of them to students in its political
science department. Wright endorsed the $3,000 check over to
Madison Publishing Company. Despite the change in the nature of the
transaction, the University's records plainly list the $3,000
expenditure as an honorarium for Wright's appearance. Instead of
passing up $3,000 or donating it to charity, Wright thus received a
$1,650 ``royalty'' for his lecture at the University.
   Wright also spoke at a Satellite Broadcasting and Communications
Association (``SBCA'') trade show in September 1985 just several
weeks after SBCA had purchased 1,680 copies of ``Reflections of a
Public Man'' for $10,000. SBCA testified that although it
historically has paid honoraria and expenses to congressmen for
their appearances, in this case SBCA's legal counsel, who arranged
for Wright to speak at the trade show, suggested that SBCA purchase
the books instead. Thus Wright received a $5,500 ``royalty'' for
his appearance before the SBCA.
   Not all bulk sales were in lieu of honoraria. For example,
Carlos Moore arranged a sale of 2,000 books to the Teamsters for
$12,200 paid out of the DRIVE Political Fund. The books were
distributed to Teamster members. Wright had not spoken at any
Teamster event.
   In addition, S. Gene Payte, a Fort Worth real estate developer,
testified that he wanted to give Wright a $5,000 gift and, in fact,
had given a $5,000 check to Betty Wright. Wright subsequently
informed him that he could not accept the gift and returned the
check to Payte. Payte continued to search for a way to give cash to
Wright and shortly after receiving the first check back from
Wright, wrote a second $5,000 check, this time to Madison Systems
for ``revision and distribution of Wright's books.'' Payte
testified that he expected to receive 1,000 copies of the revised
edition of the book and, in fact, he made a second payment of
$1,000 when he realized that $5,000 would not buy 1,000 copies of
the $5.95 book. However, the book was never revised. Payte
testified he received approximately 300 to 500 copies of the old
book instead. No further accounting was made.
</TEXT>
