<DOCNO> AP890417-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls     04-17 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Takes Up S&amp;L Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Senate opened debate Monday on
President Bush's slightly altered plan for bailing out savings and
loan depositors, Republicans blamed House Democrats for the bulk of
costs.
   ``There's enough blame to go around, but if you want to single
out one culprit, it's the House of Representatives,'' said Sen.
Jake Garn of Utah, the ranking Republican on the Senate Banking
Committee.
   Garn said the bailout costs _ estimated at a minimum of $157
billion over the next 10 years _ would be only half as much if in
1986, the Democratic-controlled House had gone along with a
Senate-approved measure to pump $15 billion into the S&amp;L insurance
funds to close insolvent thrifts then.
   ``The kindest thing I can say about the House is only that it is
totally irresponsible,'' Garn said, referring to action last week
by a House subcommittee that would require S&amp;L owners to put up
less of their own money to stay in business.
   Former S&amp;L regulators have blamed Democratic House Speaker Jim
Wright of Texas for stalling the 1986 legislation on behalf of
thrift operators in his state.
   The House Ethics Committee on Monday cleared Wright of charges
he improperly intervened with S&amp;L regulators but concluded that
there is ``reason to believe'' Wright violated official rules of
conduct 69 times by not disclosing thousands of dollars in alleged
gifts.
   Senate Banking Committee Chairman Don Riegle, D-Mich., said
state chartered thrifts in Texas and California accounted for 70
percent of the $38 billion the government committed last year to
resolve thrift problems.
   ``I don't think we can let irresponsible state legislatures hold
the key to federal deposit insurance funds,'' he said, referring to
changes his committee made in Bush's plan to put more restrictions
on state-chartered S&amp;Ls.
   Riegle said the legislation ``breaks up the close relationship
between the thrift industry and its regulators'' while assuring the
survival of most S&amp;Ls as the originator of half of the nation's
home mortgages.
   But he said ``there is no certain guarantee that this plan or
any plan will work as intended'' and conceded that taxpayers may be
asked again in the future to come up with more money.
   ``We can say that this package is the soundest and the toughest
we could put together within the time bounds given us,'' he said,
referring to the seven weeks since the package was put forth by the
White House.
   Both Riegle and Garn, as well as other members from both parties
on the banking committee, pleaded with their colleagues to forego
offering amendments to the 564-page bill.
   ``We may have a long fight ahead with the House,'' Garn said.
``Extraneous and controversial amendments would upset the delicate
balance we've reached.''
   However, several amendments were in the works, according to
Senate aides, although none were offered or voted on Monday.
   Among them was one by Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., that would
stretch out to June 1994, Bush's June 1991 deadline for small S&amp;L
operators with loans of less than $100 million to effectively
double the amount of their own money at risk.
   Pressler complained the bill provides ``a heavy advantage toward
larger institutions'' by allowing them to stretch out to as long as
25 years good-will exemptions from the capital requirements.
   A spokeswoman for Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said he is
considering proposing a variety of pro-consumer amendments .
   Other possible amendments include:
   _Reinstating a funding plan authored by Riegle, who claims it
would save $150 million a year. Riegle effectively abandoned the
plan last week under a veto threat by Bush but Majority Leader
George Mitchell said he assumes it will consume ``considerable
debate'' over the next two days.
   _Giving non-profit groups and local housing agencies a 90-day
right of first refusal to purchase at ``appraised market prices''
residential property that has fallen into the government's hand
through loan defaults to insolvent S&amp;Ls. The amendment by Sen. John
Kerry, D-Mass., was defeated in the Banking Committee, where it was
criticized by Sen. Phil Gramm, D-Texas, as ``social engineering.''
   Meanwhile, three consumers groups _ the Consumer Federation of
America, Consumers Union and Association of Community Organizations
for Reform Now _ on Monday criticized both the Senate and House
versions of the S&amp;L bill.
   ``Last week the banking committees led us down a primrose path
that threatens to end in another nightmare of S&amp;L insolvencies and
enormous public debt,'' said Peggy Miller, a CFA lobbyist. ``What
you have to concentrate on is the loopholes, because they're broad
... and easily used.''
</TEXT>
