<FIRST>r w AM-WoodExports-Japan     04-17 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wood Exports-Japan,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Report Sees Unfair Trade Barriers by Japanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oregon lawmakers said Monday that a draft
Commerce Department report on Japanese barriers to imports of
American wood products should bolster the case for U.S. sanctions.
   The draft report, obtained Monday, says Japan uses unfair trade
practices, including high tariffs, subisidies and even building
codes that require the use of nails that can crack American
plywood, to protect their mills from U.S. imports.
   The report said Japanese tariffs and other barriers were
designed to bolster imports of raw logs and discourage imports of
finished products.
   Despite earlier progress in opening some parts of the Japanese
market, the report said barriers remain which impede U.S. imports,
and it said the government of Japan has refused to enter into a new
round of talks.
   The report said ``it is unlikely that any further concessions
will be forthcoming unless additional U.S. efforts are made. Such
concessions would only be obtained if there were a clear incentive
or at the least inclusion of these barriers in the high priority of
issues to be resolved by the U.S. and Japanese governments.''
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., who requested the study more than a
year ago, said it should bolster the case for imposing trade
sanctions against Japan unless the barriers are removed.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who had earlier called for sanctions,
said in a letter to U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills the
report ``strongly supports'' a need for aggressive action by the
administration.
   Last month, the National Forest Products Association asked Hills
to rule the Japanese were engaging in unfair trade practices
involving forest products and, if negotiations failed to resolve
the dispute after 18 months, to impose sanctions.
   The association has estimated that exports of finished U.S.
forest products to Japan could increase $1.2 billion annually if
the barriers were lifted.
</TEXT>
