<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0669 04-17 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0669,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lethal Barrages Pound Beirut, Surrounding Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with more killed, injured, MOVES
UP casualty count since renewed fighting broke out. Pick up 5th pvs, `Tens
of ...' DELETES 19th graf, `Police put ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents sought shelter Monday in
basements and bunkers during citywide shelling that killed at least
45 people in three days and touched off international appeals for a
cease-fire.
   The rocket and artillery barrages slammed into both the
Christian and Moslem sectors during intensified fighting in and
around Beirut between Christian army units and an alliance of Druse
militiamen and Syrian troops.
   The dead included Spain's ambassador to Lebanon, Pedro Manuel De
Aristegui, and his father-in-law, prominent Lebanese poet Tewfic
Youssef Awwad. Warrant Officer Youssef Bitar, the Lebanese army's
top explosives specialist, said on Christian-controlled Voice of
Lebanon radio the ambassador's residence was hit by a Syrian shell.
   Police also said 175 people were wounded in renewed bombardments
that broke out late Saturday.
   Police put the toll in 41 days of fighting at 262 killed and 932
wounded. The overwhelming majority of the victims have been
civilians.
   Tens of thousands of Beirut residents had hardly emerged from
their shelters Monday morning during a brief lull when guns and
rocket launchers thundered back into action, sending them back
underground. Many were trapped without water or electricity.
   Smoldering cars lay charred Monday in streets littered with
glass shards and severed power cables. Hundreds of fashionable
boutiques were gutted.
   Many buildings burned down because firefighters had no water.
   Only a few bakeries opened Monday morning, but there was not
enough bread to go around.
   ``Please, please. I need five loaves. I have five children that
I have to feed,'' shouted housewife Amina Shehab outside a bakery
in Moslem west Beirut.
   The baker yelled back: ``I've less than three dozen loaves, and
there are many other people who want to eat as well. I can only
give you two loaves.''
   ``Lebanon's apocalypse persists,'' Beirut's independent daily
An-Nahar said in a front-page editorial Monday.
   The prime minister of the Moslem Cabinet in the split
government, Salim Hoss, said Monday he reached agreement with
French Humanitarian Assistance Minister Bernard Kouchner to
evacuate more wounded civilians.
   A source close to Hoss later said Moslem victims of the fighting
would be evacuated to a French hospital ship on Tuesday if security
conditions permit.
   Fourteen Christian victims were ferried to a French boat from
the Christian port of Jounieh on Friday.
   The United States, Kuwait, Jordan, Pope John Paul II appealed
for an end to the confrontation, which has developed into one of
the bloodiest rounds of the 14-year-old civil war.
   Pope John Paul II urged the United Nations and Arab League
nations to use their influence to bring about an immediate
cease-fire.
   In Washington, State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher
said, ``All parties, including Syria, which is a direct participant
in the artillery exchanges ... must stop the fighting.''
   Kuwait's foreign minister, Sheik Sabah Ahmed Sabah, called for
an emergency Arab League council meeting.
   The battles began after Gen. Michel Aoun, the head of the
Christian Cabinet, ordered his forces to blockade several ports
controlled by Moslem militiamen. Syria rallied to the militiamens'
aid, and Aoun pledged to expel the estimated 40,000 Syrian troops
from Lebanon.
   The Arab League invited Syria to send in its forces as
peacekeepers in 1976.
   Aoun, in an interview released Monday, accused the United States
of covering up for Syrian attacks in Lebanon.
   ``The United States is undoubtedly trying to solve the
Palestinian-Israeli or the Arab-Israeli problem at Lebanon's
expense and is thus sponsoring this dirty Syrian role in Lebanon,''
he was quoted as saying by the London-based newsletter Middle East
Mirror. Text of the interview was sent by telex to The Associated
Press in Bahrain.
   Aoun said U.S. officials were trying to portray Lebanese strife
as a problem between Moslems and Christians, but he said it is
caused by occupation by Syrian and Israeli forces, according to the
interview.
   Israel occupies a self-proclaimed ``security zone'' up to 10
miles deep in south Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
