<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Protest     04-17 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Protest,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Reported Killed in Fundmentalist Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was reported killed Monday during a
demonstration by several thousand supporters of the fundamentalist
National Islamic Front against the suspension of Islamic law in
Sudan.
   Spokesmen for the front identified the victim as Shayk Rayeh
Mahmoud, but did not give details or accuse anyone in his death.
   As they marched through central Khartoum, protesters chanted:
``There is no God but Allah! There is no alternative to Sharia
(Islamic law)! ''
   It was the fourth day of demonstrations, which began after
Parliament voted to postpone debate on Sharia, or Islamic law,
until a national constitutional conference convenes.
   The conference is to assemble all political forces, including
the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army, and one of its purposes
is to find a solution to the 6-year-old civil war in the south.
   Suspending Islamic law, which President Gaafar Nimeiri put into
effect two years before he was overthrown in 1985, has been a major
demand by the south. Most people there are Christians or animists,
while Khartoum and the rest of the north is overwhelmingly Moslem.
   Ali Osman Taha, the National Islamic Front's leader in
Parliament, told the marchers Monday: ``Demonstrations will
continue day and night until this government of traitors ...
non-believers is toppled.
   ``You have come out to tell them there are sharp swords ready to
defend the Sharia of Allah.''
   Riot police did not interfere, although the protests violate an
Interior Ministry ban on demonstrations.
   Interior Minister Mubarak Abdullah Fadil Mahdi said in a
statement later, however, that security forces would use force if
necessary to end unauthorized protests.
   Mahdi said two demonstrators were injured in addition to the one
killed, but did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
