<FIRST>r w AM-House-HatchAct     04-17 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House-Hatch Act,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Hatch Act Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House gave overwhelming approval Monday to
a measure that would repeal major portions of the Hatch Act and
allow federal Civil Service employees to participate in partisan
political activity on their own time.
   But despite the 297-90 House vote, final enactment into law is
far from certain.
   The House approved an almost identical bill last year, but it
died in the Senate.
   The administration is opposed to the bill and Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh has said he will recommend a veto should it reach
President Bush's desk.
   Nonetheless, the measure was pushed strongly by various unions
representing federal workers and their leaders were quick to praise
the House members who voted for it.
   ``This is not a political party issue ... it's a political
freedom issue,'' said Robert M. Tobias, president of the National
Treasury Employees Union. ``We urge the Senate to join the House in
standing firmly on the side of rights for federal workers.''
   However, Tobias' statement did not suggest there was anything
more than an ``excellent possibility'' the measure will pass the
Senate.
   The bill would:
   _Allow federal employees to run for partisan political office on
their own time, without taking a leave of absence unless
campaigning would interfere with performance of their duties.
   _Permit employees to request unpaid leave to run for office and
says leave must be granted unless the agency they work for
determines they cannot be spared.
   _Allow federal employees to manage political campaigns and raise
campaign money during off-duty hours.
   The measure would clarify and, in many cases, strengthen current
Hatch Act prohibitions against using a federal position for
political purposes.
   In a letter to Congress, Thornburgh said enactment of provisions
in the House will ``would lead to a tragic repoliticization of the
federal workforce.''
   Aside from concerns about specifics of the bill, wrote
Thornburgh, the overall effect on public perception of the fairness
of government dealing ``might well be devastaging.''
   ``For example, if it appears that a candidate of Party A has
misappropirated funds, it will not inspire confidence to learn that
the local U.S. attorney's office charged with investigating the
allegation is headed by that candidate's campaign manager,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
