<DOCNO> AP890417-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-Wright-Phelan 3rdadd   04-17 0816</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wright-Phelan, 3rd add,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: was made.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Some bulk purchasers did not even want the books they paid for.
For example, Wright addressed the annual meeting of the
Mid-Continent Oil &amp; Gas Association. Mid-Continent purchased $1,000
worth of Wright's book in lieu of paying him an honorarium, but
asked to receive only three books. Mid-Continent suggested that the
remaining books be distributed to libraries and other public
institutions of Wright's choice. There are no records reflecting
the requested distribution.
   The Select Committee on Ethics interpreted Rule XLVII, clause 1
in Advisory Opinion No. 13 which makes it clear that the
limitations on outside earned income may not be avoided by the mere
characterization of a payment. ``In all cases, the real facts will
control.'' (Select Committee on Ethics, Advisory Opinion No. 13,
Ethics Manual p. 179.) In this case, the facts reveal that Wright
compiled a series of previous speeches and writings into a
commercially unpublishable manuscript. His good friend Carlos Moore
formed a publishing company for the purpose of producing the book
and entering into a so-called ``royalty'' agreement inordinately
favorable to Wright. Together they sold the book almost exclusively
to lobbyists, persons interested in legislation and other interest
groups in order to provide income to Wright.
   The resulting income does not therefore become ``royalty''
income just because Moore calls himself a ``publisher'' and claims
to pay ``royalties'' on book sales. The ``royalty'' contract was
not an arms-length agreement between an author and his publisher,
but a joint business venture _ a means by which Moore could help
his friend Wright obtain money in excess of congressional
limitations.
   Receipts from sales of Wright's book should thus be
characterized as outside earned income, not copyright royalties,
and subject to the limits and reporting requirements for such
income. As Advisory Opinion No. 13 makes clear, income a member
earns through his own personal efforts is earned income for
purposes of Rule XLVII, clause 1 even when the income is first paid
to a corporation and then distributed to the member. In this
matter, Wright earned income from the books through his performance
of publisher's duties including the marketing of the book.
   However, whether or not the income from sales of the book may be
considered ``royalties,'' when books are allegedly ``sold'' to
lobbyists or interest groups, but no books are delivered to those
groups in exchange for their payments, the books retained are
``gifts'' received from persons with an interest in legislation
before Congress. Those books are also ``gifts'' when the group
``donates'' the books to a library or institution of Wright's
choice.
   Furthermore, where the books are purchased in lieu of paying a
customary fee for a speech or appearance, the payment received is
an ``honorarium,'' in the form of a ``royalty.'' The term
``honorarium'' is defined to mean ``the payment of something of
value `accepted as consideration for an appearance, speech, or
article.''' (Ethics manual, p. 83, quoting 11 C.F.R. 110.12(b); see
also 2 U.S.C. 31-1.) In this case, the ``royalty'' was itself the
honorarium paid for Wright's appearance.
   Thus as discussed in full in Section III. C. of this Report,
Wright's receipts of outside earned income, including honoraria, in
excess of 30 percent of his congressional salary are violations of
House Rule XLVII, clause 1. In addition, gifts exceeding $100 from
lobbyists and other groups with interests in legislation before
Congress are violations of House rule XLIII, clause 4. Wright's
receipt of an honorarium in excess of the $2,000 limit imposed by 2
U.S.C. 441i is a violation of that law. Finally, his failures to
disclose the receipts of income, gifts and honoraria are violations
of House Rule XLIV.
   We found no evidence that campaign funds were used to produce
the book.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>D. Wright's Use of Government Resources to Produce and Market ``Reflections
of a Public Man''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Wright used members of his staff to compile, type, proofread,
edit, and market his book, ``Reflections of a Public Man.'' The
book was Wright's own project, from which he personally received
income.
   Matthew Cossolotto, a writer and researcher on Wright's staff,
testified that he spent about 200 hours preparing the book for
printing. Other members of the staff had more limited roles in the
preparation of the book, e.g., Marshall Lynam, Wright's Chief of
Staff, solicited the quotes for the back cover of the book and also
participated to some extent in marketing the book; Charmayne Marsh,
Wright's Press Secretary, helped to select the photograph used on
the cover of the book; Mike Grisso occasionally entered passages
for the book onto the word processor; Dorothy Biard, the office
librarian, assisted in gathering and locating material; and Cathy
Mitchell, Wright's Executive Assistant and Scheduler, also
participated in marketing the book to various groups Wright gave
speeches to in 1984 and 1985. In addition, Wright used other
government resources, including a computer, to complete the
manuscript.
</TEXT>
