<FIRST>r i AM-SoccerViolence     04-17 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soccer Violence,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Algeria Suspends Games After Goalie Stabbed, 18 East Germans Reported
Hurt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stadium Disaster, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Algeria has ordered all soccer matches
suspended for a week following the stabbing of a goalie by fans
during a riot last week, officials said.
   In East Germany, a newspaper reported Monday that 18 people were
injured on April 7 when thousands of fans made a rush for tickets
to a soccer match.
   The reports followed the deaths of 94 British fans during a mad
rush Saturday at a soccer match in Sheffield, England.
   The president of the Algerian Football Federation, Mohamed
Baghdadi, said matches were suspended Saturday and would not resume
for a week. The statement Sunday came in response to violence at a
match the day before between Constantine and Setif that left two
players injured.
   Setif goalie Antar Osmani was circled by about 100 fans and then
stabbed in the abdomen. He said he had never seen ``such savagery''
during his 14-year career.
   It was not clear why Osmani was attacked.
   Baghdadi said the suspension should be used for ``meditation,
consciousness-raising and a call to responsibility.''
   In Berlin, the government-run newspaper Young World said fans
were injured during a run on tickets April 7 for a Union of
European Football Associations semifinal game between the Dynamo
Dresden soccer club and Stuttgart of West Germany.
   The newspaper printed a letter by students of Dresden's
Technical University, which said the ticket sale began suddenly
around midnight, causing ``chaotic conditions.''
   It also printed a reply by Peter Stehr, security chief for the
Dresden club, which said 18 people were hurt.
   Stehr's letter said the injuries were caused by ``inconsiderate
behavior and by the pushing and shoving of the unreasonable
(fans).'' He said the club also would revise the way it sold
tickets.
   The newspaper earlier reported that some fans had been camping
for two days for tickets to Wednesday's game.
   The students' letter said the box offices ``opened suddenly and
prematurely,'' suggesting that the injuries were caused by a crush
of thousands of fans trying to get into the line when officials
began selling tickets eight hours ahead of the announced time.
   All 38,000 tickets were sold by the morning, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
