<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary-Israel     04-17 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Israel,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Makes Unannounced Visit to Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
made an unannounced visit to Hungary, and Israel radio reported the
two countries apparently planned to renew diplomatic ties.
   A one-sentence announcement by the official Hungarian news
agency MTI said Shamir arrived in Budapest. It did not specify
whether the visit was private or official and gave no other details.
   In Jerusalem, a Shamir aide confirmed the rare unannnounced trip
and said the prime minister is due back on Tuesday. He refused to
elaborate on the purpose of the visit.
   The visit was not announced in Israel before the midnight Israel
radio report, which said the two nations apparently planned to
renew diplomatic ties. The report did not elaborate.
   Hungary would be the first East European nation to resume full
ties with Israel since all Soviet bloc nations except Romania broke
relations during the Middle East War in 1967.
   
   Shamir was accompanied to Hungary by Justice Minister Dan
Meridor, Israeli officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Shamir made what was billed as a private visit to Budapest in
September when he met with Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz.
Upon his return, he announced Budapest had agreed to renew full
diplomatic ties with Israel.
   Premier Miklos Nemeth has said he expected full diplomatic
relations to be restored between the two countries by June.
   Earlier Monday, the Israeli Foreign Ministry announced that
Hungarian and Israeli officials had set up two joint committees to
improve commercial ties between the two countries as a step toward
normalizing diplomatic relations.
   This was agreed during a four-day visit to Israel by Hungary's
deputy foreign minister, Laszlo Kovacs, which ended Sunday.
   Kovacs said last week that Hungary would like to ``accelerate''
the process of normalizing relations.
</TEXT>
