<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bartholomew-Hostages     04-17 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bartholomew-Hostages,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Choice Says He Wasn't Involved in Iran-Contra</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reginald Bartholomew, who was U.S. ambassador
to Lebanon in 1985 when U.S. arms were exchanged for the release of
an American hostage, told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on
Monday he knew ``precious little'' about the operation.
   Bartholomew, President Bush's choice for undersecretary of state
for security affairs, said that in September 1985, he was directed
by the National Security Council to make arrangements to receive a
hostage and get him out of Lebanon quickly and safely.
   On Sept. 14, 1985 a group of pro-Iranian Lebanese extremists
released the Rev. Benjamin Wier, one of six American hostages then
being held in Lebanon.
   Bartholomew said he reported the NSC directive to the State
Department and made the requested logistical arrangements.
   But he said he was not told, and did not know, that Wier was
released in exchange for Israeli shipments to Iran of 508 U.S.-made
TOW antitank missiles.
   And he said he also did not know that Oliver L. North, then a
Marine lieutenant colonel attached to the NSC staff, had visited
Beirut.
   ``If Oliver North was in Beirut when I was there as ambassador,
I did not know it,'' Bartholomew said. ``I knew precious little
about the organization of the whole affair or who was involved.''
   ``I was not involved in Iran-Contra in any way,'' Bartholomew
said.
   Bartholomew was interviewed in private but was never called as a
public witness during the various investigations into the
Iran-Contra affair.
   Bartholomew, 53, has served in a number of State Department
policy positions. He has been U.S. ambassador to Spain since 1986.
   The Foreign Relations Committee is expected to recommend Senate
confirmation of the Bartholomew nomination, with final action
likely later this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
