<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     04-17 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Militants Kill Four Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese militants detonated
explosives buried in the road and blew up an army truck on Monday
in southeast Sri Lanka, killing four soldiers and wounding eight,
government officials said.
   The vehicle was on patrol in Embilipitiya, 80 miles southeast of
Colombo, reported the officials, who cannot be identified under
briefing rules.
   They said an attacker was killed during a raid by Sinhalese
extremists on a police station in Kurunagala district, 85 miles
northeast of Colombo.
   The violence came one day before expiration of a one-week
cease-fire announced by President Ranasinghe Premadasa.
   The truce was part of a peace package the government offered to
Sinhalese and Tamil extremists in a bid to end six years of ethnic
violence that has claimed at least 12,600 lives.
   Left-wing Sinhalese militants rejected the offer, but the
largest Tamil militant group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam,
agreed on Saturday to hold talks with the government.
   Premadasa asked the Tamil rebels to pick a team for talks aimed
at ending their campaign for a separate Tamil homeland.
   The Tamil acceptance came after at least 100 people died last
week in attacks that were blamed on the rebels.
   The Tamils, most of them Hindus, comprise 18 percent of this
island nation's 16 million people. The Tamils began the separatist
campaign in 1983, saying the majority Sinhalese discriminated
against them in jobs and education.
   Sinhalese, mostly Buddhists, make up 75 percent of the
population and control the government and the military.
   The Tamil Tigers rejected an India-sponsored July 1987 accord
that gave Tamils limited autonomy, complaining it did not meet
their demands for self-rule.
   Sri Lanka lies just south of the Indian peninsula in the Indian
Ocean. India became involved because its own 60 million Tamils were
sympathetic to the rebel cause.
   The accord triggered a violent Sinhalese backlash. Sinhalese
extremists, who belong to the Marxist People's Liberation Front,
said the agreement conceded too much to the Tamils and vowed to
kill anyone who supported it.
   The Front has been blamed for more than 2,500 political killings
since January. Most of the victims were government officials and
security personnel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
