<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0655 04-17 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0655,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Troops Kill Two Teen-Agers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with a fourth death, Shamir quotes,
human rights appeal. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab reports said Israeli soldiers killed two
teen-agers Monday, the latest victims in a surge of violence that
has cost the lives of 12 Palestinians in the occupied territories
in five days.
   Rafideh Khalili Ahmad Abu Laban, 13, and Kayed Mousa Salama, 14,
were shot to death in stone-throwing protests during funerals for
earlier victims, the reports said. Ms. Laban was killed in the
occupied West Bank and Salama in the Gaza Strip.
   A third Palestinian was electrocuted Monday when he climbed a
power pole and tried to raise an outlawed Palestinian flag, and a
fourth died of earlier injuries.
   Hospital officials said a 50-year-old woman of a family named
Ayat in Jerusalem's Zeytoun district was killed by a bullet through
the heart and a male member of the family, aged betweem 25 and 30,
also was killed.
   A young woman in her 20s was reported in serious condition and
two children aged 2 and 12 also were reported wounded.
   No further details were given and circumstances of the shooting
were unclear. The army said there was no army activity or gunfire
in Zeytoun.
   Arab sources said 10 Palestinians were wounded in other clashes.
Two Israelis were reported injured in scattered stoning incidents
in the West Bank.
   Jewish settlers in a tiny enclave in the West Bank city of
Hebron said they were creating a mobile armed militia and using
attack dogs to defend their houses against Arab stonings.
   ``We've decided to create a trained group of people that would
not interfere with the army but will reach troublesome spots and
help defend Jewish houses in Hebron,'' settler leader Aharon Domb
said on Israel radio. ``We'll also secure Jewish houses by using
guard and attack dogs, to be unleashed only in emergency
situations.''
   In Jerusalem, a Palestinian human rights group appealed to the
United States and the European Community to urge an independent
investigation of the killings of four Palestinians during a border
police raid last week on Nahalin, a West Bank village.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir rejected Palestinian demands for
at least a partial army withdrawal as a condition for agreeing to
elections in the occupied lands.
   ``There is nothing to talk about regarding changes in the
deployment of Israeli army forces,'' Shamir said on army radio.
``This deployment is necessary to maintain order, and order is
necessary for elections.''
   Radio reports said Shamir went before a parliamentary committee
Monday and defended his election plan against critics in his own
right-wing Likud bloc who said elections could be the first step to
creating a Palestinian state. Shamir proposes the elections to
choose Palestinians to negotiate with Israel.
   ``I will talk, and discuss, and argue with my friends. I hope
I'll convince them that although these doubts have some basis ...
we can overcome such things,'' the prime minister said on Israel
television.
   ``If those implementing the plan decide that there will be no
Palestinian state here, I'm saying there will be no Palestinian
state.''
   Shamir told the committee Palestinian election candidates would
have to agree to certain limits in advance, including rejecting a
Palestinian state, Israel radio said.
   He also said he opposes international supervision of the vote.
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat on Sunday demanded such supervision and
the withdrawal of Israeli troops as a condition for elections.
Palestinians in the occupied lands hinted a partial withdrawal
would be a step toward the polls.
   On Monday, soldiers fired as hundreds of Arab youths threw
stones, waved outlawed Palestinian flags and set tires ablaze
during a funeral procession in Dheishe refugee camp near the West
Bank town of Bethlehem, Arab reports said.
   Ms. Laban was shot in the forehead and died en route to a
hospital, the reports said.
   In Jabaliya refugee camp in the Gaza Strip, troops fired on
stone-throwing youths after the funeral of a 50-year-old man who
died earlier Monday, reportedly from a beating by soldiers, Arab
witnesses said.
   Salama died at Gaza City's Shifa Hospital after a bullet sliced
an artery in his leg, hospital officials said.
   In the Gaza village of Bani Suheila, 21-year-old Mahmoud Shihada
Abu-Shad was electrocuted while trying to display a Palestinian
flag, Arab reports said.
   The army confirmed the death of 50-year-old Faris Said Falha
without commenting on the cause.
   An official at Mukassed Hospital in east Jerusalem said Falha
died of spinal injuries after troops beat him on March 27.
   At least 438 Palestinians have been killed killed in the
16-month-old uprising. Eighteen Israelis have also died.
</TEXT>
