<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-GreekLibel     04-17 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greek Libel,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papandreou Takes Time Magazine to Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek Premier Andreas Papandreou filed a libel
lawsuit Monday accusing Time magazine of defaming him in a story
that suggested he took millions of dollars in payoffs, his American
lawyer said.
   The lawsuit was announced here by lawyer Leonard Boudin, who
said the lawsuit was filed in London because the story was more
damaging abroad than in the United States.
   He conceded, however, that another factor was that it is easier
for a public figure to make a case under English libel law than
under American.
   The Time story, which concerned allegations of financial
wrongdoing at a Greek bank that have rocked the Papandreou
government since last fall, was on the cover of the magazine's
March 13 international edition. A similar story ran in the U.S.
edition, but it was not the cover story.
   The articles quoted former Greek bank president George Koskotas,
who is jailed in Massachusetts and fighting extradition to Greece,
as saying he passed millions from the Bank of Crete to Papandreou
and other figures in the premier's Socialist government.
   Papandreou has been Greece's premier since 1981. His government
is up for re-election in June, but the banking scandal and the
70-year premier's open affair with a 34-year-old former airline
stewardess have hurt his standing among voters, according to recent
polls.
   Papandreou has denounced the Time article as part of an
international conspiracy to topple his government.
   Boudin said Papandreou would ask for ``a considerable,
reasonable sum'' in damages from Time, but said the amount hasn't
been decided. He said clearing Papandreou's name was the main
reason for the lawsuit, launched only after Time failed to respond
to a demand for an public apology and retraction.
   Time promised in a statement to ``vigorously defend'' itself.
   ``What is most alarming about the announcement of this lawsuit
is the inescapable conclusion that Prime Minister Papandreou is
suing the messenger because he wishes to discredit the message,''
the magazine said in a statement.
   ``Such a suit, just by being brought, disregards a central role
of the press in a free, democratic society _ which is to make
important information available to the public. Time magazine will
take whatever steps are necessary to fight the allegations of this
lawsuit and defend its right to report news and information it
deems in the public interest,'' the statement said.
   Boudin said he could not recall another case in which a head of
state sued for libel, although there have been a number of cases
brought by highly placed public figures in recent years, including
the lawsuit filed against Time by Ariel Sharon, the former Israeli
defense minister.
   In that case, a New York jury found in 1985 that Time had erred
but had not acted with malice and therefore did not have to pay
damages.
   In England, Papandreou need only show that the story written
about him was defamatory and injured his reputation, while the
magazine has the task of proving that what it wrote was true,
Boudin said. In the United States, Papandreou would have to show
not only that Time wrote untruths but that it acted with malice.
   Besides New York-based Time, the lawsuit filed in London names
as defendants Time-Life branches in London and Amsterdam, and the
writer of the article, Robert Ajemian.
   Time wrote that Papandreou had refused to be interviewed or to
answer questions the magazine submitted before publishing the
article. But Boudin countered that the questions were of a general
sort about government integrity and not about any specific
accusations of wrongdoing by Papandreou.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
