<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-17 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow In Montana, Thunderstorms In The Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Western Montana got at least 4 inches of spring snow Monday as
showers and thunderstorms fell across the Midwest ahead of a cold
front that dropped temperatures 12 degrees in an hour.
   Showers and thunderstorms fell from Michigan to Indiana,
Illinois, Missouri and Arkansas. In northern Indiana, thunderstorms
produced hail a quarter-inch in diameter near Gary, South Bend and
Mentone.
   Montana's morning snowstorm dropped 2 inches of snow in an hour
in the capital of Helena. Four inches fell in Missoula in six hours.
   The cold front brought sharply cooler weather to the upper
Mississippi Valley and the northern and central Plains.
   Temperatures Monday afternoon were about 30 degrees lower than
at the same time Sunday from northern Wisconsin and Minnesota to
western Nebraska and northwest Kansas. In North Platte, Neb., the
temperature was 37 degrees at 1 p.m., compared to 72 degrees Sunday.
   As the front moved through Chicago, generating winds off chilly
Lake Michigan, the temperature fell from 60 degrees to 48 degrees
in an hour.
   In contrast, warm air pushing eastward raised temperatures in
the central Rockies.
   The mercury jumped from 49 degrees to 61 in an hour in Casper,
Wyo. At 1 p.m., it was 70 in Craig, Colo., and 43 in Cheyenne,
Wyo., which remained in the cooler air.
   Scattered thunderstorms fell in southern Florida. While sunshine
prevailed along the West Coast, the central and southern coast of
California were cloudy.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27
degrees at International Falls, Minn., to 93 degrees at Midland,
Texas.
   The forecast for Tuesday called for showers and scattered
thunderstorms from northeast Texas and southeast Oklahoma to
Arkansas, Tennessee, Kentucky and the central and southern
Appalachians; rain showers in the middle and northern Atlantic
Coast states; and scattered showers and thunderstorms in central
and southern Florida.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s and 50s from North
Dakota to the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and New
England; the 80s from inland California to much of Texas and New
Mexico and the Gulf Coast states; the 90s in southwest Texas; the
90s to near 100 degrees in the desert Southwest and in the 60s and
70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
