<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     04-17 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rightist Party to Create Information Agency on Rebel Activity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Francisco
Merino said Monday leftist rebels are ``the only generators of
violence'' in El Salvador and his rightist party is forming an
agency to keep track of them.
   He was asked if abductions and killings of leftists by
right-wing groups constituted terrorism and he said: ``Not that I
know of, because there is no extreme right.''
   Merino of the Republican Nationalist Alliance, known as Arena,
blamed rebels for a bomb attack on his home Friday that caused
extensive damage and slightly injured a nephew.
   Merino and his wife Maria Antonieta were not at home at the time
of the bombing. Four children and two other nephews in the house
were not harmed.
   Merino and President-elect Alfredo Cristiani of Arena won the
March 19 election, defeating the centrist Christian Democrats, and
are to be inaugurated June 1 for five-year terms.
   At a news conference Monday, Merino gave the names, addresses
and workplaces of eight people he said belonged to the guerrilla
cell that attacked his home. He said the information came from a
rebel who was captured and interrogated by police but released for
lack of evidence of involvement in the bombing.
   Police have not arrested the eight people he named ``because of
an excess of work, for lack of resources or for lack of will,''
Merino said.
   He said Arena was forming an intelligence service to receive
information from citizens about activities of the rebel alliance,
the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front.
   ``Our party, our local headquarters and our leaders will receive
in confidentiality'' all the information and pass it on to ``the
armed forces, the police and judicial authorities, according to the
case,'' he said.
   ``People should go before our local leaders and tell them of
these cases,'' he added. ``The members of our organization meet
frequently and this way we can elaborate a more complete picture''
of the rebel movement ``so the people play a more active role in
imposing order.''
   Arena was founded in 1981 as an anti-communist group.
International human rights organizations and the U.S. government
linked party leaders, some of whom remain active, to rightist death
squads that killed thousands of people in the early 1980s.
   The party denies any connection with death squads and Cristiani
did not join the party until 1985.
   Merino said Arena would be only a conduit for citizen reports
and would not take follow-up action on its own.
   He said ``security forces would definitely be the ones to take
appropriate action. Arena is a civilian institution. We do not have
the capacity to counter the military action of these groups.''
   Merino called the guerrillas ``the only generators of violence
in El Salvador'' and added: ``If we can minimize the terrorists'
action, the level of violence, of victims, will tend to diminish.''
   Leftist rebels began their battle for power nine years ago. More
than 70,000 Salvadorans have been killed and most of the victims
were civilians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
