<FIRST>u w BC-Wright-Phelan 6thadd   04-17 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wright-Phelan, 6th add,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: from Mallick.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   During the 1979 through 1984 period that Mrs. Wright was on the
payroll of Mallick Properties, Inc. and Mallightco, she and her
husband also received free housing from Mallick just steps away
from his office in Fort Worth. Mallick testified that housing was
provided, not as a part of compensation, but because it was
convenient for him to have Mrs. Wright living only a few feet away
from his office. Mallick could not explain why her job required her
to be so close to his office. In fact, much of her work for Mallick
Properties was done in Austin and San Antonio. Moreover, throughout
her employment with Mallick, Mrs. Wright lived primarily in
Washington, D.C., spending on the average only one week a month in
Fort Worth. Thus her consulting jobs plainly were not jobs
requiring her to be close to the office. The free housing was thus
not job related, but a gift from Mallick.
   Beginning in 1985, the Wrights began paying rent for the housing
Mallick provided. The rent was determined by dividing the fair
monthly rental of the apartment, $650, by 30, the average number of
days in a month. The Wrights were charged $21.67 (or sometimes
$21.00 or $21.50) for each day they personally occupied the
apartment notwithstanding the fact that since their furniture and
personal belongings occupied the apartment every day, they had
constructive possession of the apartment daily. Thus in 1985, the
Wrights paid rent of $881.50 for the equivalent of 41 days at
$21.50 per day. In 1986, an election year, they paid $1,711.92 for
79 days. In 1987, they paid $756 for 36 days. At fair market rent,
the apartment would have cost the Wrights $7,800 per year. Finally,
after renting for 10 days through March 1988, the Wrights bought
the apartment at what appears to be its fair market value of
$58,500. Wright's receipt of housing at substantially below market
rental is a gift from Mallick.
   Beginning in 1983, Mallick provided Betty Wright with free use
of Mallightco's 1979 Cadillac Seville. Mrs. Wright brought the car
to Washington and has used it there ever since. Although the car is
referred to in Mallightco's records as the ``BW Cad.,'' Mallightco
owned the car until approximately February 1989 and paid expenses
including license fees, insurance, tires and repairs until
approximately February 1989.
   On February 16, 1989, Special Outside Counsel received a copy of
a February 9, 1989 letter to the Committee from Thomas H. Law,
trustee of the James C. Wright Jr. Blind Trust. Law stated that he
recently discovered that:
   
   (T)he Speaker's wife, Betty, as an officer of Mallightco, used
an automobile owned by that company. I have been informed that the
parties treated this transaction as a loan of the car to Mrs.
Wright, to be handled similarly to other loans from Mallightco to
its principals. I have been further informed that the parties
intended that the automobile be purchased by the Trust at its
inception. Unfortunately, due to an oversight, the automobile was
overlooked at the Trust's creation and never accounted for.
   
   Thus only after Special Outside Counsel had completed its
investigation and questioned witnesses regarding Mrs. Wright's use
of the car, Law discovered the ``inadvertent'' omission of the car
from the Trust records. Law further stated in his letter:
</TEXT>
