<FIRST>u w BC-Wright-Phelan 7thadd   04-17 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wright-Phelan, 7th add,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: his letter:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   I have currently rectified this situation by purchasing, as
Trustee, the automobile from Mallightco. The purchase price was
$7,050, the value of the automobile on Mallightco's books as of
January 1, 1983, at which time it was taken to Washington, D.C. The
Trust made a cash payment of $7,050 plus 7 percent interest dating
back to January 1, 1983, for a total cash payment of $10,011.
   In addition, the Trust holds a $120,000 note, payable from
Mallightco. This note has been reduced by $9,302.85, representing
the sums paid by Mallightco for insurance on and repairs to the
automobile from January 1, 1983 to present.
   
   Law does not explain how the oversight was discovered. Nor does
he explain how the purchase of the automobile in 1989 at its 1983
book value ``rectifies'' the Trust's failure to purchase the car in
1987. ...
   Plainly, Law's February 9, 1989 letter to the Committee is an
attempt to cover up Wright's violations of House Rule XLIII, clause
4, with respect to Mallick's gift of the car. Mallightco never
expected nor attempted to collect rental or `loan'' payments for
the car.
   George Mallick testified that Betty Wright had the car because
she ``would use (the car) in connection with her work for
Mallightco.'' However, even assuming that Betty Wright's employment
by Mallightco in 1983 and 1984 was bona fide, there is no evidence
that she did any work for Mallightco in Washington, D.C. which
required use of a car. In addition, regardless of the legitimacy of
Mrs. Wright's Mallightco employment, there is absolutely no
justification for her retention of the car after she stopped
working for the company. Therefore, the value of using the car from
1983 to date and all related expenses are gifts from Mallick to
Wright received in violation of House rules.
   Of course, in order for gifts to violate House Rules, they must
be received from someone with a direct interest in legislation
before Congress. In this matter, we believe it is clear that George
Mallick had such an interest. We further impute his interest in
legislation to his wife Marlene Mallick.
   Mallick is and has been a major real estate developer in Fort
Worth having developed commercial and residential properties worth
over $160 million. Prior to 1986, Mallick also had major holdings
in Texas oil and gas ventures. In 1986, he stood to profit from the
proposed redevelopment of the Fort Worth Stockyards which relied
heavily on public funds being appropriated by Congress. Thus, he
had a direct interest in legislation affecting the taxation of real
estate, interest rates, the oil and gas industries and
appropriations for the Stockyards project.
   In addition, Mallick's financing of certain real estate ventures
through savings and loan associations and the subsequent
foreclosure on at least one of those properties gave Mallick a
direct interest in legislation regarding the savings and loan
industry. Nevertheless, in late 1986, Wright designated Mallick to
conduct an investigation and prepare a report concerning the
``savings and loan crisis'' in Texas. The report addressed issues
of concern to Mallick and recommended legislation which would curb
the industry's right to foreclose on loans in default.
   Thus as discussed in full in Section III. E. of this Report,
Wright repeatedly violated House Rule XLIII, clause 4; Rule XLIV;
and consideration 5 of the Code of Ethics for Government Service.
</TEXT>
