<FIRST>r a AM-LottoFever 1stLd-Writethru a0707 04-17 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lotto Fever, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0707,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Jersey, Illinois Families Share Part Of Record $69 Million Lottery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Louis and...,' to UPDATE that Matlosz' are from
Elizabeth and to CORRECT wife's name to MaryAnn, sted Mary Ann.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of two farflung families came forward
from four states Monday to claim half the record $69.9 million
Illinois Lotto jackpot, leaving the holders of the two other
winning tickets unknown.
   ``It's more money than any of us ever expected to see in our
lifetimes,'' said Daniel Dixon, 38, of suburban Naperville, Ill..,
who bought one winning ticket for his wife's family.
   Louis and Mary Matlosz, of Elizabeth, N.J., and their four
children, including Dixon's wife MaryAnn, and three grandchildren,
joined Dixon at a news conference, saying they would split their
$17.5 million share of the jackpot and plan to spend the money on
vacations and on the grandchildren.
   Another winner was Ron Miller, 36, a hog buyer from Little York,
who will share his prize with brothers in Stafford, Texas, and
Chandler, Ariz.
   Miller said he was ``hysterical,'' after learning he had won.
``I sat at the table and laughed.''
   The news got around fast in Little York, a town of 300 in
west-central Illinois, and a big sign in the Post Office declared
``Congratulations, Ron.''
   State computers recorded that four winning tickets were sold _
two in the Chicago area, one in west-central Illinois and one in
southern Illinois.
   Both the Matlosz family and the Miller family bought 15 Lotto
tickets, and Miller said he was not surprised the $69.9 million
jackpot was being shared.
   ``It's more money than I'll ever use,'' Miller said.
   He said he would not quit work altogether, but ``I'll find
something I like a little better.''
   The Matlosz family members planned to keep working.
   The remaining winners were expected to come forward this week,
perhaps after making financial preparations.
   ``Most people will have already gotten some advice,'' said state
Lottery Director Sharon Sharp.
   The final figure for the jackpot, boosted by four winner-less
drawings and a frenzy of ticket-buying last week before Saturday's
drawing, was $69,940,000, Ms. Sharp said.
   The huge jackpot, which nearly doubled in the week before the
drawing, drew dreamers to Lotto outlets from around the country and
even the world, as travelers flocked to Lotto kiosks at O'Hare
International Airport between planes.
   By Monday, life was back to normal in Lotto-land. ``It's a lot
slower than last week,'' Ms. Sharp said.
   The jackpot, bolstered by a week of record sales, beat the world
record of $61.98 million set in October in California. That pot was
split among three winning tickets, one bought by an individual and
the others bought by groups of co-workers.
   If only one person had matched the numbers, the jackpot would
have been the largest paid to a single winner. But with four
ticket-holders sharing the pot, the largest single winner in U.S.
history remains a Florida woman who walked away with $55.16 million
in the Florida lottery in September.
   The winning numbers drawn Saturday were 3, 14, 32, 40, 46 and 54.
   Illinois Lotto players pick six numbers from 1 to 54 with two
chances on each $1 ticket. The odds that a ticket carries a winning
sequence are 12.9 million to 1.
</TEXT>
