<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Wright 4thLd-Writethru a0762 04-17 1091</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0762,1100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright Formally Charged With Breaking House Rules, Denies Guilt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs at end to update</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee, with Democrats and
Republicans united, formally charged Speaker Jim Wright Monday with
69 violations of the chamber's rules including what the panel's
chairman called ``a scheme to evade'' limits on outside earnings.
   After a 10-month, $1.5 million investigation, the committee of
six Democrats and six Republicans voted unanimously to issue a
report finding ``reason to believe'' the Texas Democrat had run
afoul of House rules requiring reporting of gifts, barring
acceptance of gifts from persons with a direct interest in
legislation and limiting outside earned income.
   ``I know in my heart I have not violated any of the rules of
that institution,'' Wright said in a speech to a labor meeting
shortly after the ethics report was released.
   He said he had asked ``very urgently, very earnestly'' for a
quick meeting with the the committee ``to confront them, to
confront the allegations head-on, face-to-face.''
   While scandal has tainted other House speakers, Wright is the
first ever to be formally charged with ethical wrongdoing.
   At a news conference, committee chairman Rep. Julian Dixon,
D-Calif., emphasized that Wright is presumed innocent until the
charges are proven, and he underscored that proving them requires a
much heavier weight of evidence than the step taken Monday, which
is the panel's equivalent of an indictment.
   The move set in motion a series of steps in which Wright can
defend himself and the panel try to prove with ``clear and
convincing'' evidence that the violations occurred. That is likely
ultimately to throw the matter before the full House, where
Wright's position as the nation's highest elected Democrat could be
on the line.
   Possible punishments range from a reprimand to expulsion from
the House, although lawmakers in both parties seemed to think the
final decision would come down to whether Wright should be
reprimanded or simply chastised for poor judgment and let off
without formal punishment.
   Wright immediately began his defense in earnest, operating what
one supporter, Rep. Charles Wilson, D-Texas, called ``a war room''
out of the speaker's office. ``At some point we've got to start
figuring out who's on our side and who's on the other side,''
Wilson said.
   Wilson predicted Wright would win on the floor, ``losing a few
cowardly Democrats and picking up some brave Republicans.''
   The most serious allegation against Wright _ that Fort Worth
developer George Mallick, from whom he accepted $145,000 in gifts
over a 10-year period, had a direct interest in legislation _ also
had the narrowest margin of support on the ethics committee.
   According to records of internal committee votes released along
with the report of the panel's special outside counsel, Chicago
attorney Richard J. Phelan, Democrats Chester Atkins of
Massachusetts and Bernard Dwyer of New Jersey joined the six
committee Republicans for an 8 to 4 margin on that issue.
   The panel agreed with its counsel, Phelan, that Mallick's major
interests in real estate and oil and gas ventures and in
redevelopment of Fort Worth's historic stockyards district gave him
a direct interest in legislation on taxation and on certain
appropriations bills. His financing arrangements with savings and
loan institutions also gave him an interest in legislation
involving the S&amp;L industry, the committee found.
   But Wright's lawyer, William C. Oldaker, called that
``doublespeak'' and said ``it's one of the most outrageous readings
of legislative history'' he has seen. Overall, the report contains
``a lot of noise, a lot of clamoring, but very little substance,''
he said.
   Other matters before the committee were more clear cut. The
panel voted unanimously that there was reason to believe Wright
failed to report as gifts the use of a car and Fort Worth
condominium he and his wife received from Mallick. Committee
members voted 10-2 that Mrs. Wright's $18,000-a-year salary from a
Mallick-Wright company should also be characterized as a gift,
saying she did little or nothing to earn the money.
   The panel also voted 10-2 that certain bulk sales of Wright's
book, ``Reflections of a Public Man,'' appeared to have been used
to evade House ceilings on outside earned income.
   ``In the committee's view, seven bulk sales of Rep. Wright's
book ... demonstrated an overall scheme to evade the House outside
earned income limit because (speaking) honorarium payments were
recharacterized as royalties,'' Dixon said.
   The committee voted unanimously to issue its statement of
alleged violation formally charging the speaker with breaking the
rules.
   Forty-seven possible violations raised by Phelan were dismissed.
Those involved allegations of improper lobbying of executive branch
officials, misuse of congressional staff and misuse of campaign
funds.
   Republicans were largely holding their fire Monday, aware that
any attack could help Wright paint the investigation _ prompted
last June by a complaint from Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga. _ as a
partisan matter.
   ``No Republican is attacking Jim Wright,'' said Rep. Dan Burton,
R-Ind. ``This is a bipartisan report of the ethics committee. We
are taking a wait-and-see attitude. We will serve as a jury. Let's
not make this partisan.''
   But another GOP lawmaker, Rep. Vin Weber of Minnesota, said the
committee's release of its findings demonstrated that ``the charges
are not trivial, they are not technical, they are not aimed at his
wife,'' as Wright contended last week. ``These are serious, serious
questions, and $145,000 is a lot of money.''
   The report said that Mallightco, a small investment company
formed by Wright, Mallick and their wives, paid Mrs. Wright's
salary even though it often had to borrow money from Mallick's own
company to do so. Mallightco was little more than ``a conduit for
cash flowing from the Mallicks to the Wrights,'' the report stated.
   On one issue, the panel could not reach a conclusion and said it
would investigate further. That involved the purchase by Mallightco
of an interest in an oil and gas well known as the Sabine Lake
Prospect.
   For an initial investment of $9,120, the partnership bought a 4
percent interest on May 10, 1988. The well struck oil but soon
played out, and on June 9, was shut down. Despite the results, a
Texas petroleum investment corporation, Union Rheinische Petroleum
Inc., offered $440,000 for Mallightco's share on May 10, boosting
the value of Mallitco at a time when Wright's blind trust was
selling its interest.
   An independent appraisal of the interest in the Sabine Lake
Prospect put its value at $69,000 to $169,000, far less than Union
Rheinische offered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-Wright-Phelan 9thadd   04-17 1094</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wright-Phelan, 9th add,1090</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: October 7, 1986.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Wright did not merely ``urge prompt consideration'' of or
``express judgment'' on the Hall matter as specifically permitted
in the Select Committee on Ethics' Advisory Opinion No. 1. He
removed the recapitalization bill from House consideration in order
to pressure the Bank Board into changing its resolution of the Hall
matter regardless of the merits of the Bank Board's position. Such
pressure is a violation of House Rule XLIII, clause 1, as
interpreted by Advisory Opinion No. 1.
   On October 6, 1986, Wright met with J. Scott Mann III, an
Austin, Texas savings and loan operator who complained that the
Bank Board was discriminating against Texas savings and loans
associations and that a recapitalized FSLIC would close large
numbers of Texas institutions. Mann also set forth his complaints
in a letter of October 7, 1986 which Wright forwarded to Gray
asking that he check on the situations described. Gray investigated
Mann's charges and reported to Wright that Mann's CreditBanc
Savings had committed serious regulatory violations and was in a
precarious financial condition. Wright took no further action. Thus
Wright's request that Gray check on Mann's charges is within the
guidelines of Advisory Opinion No. 1 which expressly provides that
it is appropriate for a member to request information or a status
report.
   In early November 1986, Wright telephoned Gray regarding
Wright's ``friend'' Thomas M. Gaubert of Independent American
Savings Association, a Texas-chartered association with its main
office in Irving, Texas. Gaubert was also a contributor to the
Democratic Party and treasurer of the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee.
   In January 1986, Gaubert had been permanently removed from
Independent American and prohibited from operating any
FSLIC-insured association. Gaubert had been involved in
questionable transactions at an Iowa savings and loan as well as
regulatory violations and unsafe or unsound practices at
Independent American. As of November 30, 1986, Independent American
had a negative net worth of $454 million. Although Gaubert entered
into a written agreement removing him from the industry, he later
argued that he had been misled and treated unfairly and, therefore,
that the agreement was invalid.
   Wright asked Gray to meet with Gaubert personally in order to
get Gaubert's side of the story. Gray protested that Bank Board
rules prohibit the Chairman from meeting with parties to actions
before the Board. Despite Gray's protests, Wright insisted that
Gray meet with Gaubert; Gray did so as an accommodation to Wright.
Following his meeting with Gaubert, Gray made the unprecedented
decision in January or February 1987 to appoint an independent
counsel (selected by counsel for Gaubert) to determine whether the
Bank Board had in fact wrongfully removed Gaubert from Independent
American. Gray testified that but for his perception of Wright's
influence on the recapitalization bill, he would not have appointed
independent counsel. Independent counsel ultimately determined that
the Bank Board had not violated any statutes or regulations in its
treatment of Gaubert, although it did note some instances of
improper or unfair behavior, none of which justified Gaubert's
claim that he was removed improperly.
   Nonetheless, despite the significant concessions made by Gray,
at a meeting with officials of the Bank Board and FHLB-Dallas on
February 10, 1987 in Wright's office, Wright made it plain that he
viewed the outcome of the Gaubert matter to have been extremely
unsatisfactory. The clear inference is that Wright was not simply
seeking impartial consideration of Gaubert's claim, but a change in
the Bank Board's regulatory response to Gaubert. Such use of
Wright's influence is a violation of House Rule XLIII, clause 1 as
interpreted by Advisory Opinion No. 1.
   In December 1986, Congressman Tony Coelho called Wright's aide,
John Mack, and requested Wright's assistance on behalf of Don R.
Dixon of Vernon Savings and Loan in Dallas and Vernon, Texas.
Coelho informed Mack that the FSLIC was going to shut down Vernon
that day. He asked that Wright attempt to get Dixon a grace period
as Dixon said he had a willing buyer.
   Mack testified that following his conversation with Coelho, he
told Wright of Dixon's problem. Wright telephoned Gray and asked
him whether Vernon was being closed down. Gray responded that
closing an institution requires a Bank Board meeting and he had not
authorized any such meeting. Wright asked Gray to find out if
anything was happening and to call John Mack with the information.
Gray later informed Mack that Vernon was not being ``shut down,''
but the FHLB-Dallas supervisory agents were going to seek a
``consent to merger agreement'' from Vernon's directors at the end
of December 1986. Gray explained that such an agreement would not
affect the association's ability to find an investor and that Mack
should let the Bank Board know if an investor were found.
Ultimately, no investor was found and Vernon was placed in
receivership in March 1987.
   In this instance, since Wright merely asked for information from
the Bank Board, no violation occurred.
   In November 1986, Wright again called Gray to express his
concern about the way Texas institutions were being treated by the
Bank Board. He brought up the subject of H. Joe Selby, the Director
of Regulatory Affairs at the FHLB-Dallas and formerly the acting
Comptroller of the Currency, who had the reputation of being a
tough regulator and who had been brought into the savings and loan
crisis by Gray to implement the Bank Board's supervisory and
regulatory response. Because of his hardline posture, Selby was
feared and distrusted by many in the thirft industry.
   Wright told Gray he understood from unnamed sources that Selby
was a homosexual who was sending all of FHLB-Dallas' work to a
``ring of homosexual lawyers in Texas.'' Wright asked Gray if there
was anything Gray could do to ``get rid of'' Selby. Gray refused
Wright's request and defended Selby as a highly competent regulator
doing the tough job expected of him.
   Although unsuccessful, Wright's attempt to destroy Selby's
career based upon such an accusation violates House rule XLIII,
clause 1, because it does not reflect creditably on the House.
   Similarly, when in late 1987 or early 1988 Wright's aide, Phil
Duncan, called Carl Hoyle, the Bank Board's Director of
Congressional Affairs and said he wanted William Black fired from
the staff of the FHLB-San Francisco, such a request indirectly from
Wright is also a violation of House Rule XLIII, clause 1.
   Thus, as discussed in full in Section III. F. of this Report,
Wright committed four violations of House Rule XLIII, clause 1, as
interpreted by Advisory Opinion No. 1.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   End Wright-Phelan _ 10 Takes
</TEXT>
</DOC>
