<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Emigre     04-17 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Emigre,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artist-Photgrapher Petrov Given Permission to Leave Russia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artist-photographer Sergei Petrov said Monday he
was being allowed to leave the Soviet Union after being refused
permission to emigrate for eight years and that he hoped to go to
the United States this week.
   The 36-year-old Petrov said in a telephone interview that he had
tried since 1981 to join his American wife, Virginia Johnson, but
was turned down for reasons of state security.
   Now, he said, ``I have my passport in my hand.''
   Petrov said he received notification from the Soviet visa office
in Sunday's mail and picked up his external passport Monday. He
said he filed repeated invitations for visits to America with the
visa office long ago and that ``they just picked one.''
   He replied when asked why he now was being granted permission to
leave: ``I will never know. I think the reason is all the joint
effort of the U.S. Embassy, the State Department, and other
countries like the Netherlands and Australia. But mostly it was the
State Department's pressure.''
   Petrov's photographs were put on display at the State Department
late last year and his case has been a priority human rights case
pursued by Washington.
   He said he will go to the United States ``as soon as I can,
sometime this week,'' but that his plans were not certain.
   The photographer said former U.S. Ambassador Arthur Hartman and
his wife Donna worked especially hard on his case.
   Petrov said he was told before he began working in an
electronics laboratory in 1977 that he would not be allowed to
leave the Soviet Union for five years. He left the laboratory after
three months, but officials continued to refuse permission to
emigrate for years after.
   In December he was refused permission when authorities allowed
his 71-year-old mother Klavdia to go to the United States for
medical treatment. She is in Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
