<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Israel-Phoenicians Adv25   04-17 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Phoenicians, Adv 25,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs April 25 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cemetery of Ancient Phoenicians Uncovered in Northern Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists have unearthed an ancient
cemetery in northern Israel and say the 3,000-year-old finds
indicate the Phoenicians were landlubbers before they went to sea
and dominated the Mediterranean.
   The Phoenicians emerged about 1,000 B.C. and established
city-states throughout the Mediterranean Basin from Lebanon to
Spain, surviving until Roman times.
   Pottery, jewelry and other remains of their cities show a
variety of influences from Greek cultures in the Aegean as well as
ancient Egypt and Mesopotamia.
   But little is known of the origins of the ancient Phoenicians.
   Evidence uncovered by a Hebrew University team in the tombs at
Achziv near Israel's border with Lebanon point to a Semitic
background, either from the ancient land of Israel, also known as
Canaan, or further inland.
   The team declined to give a specific location of the cemetery
for fear of plunderers; they believe artifacts and gold may be
buried in the tombs.
   Elat Mazar, an archaeologist at Hebrew University in Jerusalem,
said the architecture of the tombs carved into the bedrock linked
the early Phoenicians to the ancient Hittites, a Semitic people who
lived in what is now Turkey and Syria and had no significant
sailing tradition.
   ``We found a hole in the ceiling on the tomb which is
characteristic of Hittite burial chambers,'' she said. ``In their
cult of the dead, it was a symbolic link between the living world
and the world of the dead.''
   She added that the Phoenicians had a sophisicated society with
advanced sailing technology, refined tastes in jewelry and an
unparalled ability to adapt material from other cultures.
   ``There is no question they were more developed than the
Israelite culture of the time. They were Semitic and close to the
Israelites but different.''
   The pack-rat characteristic of borrowing from neighboring
societies made the Phoenicians something of a mystery, however.
   Patricia Smith, a British-born anthropologist and dentist
interviewed at her laboratory in Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital,
said a study of the ancient human remains show the physical
features of the Phoenicians were Semitic.
   ``This was no Greek,'' said Ms. Smith, turning the skull of a
Phoenician and pointing to the wide skull, arch of the nose and the
high cheekbones. A cast of an Israelite skull from the same eighth
to seventh century B.C. period had similar features.
   From his teeth, Smith deduced that the man, 45 to 50 years old
when he died, suffered either from fever or hunger in his infancy
but was quite fit as an adult, with not a single tooth cavity.
   ``Apart from this hole in his head, he was very healthy,'' Smith
said of the Phoenician, who died of a powerful blow to the back of
his head, apparently struck by a heavy blunt instrument.
   The Israeli expedition unearthed about 50 skeletons from two
cave tombs measuring about 10 feet by 10 feet. The cemetery covers
seven acres and may contain the remains of thousands of Phoenicians
spanning almost the entire 1,000-year life of their society here.
   Ms. Smith said she hoped to use the remains, especially the
skulls, to recreate the general ``Phoenician look.''
   ``It will be very exiting to find out who the Phoenicians were.''
   Ms. Smith uses video cameras and still photography to recreate
faces. She employed the technique on behalf of the prosecution in
the trial of John Demjanjuk, a Cleveland, Ohio, autoworker
convicted last year in Israel of Nazi war crimes and sentenced to
death.
   She made a video that superimposed a recent video image of
Demjanjuk on a 40-year-old Nazi identity card to show it was the
same man.
   With the Phoenicians, she plans to use the same technique to
superimpose video images from ancient drawings of Phoenicians and
modern sketches over the skulls themselves.
   ``I would be able to define a type, but not an individual. We
should be able to tell how varied the Phoenicians were,'' she said,
explaining that a perfect re-creation was impossible without
knowing the features of soft tissue such as eyelids, ears and lips.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs April 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0806EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-RabbiWatchdogs Adv26   04-17 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rabbi Watchdogs, Adv 26,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs April 26 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Israeli Rabbi Group Monitors West Bank Human Rights Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bearded rabbis recently slipped under the
cover of night into an occupied West Bank village to question
residents about allegations of Israeli troop brutality during an
army-imposed curfew.
   They are members of the new Rabbinic Human Rights Watch, which
is gaining prominence among the growing number of Israeli groups
monitoring abuses in the occupied territories.
   Membership has swelled from a handful of rabbis a few months ago
to 75 rabbis embracing all streams of Judaism _ the Orthodox,
Conservative and Reform movements.
   The group's first action was to survey community health care in
several West Bank villages, then write to Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin complaining that medical treatment was being ``used as a
means of political pressure on the population.''
   ``It was immediately published in the papers and we said, `We as
rabbis have the power.' We have credibility as Jewish leaders who
first of all think of the moral side,'' said the U.S.-born chairman
of the group, Rabbi David Forman.
   The group has since monitored the Palestinian village of Batir,
three miles outside Jerusalem.
   In early April, one day before a group of rabbis was to have
visited Batir, the army clamped a curfew on the village in
retaliation for a stone-throwing attack on a train.
   Four days later, Forman and another rabbi, Yermiyahu Milgrom,
slipped into Batir at night to hear the villagers' complaints.
   Their report of alleged troop brutality, including beatings and
verbal abuse, was submitted to Rabin and was carried in the Israeli
press.
   The group includes about 10 Orthodox rabbis, with the rest of
its members equally divided between Reform and Conservative
clerics. It is run by a board of six rabbis that includes two
representatives from each of the three movements.
   The unusual cooperation between Orthodox and rival Reform and
Conservative rabbis, as well as the group's lack of political
ideology gives it a moral authority over most of the dozen or so
other Israeli movements considered to be comprised of leftists.
   Western human rights groups, on the other hand, are considered
by many Israelis to be biased in favor of the Palestinians.
   ``We raise our voice, the moral voice of the Jewish spirit,
which holds that every man and woman, without regard for religion
and nationality, is created in the image of God,'' the group's
platform states.
   ``Invested with a religious mandate to speak for the Jewish
people who has suffered so painfully, we must forever remain
sensitive to the suffering of others.''
   Forman criticized Israel's religious leaders on grounds that
they failed to speak out against brutality in the occupied
territories.
   ``We sense a lack of the rabbinic voice and when we do hear it,
it's usually on the farthest right,'' said Forman, 45, a reform
rabbi who immigrated to Israel from Boston in 1972. ``We invite the
chief rabbis to respond to what's happening because it opposes the
spirit of Jewish law and tradition.''
   Chief rabbinate spokesman Eitan Eizman denies the allegations,
saying Israel's Orthodox chief rabbis ``have responded every time
there was an outstanding violation, writing that innocent people
should not be harmed or beaten.''
   Rabbi Moshe Levinger, a settlement leader in Kiryat Arba near
the West Bank town of Hebron, called the rabbis' criticism
misguided.
   ``We have never agreed that these are occupied lands,'' Levinger
said. ``We'll stop the moment the Arabs stop.''
   The rabbis' group is careful not to endorse a political solution
to the 16-month-old conflict, and it denounces Palestinian violence.
   Milgrom, 35, said Judaism ``is often seen as something that
comes to discriminate and persecute the non-Jewish side, and we
oppose that. It does not correctly portray Judaism. ... Man was
created in God's image, every man and not just the Jews.''
   The rabbis said adherence to Jewish religious tradition has also
helped the group in gathering testimony.
   At Batir, for example, Forman and Milgrom used a method
described in Talmudic religious law of comparing testimony from
different witnesses. Forman said that as a result he was convinced
people told the truth, despite an army denial of events described
in the group's report.
   He said the rabbis' group also offers ``rabbinical counselling
for soldiers deeply troubled by the moral and ethical struggle they
confront'' while serving in the occupied territories.
   The group's next project is an investigation of the army policy
of forcing Palestinians to remove barricades built by protesters in
the occupied territories, Forman said.
   ``I don't want to compare us with other countries,'' he said.
``We have to measure our behavior by Jewish standards. If we start
using the lowest common denominator, we cease to be a light unto
the nations.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs April 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
