<SECOND>BC-History, Adv24,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, April 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, April 24, the 114th day of 1989. There are 251
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On April 24th, 1800, Congress approved a bill establishing the
Library of Congress in Washington, D.C., appropriating $5,000 ``for
the purchase of such books as may be necessary.''
   On this date:
   In 1704, the first American newspaper printed on a regular
basis, the ``Boston News Letter,'' was published for the first time.
   In 1792, the French national anthem ``La Marseillaise'' was
composed by Claude-Joseph Rouget de Lisle.
   In 1877, federal troops were ordered out of New Orleans, ending
the North's post-Civil War rule in the South.
   In 1897, William W. Price began work at the ``Washington Star,''
where he became the first reporter to cover the White House on a
regular basis.
   In 1898, Spain declared war on the United States after rejecting
America's ultimatum to withdraw from Cuba.
   In 1915, the Turkish Ottoman Empire began the mass deportation
of Armenians during World War I. Hundreds of thousands of Armenians
are believed to have died en route.
   In 1916, Irish nationalists in Dublin launched the Easter
Rising, which was put down by British forces several days later.
   In 1953, British statesman Winston Churchill was knighted by
Queen Elizabeth II at Buckingham Palace.
   In 1961, following the Bay of Pigs fiasco, the White House
issued a statement in which President John F. Kennedy accepted
``sole responsibility for the events of the past days.''
   In 1962, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology accomplished
the first satellite relay of a television signal, between Camp
Parks, Calif., and Westford, Mass.
   In 1968, leftist students at Columbia University in New York
began a week-long occupation of several campus buildings.
   In 1970, the People's Republic of China launched its first
satellite, which transmitted a popular communist Chinese song,
``The East is Red.''
   In 1986, Wallis, the Duchess of Windsor, for whom King Edward
VIII had given up the British throne, died in Paris at age 89.
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter presided over an official
state ceremony in the U.S. Capitol to pay tribute to the 11 million
people killed in the Nazi Holocaust.
   Five years ago: The government reported consumer prices rose
two-tenths of 1 percent in March 1984, leaving inflation for the
year running at a moderate annual rate of 5 percent.
   One year ago: Three sailors were killed and 22 injured when fire
broke out aboard the diesel-powered submarine USS Bonefish off the
Florida coast.
   Today's birthdays: Poet Robert Penn Warren is 84. Critic Stanley
Kauffmann is 73. Actress Shirley MacLaine is 55. Actress Jill
Ireland is 53. Actress-singer Barbra Streisand is 47.
   Thought for today: ``There is no greater mistake than the hasty
conclusion that opinions are worthless because they are badly
argued.'' _ T.H. Huxley, English biologist and author, 1825-1895.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for use Monday, April 24</NOTE>
