<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Saturday, April 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, April 29, the 119th day of 1989. There are
246 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On April 29, 1945, American soldiers liberated the Nazi
concentration camp in Dachau, Germany, where tens of thousands of
people had perished. With the Third Reich collapsing around him,
Adolf Hitler appointed Admiral Karl Doenitz his successor. Hitler
also married his mistress, Eva Braun, in a Berlin bunker.
   On this date:
   In 1429, Joan of Arc entered the besieged city of Orleans to
lead a victory over the English.
   In 1861, Maryland's House of Delegates voted against seceding
from the Union.
   In 1862, New Orleans fell to Union forces during the Civil War.
   In 1863, newspaper publisher William Randolph Hearst was born in
San Francisco.
   In 1894, several hundred unemployed men known as ``Coxey's
Army'' swarmed into Washington to ask Congress for help.
   In 1913, Swedish-born engineer Gideon Sundback of Hoboken, N.J.,
patented the zipper.
   In 1916, the Easter Rising in Dublin ended as Irish nationalists
who had seized control of the General Post Office surrendered to
British authorities.
   In 1946, 28 former Japanese leaders were indicted in Tokyo as
war criminals.
   In 1974, President Richard M. Nixon announced he was releasing
edited transcripts of some of the secret White House tape
recordings related to the Watergate scandal.
   In 1977, Pope Paul XI and the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr.
Donald Coggan, participated in a Christian unity service in the
Vatican's Sistine Chapel.
   In 1983, Harold Washington was sworn in as Chicago's first black
mayor, vowing to freeze hiring and fire recent political appointees
to ease the city's fiscal crisis.
   In 1985, the space shuttle ``Challenger'' lifted off with seven
astronauts and a ``mini-zoo'' of monkeys and rats.
   Ten years ago: Israel's Cabinet voted to reinstate the death
penalty for terrorists convicted of ``acts of inhuman cruelty,''
one week after a PLO attack claimed the lives of four Israelis.
   Five years ago: President Ronald Reagan and his wife, Nancy,
flew 600 miles from Beijing to central China, where they saw farms,
peasant villages and an archeological site.
   One year ago: The head of the federal agency researching
``AIDS'' drugs, Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, told a House panel he was
basically satisfied with the job scientists were doing, but
acknowledged some human trials had been delayed due to lack of
money.
   Today's birthdays: Movie director Fred Zinnemann is 82. Actor
Tom Ewell is 80. Actress Celeste Holm is 70. Football coach George
Allen is 67. Poet Rod McKuen is 56. Conductor Zubin Mehta is 53.
Singer Tommy James is 42. Actress Kate Mulgrew is 34.
   Thought for today: ``How easy it is for a man to die rich, if he
will but be contented to live miserable.'' _ Henry Fielding,
English author and dramatist, 1707-1754.
</TEXT>
