<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:PeerGynt Adv20   04-17 0939</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Peer Gynt, Adv 20,0960</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs AMs, April 20, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Marathon Version of Ibsen's `Peer Gynt' at Hartford Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the Hartford Stage Company, director
Mark Lamos has recreated the magical, mystical world of ``Peer
Gynt'' in a dazzling two-part, five-hour production of Ibsen's
rarely performed masterpiece.
   The play, on view through May 20, is a glorious theatrical
adventure, a journey that Lamos manages to make both epic and
intimate.
   Using 26 actors in more than 70 roles, the director and scenic
design wizard John Conklin transport theatergoers around the globe
_ from rustic Norway to a bizarre troll underworld to the sands of
North Africa to a Cairo madhouse to a ship wrecked in a raging sea
and then back again to Norway.
   But Lamos doesn't forget this tale is one man's story of
self-discovery, from brash, self-centered, carefree and charming
youth to cynical, even despairing, old man who finally finds
redemption through the love of a forgiving woman.
   Negotiating the sweep and intimacy of Lamos' production is actor
Richard Thomas. He plays Peer with a fierce determination. Thomas,
who was a robust, non-melancholy Dane in Hartford's ``Hamlet'' last
year, is one of those fearless, energetic actors, willing to take a
chance. Despite his eagerness, he doesn't rush through Ibsen's
difficult poetry, done here in a new, very modern translation by
Gerry Bamman and Irene B. Berman. They follow the playwright's
original rhyme schemes.
   Bamman played the older Peer in Livui Ciulei's production of the
play in 1983 at the Guthrie Theater in Minneapolis. Lamos saw that
revival and thought about doing it at Hartford.
   ``The play has always been sitting there in my mind, waiting, I
guess,'' Lamos says. ``Every year it would come up, and we've talk
about it. But after Richard played `Hamlet' here, we decided to do
it.''
   In fact, Lamos said if it weren't for Thomas, he wouldn't have
attempted the mammoth revival. The actor, according to Lamos,
exuded ``a willingness to take a journey with `Peer Gynt' that
really didn't always seem as if it had a purpose or a goal to it.
That was really the best part of the rehearsal process. We just
kept looking at each other and saying, `Well, let's just keep
traveling. We aren't going to get all the answers right away.'''
   Lamos felt he would get to know the play better if he could
collaborate with Bamman and Berman as they worked on the
translation, which was commissoned by Hartford Stage.
   ``It was a wonderful way of learning `Peer Gynt' from the inside
out and without preconceptions and not taking anything for
granted,'' Lamos says. ``Literally, each moment in the play had to
be dealt with very, very carefully and specifically.
   ``The big surprise was that we found out that a lot of the
existing translations were glossing over more of the crudities
Ibsen was after and more of the slang that he definitely put into
the play. At first, things that we were criticizing in the early
drafts we discovered were, in fact, Ibsen's intentions.
   ``And that made a huge difference in the whole approach to the
play. It was one of the reasons the production became more
childlike and naive and began to have more of a folk quality than I
originally thought it would have.''
   Conklin's settings re-enforce that theme, beginning with the
opening moments of the play. The stage is decorated like a
surrealistic nursery in which Peer lounges in a cradle or commands
a rocking horse as if it were a galloping steed.
   The director and designer have created several memorable images,
the most poignant being the death scene of Peer's mother at the end
of ``Into the Mountains,'' which is Part 1 of the play. The mother,
beautifully played as a loving scold by Patricia Conolly, is
transported to her grave in Peer's cradle now turned into a sleigh
and driven by her son.
   In Part 2, ``The Voyage,'' Conklin fills the stage with
billowing black plastic which becomes the violent sea that finally
washes Peer back home.
   The designer uses yards of fabric to cover the theater floor,
creating snowy mountains, yellow deserts and green forests. More
cloth hangs like a curtain over the theater's back wall, allowing
lighting designer Pat Collins to conjure up mountains as well as
spectral images. Conklin's original designs were more complicated,
Lamos says.
   ``At first, John created a set model which was filled with large
and colorful scenery,'' he said. ``We slowly took pieces out of it
until we came to something much simpler and realized we wanted
something that had more fluidity. That's when we arrived at the
idea of these thousands of yards of flowing China silk and the
shadows that they made behind them.''
   The large cast matches Thomas' enthusiasm, particularly Stephen
Rowe as the vulgar, hedonistic troll king who urges Peer to ``be
yourself and nothing else,'' a motto that still has a large
following today.
   For Lamos, the most challenging aspect of the production was
``to stay open and not try to contain the play with a metaphor of
some kind. I just let it be what it turned out to be, and then it
began to unify itself in a funny way.''
   What can Lamos and Hartford Stage do for an encore?
   The director is not thinking about that just yet.
   ``I don't even want to browse through my drama book shelf at
home,'' Lamos sighs. ``I just want to go look at the ocean for a
while.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
