<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV30   04-17 1057</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 30,1085</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Little things bring home the reality of starring
in a big Broadway play.
   People on the bus who ask, ``Did I go to high school with you?''
or ``Did you live in my mother's apartment building?''
   Or the persistent gaze of strangers who give you the kind of
stares that mean they either want to steal your purse or
congratulate you on your performance.
   Such are the problems facing actress Joan Allen, who now has her
name above the title in Wendy Wasserstein's hit comedy, ``The Heidi
Chronicles.''
   ``I try to be nice to people, but it makes me embarrassed,''
says the quiet, almost shy Allen, relaxing in her tiny dressing
room backstage at the Plymouth Theater. ``Especially when they say
`Where do I know you from?' And then you have to stand there and
say `I did this and I did that' and listen to them say, `No, No.
No.' And finally, `Oh, that's it!''
   For Allen, the Plymouth Theater has become something of a
permanent home.
   She was there last season in Lanford Wilson's ``Burn This.'' She
won a Tony Award as best actress for her portrayal of a grieving
dancer mourning the death of her roommate.
   Now she is back with ``The Heidi Chronicles,'' which won the
1989 Pulitzer Prize for drama. In it, she plays art historian Heidi
Holland, a witness to 20 years of changing attitudes toward women
in modern America.
   ``Heidi is a very complicated character,'' Allen says. ``The
more I've done the play, the more I've learned about her.''
   And she has had time to get acquainted with Heidi. The play
began last December at off-Broadway's Playwrights Horizons, a small
but important New York company where such works as ``Sunday in the
Park with George'' and ``Driving Miss Daisy,'' two other recent
Pulitzer Prize winners, got their start.
   ``Heidi may not get involved, but she takes everything very
personally,'' Allen says. ``She feels things deeply and sticks to
her own path. Because she doesn't rail at the winds, people find
her to be some sort of a pushover. I don't find her to be that
passive.''
   The play follows Heidi from the late '60s and the era of Vietnam
War protests to the late '80s when the Reagan era has come and gone
and the dreams of the baby boomers have begun to burst.
   The 32-year-old Allen came of age some seven or eight years
later than the character she plays on stage. And with less
turbulence. The actress is from Rochelle, Ill., some 80 miles west
of Chicago. Her father, now retired, ran a gas station.
   ``It's farm country _ corn fields and soybeans,'' she says. ``It
was very quiet and a great way to grow up. I was allowed to be a
kid forever.''
   Allen first went to Eastern Illinois University where as a
freshman she studied drama and met John Malkovich, a junior. The
following year Malkovich transferred to Illinois State University
and linked up with people like Gary Sinise, Terry Kinney and Laurie
Metcalfe. Out of this group of young drama students came the
Steppenwolf Theater Company.
   After college, Allen joined the fledgling company which had
found a home in the Chicago suburb of Highland Park. To earn money,
she kept a full-time job as a secretary for an educational film
company.
   ``My experiences aren't like those of a lot of other
actresses,'' she says of her early days. ``With Steppenwolf, I had
a ready-made family. I would know what show I was doing, and I
almost never auditioned during the entire seven years I lived in
Chicago. We read for parts among ourselves. It created a lot of
security. We didn't have to keep proving ourselves.''
   Allen kept her job as a secretary even when she was doing eight
shows a week at Steppenwolf. Only when she came to New York in 1983
with a Steppenwolf production of ``And a Nightingale Sang'' did she
quit outside work.
   The success the previous year of Sam Shepard's ``True West,''
starring Malkovich and Sinise, made the move to New York easier for
other Steppenwolf members.
   ``Until then, I had never been to New York _ not even to
visit,'' Allen says. ``It was the right time in my life. I was in
my late 20s, and it was a good role for me. Again I came with a
Steppenwolf show, so there was a sort of built-in security.''
   In ``Nightingale,'' Allen played a shy, crippled English
spinster. From the show, Allen got an agent, rave reviews and a
six-month run. She decided to stay in New York and won a part in
Christopher Durang's comedy ``The Marriage of Bette and Boo,'' as
well as movie roles in such films as ``Peggy Sue Got Married,''
``Manhunter'' and ``Tucker.''
   Allen teamed up with Malkovich for a year-long run in ``Burn
This,'' which first played Los Angeles, then Steppenwolf's theater
in Chicago and finally New York.
   The month that ``Burn This'' opened on Broadway in 1987, Allen
did a reading for ``The Heidi Chronicles.'' It was an early draft
of the play, but Allen immediately knew she wanted to play Heidi
when the comedy was done on stage.
   She got her wish. For the next six months or so at the Plymouth,
Allen will concentrate on Heidi, refining the character.
   ``When we started rehearsals, Wendy would drop telling comments
about the kind of woman Heidi was and then I would use my
imagination,'' Allen says. ``We also sat in on some art history
lectures and talked to different art historians.''
   The actress also met with well-known feminist art historian
Linda Nochlin who teaches at the City University of New York. She
attended Nochlin's graduate class and read her essay, ``Why are
there no famous women painters?''.
   Still, the actress doesn't know if her portrait of Heidi Holland
will ever be complete.
   ``That's what is so good about the theater,'' she says. ``It's
an alive art form. You keep working on something and hopefully, the
more you do it, the better you get at it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
