<DOCNO> AP890417-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-ContinentinCrisis-Chile Adv23-2Takes   04-17 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Chile, Adv 23-2 Takes,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Chile _ An Ominous Military Shadow</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in nearly 20 years, Chileans
will elect a president this year to replace an iron-fisted military
leader. But it could be too early for rejoicing. This is another in
a series of periodic reports by The Associated Press on the
economic, social and political turbulence that has turned South
America into a continent in crisis.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lame ducks though they may be, Chile's
military leaders already are casting an ominous shadow over the
civilian government that will take office next year.
   They have made it unabashedly clear that while they will step
aside they won't step out and will seize power again if they think
it is necessary.
   And therein lies a major difficulty for the civilian who wins
the presidential election Dec. 14 and takes over March 11 from Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, the iron-fisted president since 1973.
   The military government will bequeath a growing and stable
economy to the civilians, but they also will leave deep and
potentially explosive social imbalances.
   Millions of Chileans are still poor _ as they were when Pinochet
led the military into the civilian disarray of September 1973 and
overthrew President Salvador Allende, the Marxist who professed to
want to help the poor.
   Recent opinion polls indicate that while Chileans have a
relatively robust economy, low salaries and unemployment are high
on their list of priorities for the civilian government.
   As politicians prepare for the election, Pinochet and other
military leaders make it clear they do not plan a complete retreat
from the political scene.
   Pinochet recently said military leaders have the obligation to
ensure that the future civilian president is ``an authentic
democratic man.''
   And the military is on record that it won't hesitate to
intervene again.
   ``If the institutional order is broken, the armed forces have
the duty to restore it, using compulsion and all the necessary
means,'' Gen. Alejandro Medina, head of a center of strategic
studies, said in a recent lecture to non-commissioned officers.
   Civilian politicians complain that will place the armed forces
in the role of ``armed guardians'' of the civilian government.
   A constitution drawn up by the military government in 1980 gives
the armed forces the means for such a role. It allows Pinochet, who
still commands the army, and the commanders of the navy, air force
and national police to keep their posts until 1998.
   Pinochet, who is constitutionally prohibited from seeking
re-election in December, has already said he will remain as army
commander after the election.
   That is tantamount to ``creating an armed state within an
unarmed democratic state,'' said Genero Arriagada, vice president
of the centrist Christian Democratic Party, the largest in the
opposition.
   The constitution also established a military-dominated National
Council, which may ``represent'' its views to the civilian
government on key matters.
   More complicated for the future leaders may be the problem of
human rights violations during 16 years of military rule.
   Opposition leaders say that should they win the election, they
will investigate the abuses and try those found responsible.
   The military leaders have made it clear, however, they it will
not permit reprisals for what they see as actions that were part of
a war.
   In the military years, thousands of leftists were arrested, many
were sent into exile and hundreds were killed. Local and foreign
human rights groups have documented more than 700 cases of
dissidents who disappeared after being arrested by security forces.
   A recent opinion poll taken by the Center for Public Studies, an
independent research institute, however, indicates that Chileans
are more interested in their personal economic situations than in
the political complexities of the process to restore civilian rule
or in the military threats to take power again.
   In a nationwide poll taken by the center in March and April, 46
percent of the respondents mentioned low salaries and inefficient
public health services as the two top items on a civilian
government's agenda.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Turkey-Pressures Adv23-2Takes   04-17 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Turkey-Pressures, Adv 23-2 Takes,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Turkey Looks West But Feels Pull of East</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkish yuppies in bluejeans and
miniskirts sip coffee at a fashionable waterside cafe on the
Bosporous, seemingly oblivious of the Moslem faithful bent in
sabbath prayers in a mosque just a few feet away.
   Turkey is a country of such contrasts.
   Istanbul and Ankara, the centers of commercial, intellectual and
parliamentary life, feature glittering Hiltons, shopping centers
and traffic-clogged streets, while an hour's flight away are the
horse-drawn carts and souks of Diyarbakir in the far east where
politics are often inflamed by blood feuds.
   With one foot in Europe and the other in Asia, Turkey yearns to
be a part of the West but also feels the pull _ and bears the
vestiges _ of the East.
   Its armies reached the gates of Vienna three centuries ago but
were beaten back in what was the start of the decline of the
Ottoman Empire.
   Today Turkey seeks to enter Europe peacefully, bidding for
membership in the European Economic Community (EEC), the symbol of
West European democracies' economic and political clout.
   It would fulfill the dream of Kemal Ataturk, the revered father
of modern Turkey, who put the overwhelmingly Moslem country on a
Westward bent by turning away from Islamic law to build a republic
based on separation of church and state in 1923.
   Turkish officials believe they have already paid their dues for
admission to the West by fighting alongside U.S. troops in Korea
and by membership in North Atlantic Treaty Organization, protecting
a land border with the Soviet Union. But the EEC bid is seen as the
acid test.
   ``It's one of the few subjects in which there's more or less a
consensus in Turkey,'' said Inal Batu, the Foreign Ministry
spokesman.
   He acknowledged, stressing Turkey's dilemma, that some Europeans
think the EEC ``is a club for Christians.''
   Says Stephen J. Karper, general manager of Citibank in Istanbul
and an American: ``Europeans have to become familar with Turkey.''
   But Turks, too, have become increasingly wary of signs of a rise
of Islamic fundamentalism, which has seen women marching in the
streets covered head to toe and strained Turkey's relations with
neighboring Iran.
   That, coupled with a history of military interventions to topple
democratic governments and charges that torture in prisons
persists, raises questions about how solid Western foundations are.
   On the other hand, since the military returned to the barracks
in 1983, Premier Turgut Ozal has taken giant steps in shaping a
Turkey of the late 20th century.
   New airports, highways and power grids have gone up around the
country, bringing electricity and direct-dial telephone service to
remote mountain villages in the east. Vast housing projects are
being built, replacing the ``gecekondu'' (meaning ``built
overnight''), the shantytowns that gave Ankara and other cities a
Third World look.
   Bankers are high on Turkey as a safe place for foreign
investment and cite its large domestic market and food resources.
   ``When you can feed people, they have more patience,'' said
Citibank's Karper.
   On the drawing board is a vast project to irrigate the barren
southeast Anatolian plain, near Turkey's borders with Syria and
Iraq, to further exploit Turkey's rich agricultural potential and
stem the flow of peasants to the cities in search of work.
   In other words, development in a rush not only to get Turkey on
the European track but also to provide for a fast-growing
population now at 55 million.
   But Turks, and now Ozal himself, have paid a price for this.
Ozal's liberal economic policies aimed at forcing Turkish
industries to compete on European terms and heavy public spending
have spurred economic growth but also triggered inflation running
as high as 75 percent that has impoverished many Turks.
   This in a country where school teachers and other civil servants
earn as little as $100 a month without wage indexing to protect
against inflation so dear to Western Europe's Socialist economies.
   Voters punished Ozal in nationwide local elections in March,
sending his governing Motherland Party to a humiliating third place
in the polls.
   But others factors were also blamed and tell much about Turkey
today.
   Ozal's expressed sympathy for Moslem fundamentalist women,
barred by the Constitutional Court from wearing Islamic headscarves
on university campuses, apparently cost him the votes of millions
of ``secular'' Turks. The fundamentalist vote, about 10 percent of
the electorate, went to a religious party.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
