<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--MedicalResidents-AIDS Adv20   04-17 1172</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Medical Residents-AIDS, Adv 20,1197</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, April 20, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AIDS Reduces The Ranks Of Residents At NYC Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kings County Hospital is the Parris Island of
American medicine, a sometimes hellish boot camp that tuns out
seasoned professionals.
   It has 140 internists in training, more than any other U.S.
institution, and some of the city's poorest and sickest people.
Recruiting a few good men and women, however, has been getting
harder and harder.
   Five years ago, 90 percent of the hospital's medicine residents
_ staff doctors in training _ were graduates of American medical
schools; today, less than half are. Even in the worst years, Kings
County could count on getting 20 to 25 graduates of the medical
school of the State University of New York, with which it is
affiliated; last year not a single SUNY graduate applied, and only
three of 60 first-year residents are from American schools.
   There are a many reasons why young doctors might shun a hospital
like Kings County, but here's the most obvious: Half the patients
in the internal medicine service have AIDS. ``That may have been
the straw that broke the camel's back,'' says Dr. Richard Schwartz,
the medical school's provost.
   With more than 8,800 residents, New York City hospitals train
almost 10 percent of the nation's physicians _ three times more
than any other city. But at a time when the hospitals need more
residents than ever, the quality and quantity of applicants is
declining. Leading teaching hospitals can't attract their top
recruits, and others have scrambled to fill their residency slots
with graduates of foreign medical schools.
   In recent years fewer U.S. medical students have gone into less
lucrative ``primary care'' specialities like internal medicine and
pediatrics. New York seems to be having more trouble attracting
such residents than other cities and one thing that sets it apart
from them is AIDS. It has a fourth of the nation's cases, and in
two years as many as 10,000 of its 25,000 general hospital beds
could be filled by AIDS patients.
   Although the chances of doctors catching acquired immune
deficiency syndrome from their patients are low, a survey at New
York and San Francisco hospitals found that fear of AIDS
preoccupied doctors and gave them nightmares.
   Medical students ``can be so overwhelmed with AIDS patients you
don't get the broad experience a resident wants,'' says Caroline
Reich of Emory University, chairman-elect of student
representatives to the American Association of Medical Colleges.
   A residency is supposed to expose young physicians to a wide
variety of illnesses and patients; doctors worry that if too many
of their patients have AIDS, their exposure becomes too narrow and
their diagnostic skills atrophy. A residency is also supposed to be
educational but AIDS patients are so sick that their care leaves
little time for study or consultation with senior doctors.
   Donald Wilson is chief of medicine at Kings County Hospital.
When he was making his hospital rounds as a resident 25 years ago,
he usually had to spend only five to 10 minutes with each patient.
``A good proportion of them weren't particularly sick,'' he says.
   Now, though, ``one AIDS patient might require as much time and
attention as six of the people I used to see,'' Wilson says. ``It
takes an enormous toll, physicially and emotionally, on our staff.''
   AIDS is the health care crisis of the decade, but in much of the
nation it remains an exotic curiosity. ``Most people who are
looking to go into private practice don't think they'll be seeing
many AIDS patients and don't feel they need an intensive exposure
to AIDS during their residency,'' says Cindy Osman of Brown
University, president of the American Medical Student Association.
   Some doctors and students argue that caring for AIDS patients is
good training. ``It doesn't sound nice to say it, but AIDS patients
have lots of medical problems, and the sickest patients are often
the ones you learn the most from,'' says Ron Samuels of Syracuse
University Medical School, who plans to do his pediatric residency
a New York City hospital.
   The real problem may not be AIDS per se but the type of AIDS
patients increasingly entering New York hospitals: intravenous drug
abusers. Nationally, AIDS is spreading fastest among drug users,
their sex partners and children, and New York City has about a
third of all such cases. Drug abusers have surpassed gay men in
newly reported cases in the city.
   The average drug-addicted AIDS patient is a physician's
nightmare: he requires vast amounts of care, although very little
can be done to help him. He frequently fails to follow medical
instructions, and often resents the doctor's inability to halt his
decline.
   ``An important part of medicine is identifying with the patient,
knowing how to talk to them,'' says Michael Caldwell, a student at
Mount Sinai Medical School. ``But that's so lacking with a lot of
these AIDS patients.
   ``I have nothing in common with a male prostitute drug addict. I
have sympathy for him, but I can't empathize.''
   Homosexual men, on the other hand, are generally regarded as
good patients. They tend to have supportive relatives and friends
and a respect for medical authority. At San Francisco General
Hospital, which has relatively few drug addicts, applications for
internal medicine residencies has increased.
   The burden of caring for AIDS patients is accentuated by a
shortage of nurses and support staff. That translates into the bane
of every resident _ scut, hospital slang for necessary but
non-medical tasks that can be performed by non-physicians, such as
taking blood or delivering medical records.
   If students think New York is short of people to help with scut,
they'll give its hospitals a wide berth, said Clay Balentine,
chairman of student representatives to the American Association of
Medical Colleges. ``The time you spend pushing a wheel chair is
time you can't spend reading.''
   At elite institutions like Columbia Presbyterian Hospital and
New York University-Bellevue Hospital, AIDS and its related
problems have merely made residency programs less selective. At
others, it has meant an increase in the number of foreign medical
school graduates hired as residents.
   Although everyone pays lip service to the notion that foreign
medical school grads _ FMGs, as they're called _ aren't necessarily
inferior to AMGs, the best teaching hospitals take virtually
nothing but AMGs because they are a known commodity. This attitude,
passed to students, guarantees segregation.
   ``If a program has a high percentage of foreign school grads,
that program is that much less attractive to American school
students,'' says Beth Aklo, a fourth-year medical student at the
University of Connecticut and a student representative to the
medical colleges association.
   ``While most of us feel that the good students at foreign
medical schools are as as good as U.S. grads, the bad are really
bad. They couldn't get out of American schools. Doctors don't want
to work with other doctors who are weak.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for April 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
