<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0734EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-BusinessHighlights     04-17 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0825</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventy-five years after the nation was
introduced to Form 1040, Americans are closing another
return-filing season with several million taxpayers apparently
putting off the chore until tonight's midnight deadline.
   The Internal Revenue Service promised that its walk-in offices
would remain open on the final day until every taxpayer with a
question was served. The Postal Service went out of its way to
receive returns and make sure they were postmarked before midnight.
   Taxpayers were given an extra two days to file because the April
15 deadline fell on Saturday. Residents of New England and most of
New York state have until Tuesday midnight because today is a legal
holiday, Patriot's Day, in Massachusetts, site of the IRS service
center that receives returns from those states.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices rose a moderate 0.4 percent
in March, the government said in a report that buoyed spirits on
Wall Street, where fears of spiraling inflation had risen in tandem
with earlier steep price increases.
   Analysts said that while last month's restrained gain in the
Producer Price Index for finished goods should allay fears that
inflation will skyrocket, it does indicate that price rises persist.
   March's 0.4 percent gain, combined with steep gains of 1.0
percent in January and February, works out to a compound annual
inflation rate of 10.2 percent for the first quarter of 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit widened
sharply in February, the government said, bolstering economists'
belief that improvement in the nation's trade performance is
fizzling.
   The Commerce Department said Friday the monthly, seasonally
adjusted deficit swelled 20.9 percent to $10.5 billion, up from a
revised $8.68 billion in January. The deterioration reflected a 5.3
percent increase in imports, which swamped a slight 0.6 percent
improvement in sales of U.S. goods abroad.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and congressional leaders have
announced a showpiece budget compromise to reduce the 1990 federal
deficit to under $100 billion without raising taxes.
   But the pact Friday put off most hard decisions and Democratic
leaders suggested it could open the way to tax increases next year.
Bush called the pact a ``first manageable step'' in the
deficit-fighting journey.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Junk bond dynamo Michael Milken has agreed to
set aside about $700 million of his assets to guarantee payment if
he is convicted of fraud and racketeering charges in the
government's largest-ever securities prosecution.
   The former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. financier also was
ordered Friday to post a $1 million bond and surrender his passport
in exchange for his freedom until an expected trial later this year
culminating Wall Street's insider trading scandals.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and federal officials dissected
Exxon's cleanup plan for hundreds of miles of shoreline as an
environmentally risky steam-cleaning method was tested on rocks
blackened by America's worst oil spill.
   Oil from the 10.1 million-gallon spill, mostly in the form of
tar balls and mousse-like foam, on Sunday threatened Homer and
other ports on fish-rich Cook Inlet. In Kodiak, the nation's No. 1
fishing port, herring from a closed fishery were examined for
contamination.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said its
first-quarter profit rose 1.8 percent excluding an accounting
change, and the stock market responded favorably to the news.
   The gain Friday came in spite of a chip problem that caused a
delay in shipment of mainframe computers, the biggest and most
profitable part of IBM's product line. IBM's stock rose $1.62{ to
$110.87{ in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading,
contributing to Wall Street's best day since October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smith
received about $3.6 million in salary and benefits last year,
placing last in terms of compensation among the chiefs of the
nation's Big Three automakers, GM said.
   In its annual proxy statement issued Friday, the nation's
largest automaker said Smith received $983,000 in salary, exercised
$1 million in stock options and had $68,833 contributed by the
company to a savings and stock purchase plan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ran up its sharpest gain in nearly six months
Friday, inspired by an apparent easing of inflationary pressures.
The Dow Jones industrials average jumped 41.06 to 2,337.06, for its
best single-day showing since it rose 43.92 points last Oct. 20.
   The dollar finished mostly lower in light domestic dealings.
   The bond market had its best day since early December.
   Fears that drought conditions will persist for another year in
the Midwest drove grain and soybean futures prices up sharply on
the Chicago Board of Trade. Coffee futures surged; platinum gained
while gold and silver futures retreated; petroleum prices rose; and
livestock and meat futures were mostly higher.
</TEXT>
