<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0839EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Stroh'sImage     04-17 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stroh's Image,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit-Based Brewer Cracks Open A New Image</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five years after what company officials admit was
a false start in trying to break out of the Midwest, Stroh's beer
is taking a new look and message nationwide.
   Stroh Brewery Co. has sunk $50 million into the marketing
campaign for its flagship brand that begins this week. Experts will
be watching closely to see whether the effort founders amid flat
beer sales in recent years and a market increasingly dominated by
industry-leaders Anheuser-Busch and Miller.
   ``Once you get beyond the No. 1 and No. 2 brewers, Nos. 3, 4 and
5 all face problems,'' said Jerry Steinman, editor of Beer
Marketers Insights, an industry journal. ``They have to look to
take sales from the big guys, but that's like taking it from
gorillas.''
   Stroh, privately held and based in Detroit, is the nation's
third-largest brewer. But its entire lineup holds just an 11
percent share of the U.S. beer market, compared with 41.9 percent
for Anheuser-Busch and 21.6 percent for Miller, according to
Beverage Industry Magazine.
   Company sources told The Detroit News that Stroh annual revenues
have stagnated at $1.5 billion annually since 1985. And the Stroh's
brand itself holds only 2 percent of the national market, Beverage
Industry said.
   The new campaign includes revamped advertising, redesigned
containers and even new posters and mirrors to be distributed to
bars and party stores.
   ``We consider this a continuation of our (national) introduction
of the brand,'' said William L. Henry, Stroh vice president of
marketing.
   ``Our opportunity with Stroh's is to appeal to a lot of people
in America who have never even had a Stroh's,'' said Hal Riney, a
San Francisco advertising executive who created the new campaign.
``And there are millions of those.''
   Stroh will spend $20 million on Riney's new ads, which will
stress both the new packaging and the company's 200-year heritage
as a family enterprise. Anheuser-Busch, by comparison, spent an
estimated $130 million in 1988 just to advertise Budweiser.
   Another industry expert questioned whether Stroh could overcome
the growing piles of money that Anheuser-Busch and Miller are
throwing into a market diluted in recent years by beverages other
than beer.
   ``I know of no brewers in the history of the brewing industry
who have ever turned around a brand after a serious slide,'' said
Robert Weinberg, head of R.S. Weinberg &amp; Associates. ``It's a very
unforgiving industry.''
   Stroh still has other brands on which to fall back, including
Old Milwaukee, Schlitz and Schaefer, all of which it acquired
earlier this decade. But officials are hopeful of reviving the
company's namesake brand.
   ``In my 11 years here, this is the most striking set of changes
I've seen,'' Stroh president Roger Fridholm said. ``I think we have
a chance of getting some very positive consumer reaction.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0849EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest-Perpich     04-17 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest-Perpich,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Perpich Holds Secret Meeting With Davis In San Francisco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines suitor Marvin Davis is
determined to continue with his bid to buy the airline, Gov. Rudy
Perpich said today after meeting secretly in San Francisco with the
billionaire oilman.
   ``He's serious,'' Perpich said early today in a telephone
interview from his hotel room in Atlanta. ``He said he's going to
the mat, and I believe him.''
   Davis' $2.62 billion offer for NWA Inc., Northwest's parent, has
been rejected by the company's board, but Perpich said Davis still
plans to outline today how he would pay for the buyout of the
nation's fourth-largest carrier.
   Neither Davis nor a spokesman could be reached immediately for
comment.
   Perpich, who has led efforts to stop Davis' attempted takeover,
met Sunday morning with Davis, who flew into San Francisco
International Airport on his private jet. Perpich was in California
on other state business.
   KSTP-TV taped the two shaking hands on the tarmac before the
90-minute meeting.
   Perpich said he had heard talk that Davis has been unable to put
together financing to buy Northwest, and ``I was hoping to hear
that (Davis was) going to back off.''
   But the governor said he found a determined Davis.
   ``He knows what he wants,'' Perpich said. ``This (Northwest) is
what he wants. He's not going away. I think it's (the takeover
battle) going to be a long one.''
   Perpich said he left the meeting with a favorable impression of
Davis, but he added that he will continue his effort to stop the
takeover.
   ``Some people were saying he's in it just to make a quick
buck,'' the governor said. ``That's not his intent. He's put a lot
of money into this effort.''
   Davis told Perpich he also considered making offers for Eastern
Airlines and Trans World Airlines.
   ``He's interested in Northwest because it goes to the Far East,
and that's the future,'' the governor said. ``I think this is going
to be the Super Bowl of takeovers.''
   Perpich said the meeting gave him a chance to tell Davis the
importance of keeping intact the airline, which employees more than
15,000 people in Minnesota.
   Perpich said Davis assured him that jobs and the airline hub
would stay in Minnesota, and that Davis planned further expansion
in the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
