<DOCNO> AP890417-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0956EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Stocks     04-17 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Slightly Firmer At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were moderately firmer in dull
trading early Monday afternoon as traders said the market lacked a
unifying theme to push it in either direction.
   ``There's not a lot of action,'' said one British dealer. ``We
always find Mondays are a bit hesitant and it takes some time for
the market to get rekindled from the weekend.''
   British economic indicators released late in the morning did
little to inspire more activity in the market, dealers said.
   Some market watchers said most eyes were on the futures market,
where stock-index futures traded up to a 60-point premium over the
cash market.
   Others said the onset of a three-week trading account tended to
put off investment decisions until a clear short-term direction for
the market could be discerned.
   At noontime in London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was hovering just above 2,058.0, a gain of 4
points, or .19 percent. The market made its way toward the 2,065.3
intraday high in early trading, while its late morning low point
was 2,056.8.
   At 11 a.m. GMT, the narrower Financial Times 30-share index was
off 2.3 points at 1,688.7.
   Turnover amounted to 218.3 million shares by midday.
</TEXT>
