<DOCNO> AP890417-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1019EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     04-17 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0324</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pulled back in early trading
today, retracing some of Friday's sharp gains ahead of the March
consumer price data.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 4.22 points to
2,332.84 after a half-hour of trading at 10 a.m. EDT.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers on the Big Board by about
3 to 2, with 553 issues up, 377 down and 565 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 17.71 million shares.
   Analysts said some market players decided to take profits and a
brief respite after Friday's big gains.
   ``The market has a tendency to follow a pop like Friday with a
pullback,'' said Larry Wachtel, vice president of Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. ``Also, despite the producer price numbers, there
is some concern that consumer prices might not be that good.''
   The government is scheduled to release data on consumer prices
for March on Tuesday.
   The market rallied from a week-long stupor on Friday after the
government released several economic reports which the market
interpreted as indicating inflationary pressures were easing.
Producer prices, which is a gauge of inflation at the wholesale
level, rose 0.4 percent last month, after the index grew by 1
percent in each of the two previous months, the government said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.24 to 168.65.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
0.14 to 335.68.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 41.06 points
to 2,337.06, for its best single-day showing since it rose 43.92
points last Oct. 20.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 5 to 2 on the
NYSE, with 1,072 up, 393 down and 468 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 169.78 million shares, against 141.59
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
