<FIRST>u f PM-ControlData 1stLd-Writethru f0032 04-17 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Control Data, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0032,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Control Data To Drop Supercomputer Business; Cut 3,100 Employees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details on Control Data's financial
health, products, prospects and its stock price. No pickup. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Money-losing Control Data Corp. today said it
will eliminate its supercomputer business and make other cuts that
will cost 3,100 jobs.
   The computer maker decided it ``can't afford to continue product
development across such a wide section of products,'' said
spokesman Frank Ryan.
   The move will result in restructuring charges of $490 million,
including $350 million from liquidation of ETA Systems, the
subsidiary started in 1983 to compete with Twin Cities rival Cray
Research Inc. and other supercomputer makers.
   Asked if Control Data attempted to sell ETA Systems, Ryan said,
``We looked at all options. The shutdown was the most practical.''
   ETA has never made money for Control Data. In 1988 it had
operating losses of about $100 million. It has sold 34 machines
ranging in price from $1 million to $20 million.
   ETA will account for 800 of the 3,100 layoffs, with the rest
made in corporate ranks and other sectors, Ryan said.
   Ryan said the company will continue to service its supercomputer
customers. Besides focusing on its Cyber mainframe computers,
Control Data will also build its data storage business and
businesses such as lottery equipment for states.
   Control Data stock dropped 62{ cents to $21.75 in early morning
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Chairman Robert Price said the company, which has had five
consecutive years of financial difficulty, said the restructuring
should result in a profitable second half of 1989 and set the stage
for sustained growth.
   Control Data has had two consecutive quarterly losses, including
a $12.8 million loss in the fourth quarter of 1988. For the year,
the company had a profit of $1.7 million after earning $19.3
million in 1987 and losing a total of $832 million in 1986 and 1985.
   Ryan said most of the restructuring costs will be charged
against the second quarter of this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-PPG     04-17 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-PPG,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coatings, Chemicals Pace Record First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PPG Industries Inc. said today that higher
sales and operating earnings in its coatings and chemicals
businesses helped produce the company's best first quarter ever,
with a 9 percent profit increase.
   The company said after-tax earnings rose to $129.8 million, or
$1.15 per share, in the first 1989 quarter from $118.6 million, or
$1.07 per share, in 1988's first quarter. Sales increased 6 percent
to $1.459 billion from $1.373 billion.
   Lower sales of flatglass and unfavorable currency transactions
washed out sales gains for original and replacement auto glass, the
Pittsburgh-based company said.
   Sales of glass, PPG's leading product, slid 1.7 percent to $588
million from $598 million. Operating earnings for the unit dropped
18.3 percent to $94 million from $115 million.
   Increased sales of automotive paint and industrial coatings and
progress in controlling costs overcame the less favorable currency
exchange rates in PPG's second-largest line. Unit sales rose 10
percent to $512 million from $465 million, and operating earnings
rose 17.6 percent to $80 million from $68 million.
   Improved prices and sales volume for most basic and specialty
chemicals, including a new chemical plant in Taiwan, helped lift
the unit's revenue 40.7 percent to $315 million from $261 million
and boost operating earnings 20.6 percent to $76 million from $63
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
