<DOCNO> AP890417-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-17 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher On Dry Weather Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures opened strongly this
morning on the Chicago Board of Trade amid fears that the Midwest's
unusually dry spring will extend into the growing season.
   Wheat futures were slightly higher in early trading.
   Memories of last summer's drought remain fresh in traders'
minds, and each day without rain in the Corn Belt bolsters the
bullish trend.
   Of special concern is the low level of subsoil moisture in Iowa
and northwestern Illinois, some of the nation's prime corn and
soybean country.
   The Des Moines Register is reporting that an Iowa State
University study has found Iowa's soil moisture to be at about half
the normal level across much of the state.
   The National Weather Service is predicting increased rainfall in
the western Corn Belt late this week and early next week. But many
private forecasters foresee little rain and warmer temperatures.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 2\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.14 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 4 cents higher with May at $2.74 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
5} cents higher with May at $1.97{ a bushel; soybeans were 6} cents
to 9\ cents higher with May at $7.40 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were moderately higher while pork futures were
mixed in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .40 cent higher with June at 71.35
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .57 cent higher with
May at 76.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to .05
cent higher with June at 46.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent to .35 cent higher with May at 33.50 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
