<FIRST>r f PM-Lockheed-CargoPlanes 1stLd-Writethru f0014 04-17 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lockheed-Cargo Planes, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0014,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockheed To Deliver Last Of 50 C-5B Planes To Air Force</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with last plane delivered; PICKS
UP 5th graf pvs, `The C-5B ...' Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. today delivered the last of 50
C-5B jumbo cargo planes to the Air Force, completing a seven-year,
$6.9 billion contract that drew accusations of greed from Congress.
   The final C-5B, the biggest air cargo carrier in the free world,
took off after a ceremony, made a salute lap around Lockheed
Aeronautical Systems Co. headquarters in suburban Marietta and then
headed for the air base at Dover, Del.
   The company has no plans for further production of the C-5B,
said Robert Z. Christopher, director of the C-5 program. Lockheed
Aeronautical is a division of Lockheed Corp., the Calabasas,
Calif.-based aeronautics giant.
   The C-5B is 248 feet long, has a wing span of 223 feet and a
65-foot, T-shaped tail, high as a six-story building.
   The jet, an updated version of the C-5A, can carry almost any
piece of the Army's hardware _ two 50-ton M-1 tanks, for example.
   It has been used recently for such non-military missions as
carrying equipment and supplies to the site of the Exxon Valdez oil
spill in Alaska and aid to the victims of the earthquake in the
Soviet republic of Armenia, said Air Force spokesman Capt. Tom
Dolney.
   The huge contract has been a boon to the Atlanta-area, providing
thousands of jobs and pumping millions of subcontracting dollars
into 40 states.
   Today's ceremony marked a happy landing in the flight of the
C-5B project. But it was a bumpy ride.
   Lockheed won the contract in 1982, beating out Boeing and
McDonnell Douglas. The original pact was for $7.8 billion.
   Production of the plane's predecessor, the C-5A, was marred by
revelations that the Air Force had purchased ineffective repair
kits from Lockheed that included $229.94 nickel-sized washers.
   Shortly before the first C-5B was to be delivered in late 1985,
it was discovered that tens of thousands of nuts on the planes had
to be replaced because the ones installed were the wrong kind.
   The Pentagon accused the company of inflating the C-5B contract
by as much as $500 million by withholding details of a proposed
two-tier wage system for its new employees; by 1987 the price tag
had been whittled down to $6.9 billion.
   A review by the General Accounting Office, Congress'
investigative arm, found that in late 1986 Lockheed proposed to
charge the government $211.13 for an inch-long shim, a metal wedge
that was an excess part from C-5B production and originally valued
at $22.09.
   Last month, the Air Force said it had imposed flight
restrictions on 20 C-5B's because of a problem with the pylon, the
assembly that holds the jet engine to the wing.
   Lockheed has proposed to the Air Force that the plant maintain
its C-5B tooling, company spokesman Doug Oliver said.
   ``Their decision will pretty much tell us what the future of the
C-5B is,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0250 </DOCNO>
