<FIRST>u f PM-Qintex 1stLd-Writethru f0029 04-17 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Qintex, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0029,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Qintex Board Approves Acquisition of MGM-UA</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: CLARIFIES that Australian buyer getting United Artists and U.S.
financier keeping MGM studio; edits and adds detail throughout. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $1 billion sale of the United
Artists movie studio to Australia's Qintex Entertainment Inc. has
been approved by the Quintex board of directors, the company
announced today.
   The deal, in essence, will split the present MGM-UA
Communications Co., and leave majority shareholder Kirk Kerkorian
in control of the MGM portion of the business.
   The renamed United Artists Corp. would be the first big American
motion picture studio to pass into foreign hands.
Australian-turned-U.S. citizen Rupert Murdoch owns 20th Century Fox
Film Corp. through his News Corp.
   Qintex Entertainment is a TV company that financed part of the
CBS miniseries ``Lonesome Dove'' and bills itself as Australia's
largest independent TV production and distribution company.
   United Artists, one of the five dominant U.S. movie studios,
holds the rights to 4,000 movies, including the ``The Pink
Panther'' and James Bond series and Rocky films.
   The sale agreement calls for Qintex to pay $20 a share, or about
$1 billion, for MGM-UA.
   Financier Kirkorian, who holds 82 percent of MGM-UA stock, then
will buy back MGM assets for $250 million. Included in the ``new''
MGM will be movie and TV production assets and a library of 34
recent films, including ``Moonstruck'' and ``A Fish Called Wanda.''
   The deal is expected to close in late summer.
   MGM-UA lost $39.5 million in the first quarter of its 1989
fiscal year. The loss was attributed to increased interest expense
and high write-offs on movies in production and already released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
