<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Fall In Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell sharply Monday against major
currencies in European trading after signs of a slowdown in the
American economy. Gold prices also dropped.
   Foreign exchange dealers said recent U.S. economic statistics
had confused their market about whether the dollar was headed
higher or lower and the uncertainty caused a drop.
   They said the main factors had been the 20.9 percent swelling in
the U.S. trade deficit to $10.5 billion in February and the slowing
of the growth rate in U.S. producer prices.
   The U.S. consumer price index due on Tuesday could set the
dollar's tone for the rest of the week, dealers said. One dealer
said if the rise in the index is small, the dollar could drop from
1.85 German marks to 1.83.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7095 late Monday, more
expensive for buyers than Friday's $1.7000.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Friday's
late rates: 1.8565 West German marks, down from 1.8725; 1.6385
Swiss francs, down from 1.6510; 6.2825 French francs, down from
6.3350; 2.0953 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1145; 1,364.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,374.25; 1.1855 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1875.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 131.83 Japanese yen, down
from 132.55 at Friday's close. In London late Monday the dollar
traded lower at 131.70 yen.
   Gold bullion traded late in London, the major market, at $385.00
bid a troy ounce, down from $386.50. The late bid price in Zurich
was $384.50, down from $387.00.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $385.65, down from $382.65.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.80 a troy
ounce, down from $5.89.
</TEXT>
