<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1417EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ToxicCleanups Bjt   04-17 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toxic Cleanups, Bjt,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insurers, Businesses Fight Over Who Pays For Multibillion-dollar
Cleanups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The start of multibillion-dollar industrial
waste cleanups around the nation has triggered a legal war between
insurance companies and corporate polluters over who should foot
the bill.
   Insurers last week won their second battle in recent months,
when a New Jersey judge ruled that 126 insurers for former Diamond
Shamrock Co. bore no liability for injuries caused by the
production of a toxic byproduct of the defoliant Agent Orange.
   Lawyers said the decision by Superior Court Judge Reginald
Stanton in Morristown will have bearing on more than 50 similar
lawsuits involving billions of dollars around the country.
Potentially, the problem could involve thousands of cleanup sites.
   The Diamond Shamrock case is ``part of a larger struggle that's
going on between the insurance industry and companies'' facing
cleanup costs, said Jacquie Warren, a lawyer with the Natural
Resources Defense Council in New York.
   In December, a jury found Shell Oil Co. liable for cleaning up
the Rocky Mountain Arsenal near Denver, where the company leased
land from the Army from 1952 to 1982 for a pesticide production
plant.
   The jury ruled that Shell could not collect from its more than
250 insurers for cleanup and injury costs at the site estimated by
the federal government in 1983 at $1.8 billion.
   ``I think that the insurance companies are now engaged in a
massive nationwide effort in courts and the media to try to renege
on their obligations to their policy-holder,'' said Eugene
Anderson, a New York lawyer whose firm represents more than 40
policy-holders fighting for insurance coverage.
   Judge Stanton ruled that Diamond Shamrock's insurance policies
do not cover an industrial cleanup of more than $25 million because
the company knowingly bypassed environmental controls, polluting
the Passaic River and land around a Newark plant with dioxin.
   The company, then known as Diamond Alkali, made Agent Orange and
other herbicides at the Newark plant from 1951 to 1969. A byproduct
was dioxin, which has been linked to various cancers, liver
disease, birth defects and a severe skin rash.
   ``Diamond's conduct in operating the Newark plant was
unacceptably wrong and irresponsible,'' Stanton wrote in a 50-page
opinion. ``Diamond always put its narrowly perceived economic
interest first. It deliberately and persistently cheated on the
limited environmental regulations which were in place.''
   But Stanton did order the insurers to pay the company's $23
million share of a $180 million settlement with Vietnam War victims
of Agent Orange, which was used to strip natural cover from
guerillas.
   For Maxus Energy Corp. of Dallas, Diamond Shamrock's parent, the
cleanup cost in Newark will exceed $25 million. Maxus said it
intervened as soon as dioxin was found at the site in 1983 and
cooperated with environmental officials in its removal.
   Diamond Alkali was a predecessor of Diamond Shamrock, which was
sold to Occidental Petroleum Corp. in 1986. Maxus Energy assumed
liability for cleanups of certain sites, including the Newark plant.
   After the 1986 sale, Maxus set aside a $75 million reserve for
cleanup costs, spokeswoman Ginger Shearburn said.
   Maxus called Stanton's ruling on the dioxin ``incorrect'' and is
considering an appeal. Its stock dropped 12{ cents to $7.62{
Wednesday, a day after the decision was released to lawyers, and
was trading in the $7 range Monday.
   Stanton's ruling goes against much of the state's case law on
the subject, which is generally favorable to policy-holders,
lawyers said. More than a dozen such lawsuits have been filed in
New Jersey, the most in the nation.
   Diamond Shamrock sued its insurers over the Newark plant in
1984. Two years later it again sued its insurers, seeking coverage
for about 20 non-dioxin sites nationwide.
   Robert Bates, attorney for American Re-Insurance Co. of
Princeton, a defendant in the Morristown lawsuits, said Stanton's
decision could have a major impact on the second case, in which
cleanup costs were not available.
   Ms. Warren of the Natural Resources Defense Council, an
environmental activist group, said insurance policies should be
expensive enough and companies should assume enough risk to
guarantee they handle and dispose of dangerous materials properly.
   But she added that society needs an ``insurance cushion'' to
protect an innocent third party if a company cannot pay for a
cleanup. ``It's a fine line to draw,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0254 </DOCNO>
