<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-UnitedTelecom     04-17 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-United Telecom,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>First-Quarter Income Up Sharply; US Sprint ``Turns Corner''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Telecommunications Inc., saying
its US Sprint unit has ``turned the corner,'' reported Monday that
companywide earnings more than doubled in the first quarter.
   United Telecom said it earned $76.4 million, or 73 cents a
share, during the quarter ended March 31, up from $34.4 million, or
33 cents a share, in the first quarter of 1988.
   The earnings came on an 18 percent increase in consolidated
revenue, to $1.77 billion from $1.5 billion.
   US Sprint Communications Co., the long-distance telephone
operation which lost $124 million in the first quarter of 1988, had
operating income of $27.5 million this time. Its operating revenue
increase 30 percent to $984 million from about $757 million a year
earlier.
   A 9 percent gain in traffic volume offset the effects of a
first-quarter price decrease, producing revenue gains of 6 percent
over the fourth quarter of 1988.
   ``Clearly, US Sprint has turned the corner,'' said United
Telecom President William T. Esrey.
   US Sprint was formed in July 1986 as a joint venture in which
United Telecom and GTE Corp. combined their long-distance and data
communications subsidiaries. United Telecom, which also provides
local phone service in several states, purchased controlling
interest last year.
   Esrey cited significant new revenue growth opportunities in the
international market, the public pay phone market and a contract
with the federal government. He also said the company has
strengthened its capabiliities to penetrate the ``800'' and private
line markets and will benefit from the entry of its Sprint Services
unit into the ``900'' and operator services markets.
   Sprint Services, formed to provide directory assistance, credit
card validation and operator assistance for person-to-person and
collect calls for US Sprint customers, will start service by
mid-year.
</TEXT>
