<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-EthanolLawsuit     04-17 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethanol Lawsuit,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Dismiss Lawsuit By Ethanol Producers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has refused to dismiss a
$2.1 billion antitrust lawsuit filed by fuel alcohol producers
against four major oil companies.
   U.S. District Court Judge Harold Baker on Friday rejected the
oil companies' argument that the ethanol producers were not in
competition with them and therefore had no financial interest that
would lead them to sue.
   Seven ethanol producers allege that the oil companies _ Marathon
Petroleum Co., Shell Oil Co., AMOCO Oil Co., and Chevron U.S.A. _
conspired to ruin the market for gasohol, a blend of 90 percent
gasoline and 10 percent ethanol.
   Attorney Bob Wright of Lafayette, La., representing the
plaintiffs, has argued that the oil companies tried to ``retard''
the growth of the ethanol industry.
   The judge ruled the oil companies and the ethanol producers were
in competition for the non-diesel automobile fuel market.
   The ethanol makers contend the oil companies used signs on their
gasoline pumps saying such things as ``our gasoline contains no
alcohol or ethanol'' to discourage motorists from using gasohol.
   Ethanol, which can be made from corn, increases the octane of
gasoline and reduces pollution in automobile emissions, according
to the National Corn Growers Association.
   The plaintiffs are Greater Rockford Energy and Technology Corp.,
of Rockford; Shepherd Oil Inc., of Jennings, La.; Vidalia Ethanol
Ltd., of Vidalia, La.; Lakefield Ethanol Inc., of Lakefield, Minn.;
A.E. Montana Inc., of Amsterdam, Mont.; Shreveport Ethanol Inc., of
Shreveport, La.; and Alpebo Inc., of Jennings, La.
</TEXT>
