<FIRST>r f AM-Superbroker-Lawsuit     04-17 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Superbroker-Lawsuit,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Stockbroker and PaineWebber Slug It Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto NXJ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a long way from Wall Street to the
6th floor of Bridgeport Superior Court, but a lawsuit being heard
here is being closely watched by stockbrokers.
   Closing arguments are to begin Tuesday in a legal dispute that
pits PaineWebber Inc. against one of the so-called ``superbrokers''
it hired away from competitors in the early 1980s, most from Lehman
Brothers Kuhn Loeb Inc.
   Five of the brokers were fired in 1984. They filed suit against
PaineWebber and its parent, PaineWebber Group Inc., claiming the
investment firm lured them away just to capture their multimillion
dollar client base.
   Four of the brokers agreed to arbitration before the case could
go to trial in federal court in Manhattan, but Geoffrey J. Winters
pursued the case and is asking for at least $16 million in damages.
He claims he was fired unjustly.
   The case ended up in the Connecticut courts after PaineWebber
obtained a lien against Winters' Greenwich home to recover a
$300,000 signing bonus he was to repay if he was fired within four
years because of poor performance.
   Perrin Long, an analyst with Lipper Analytical Securities Corp.
in New York, said Wall Street is watching the case with interest
largely because it is highly unsual for brokers to sue their former
employers.
   ``If there is any disagreement, they try to settle it ...
in-house,'' he said Monday. ``They are watching this very closely
... to see whether the suit sets a precedent for future suits.''
   Winters, 46, calls PaineWebber's actions outrageous.
   Alan R. Spirer, an attorney representing PaineWebber, says
Winters has failed to prove the brokerage house did anything
malicious or false.
   The case had its origins in October 1982, when Winters left
Lehman Brothers Kuhn Loeb, now Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., to join
PaineWebber. He and other new employees were touted as
``superbrokers'' in brochures PaineWebber sent out to potential
customers.
   The brokers earned the nickname because each had produced more
than $1 million in annual commissions.
   When he joined PaineWebber, Winters was given two promissary
notes, one for $240,000 and another for $60,000, that were secured
by an advance compensation agreement. The principal amounts for
both were due in five years without interest.
   But on March 23, 1984, PaineWebber fired Winters for alleged
willful misconduct.
   After Winters filed his original lawsuit in New York,
PaineWebber went to court in Connecticut seeking to collect on its
promissary notes.
   Winters denied that he owed PaineWebber any money and filed
seven counterclaims, seeking damages for breach of employment
contract, false and fraudulent promises and defamatory statements.
   PaineWebber won a judgment against Winters who appealed to the
state Supreme Court. The court granted him a new trial in March
1988.
   Winter's attorney, John H. Chaman, and Spirer told the judge
they had agreed on most points to be covered in the final arguments
and would be ready for the arguments Tuesday.
   Spirer also has asked the court to dimiss Winters' counterclaims
before the case gets to the jury.
   Judge Dennis F. Harrigan reserved a decision on the request. He
indicated he would rule after hearing the closing arguments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
