<DOCNO> AP890417-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AnimalRightsProxies     04-17 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Animal Rights Proxies,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Animal Rights Groups Put Issues Before Shareholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a growing movement to force
corporations to disclose more information about animal
experimentation, animal-rights activists are taking their fight
directly to shareholders.
   This year, shareholders at 10 companies will vote on resolutions
proposed by animal-rights activists, an increase of two over 1988,
according to the Washington-based Investor Responsibility Research
Center.
   ``It's a thoughtful and sophisticated way to encourage companies
to seriously consider questions of humane treatment of animals in
connection with their business,'' said attorney Alan Lovenheim, who
has represented about a dozen groups seeking animal-rights
resolutions.
   Corporations generally have opposed the proxy resolutions.
   After years of fruitless picketing against U.S. Surgical Corp.'s
use of dogs in product tests, activists secured a resolution on the
company's proxy ballot for its May 2 annual meeting demanding a
halt to the tests.
   People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals has proxy
resolutions asking eight corporations _ American Home Products
Corp., Avon Products Inc., Bristol-Meyer Co., Colgate-Palmolive
Co., Gillette Co., Greyhound Corp., Schering-Plough Corp. and
Johnson &amp; Johnson _ to cite progress in developing alternatives to
animal testing.
   For the third year, International Business Machines Corp. has
included an animal-rights resolution on its ballot.
   The proposal, filed by an individual shareholder, simply asks
the company to disclose information on animal experiments that it
may conduct. IBM has opposed the resolution.
   On all issues, 170 proxy resolutions have been proposed this
year, about half dealing with South Africa, according to the
Investor Responsibility Research Center, which monitors
shareholders' resolutions.
   In 1985, Lovenheim successfully sued Greenwich-based Iroquois
Brands Ltd., in which he held stock, to get his animal-rights
resolution included for vote in the company's proxy ballot.
Lovenheim wanted to know whether the French farmers who supplied
the company with goose liver were treating the fowl humanely.
   The American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals
drafted a resolution for the McDonald's Corp. proxy ballot this
year, but withdrew it after McDonald's agreed to assess farming
practices used to produce its meat and eggs.
   ``It was gratifying this year to find McDonald's was willing to
sit down and discuss the proposal,'' said Lovenheim, who
represented the ASPCA.
   Lovenheim said the Securities and Exchange Commission has
supported every resolution he has proposed or defended, despite
corporate objections.
   The New England Anti-Vivisection Society last week filed suit in
federal court in Boston against Norwalk-based U.S. Surgical,
charging the company used false information in recommending that a
resolution calling for suspension of animal testing be rejected.
   The society has owned 66 shares of U.S. Surgical, which
manufactures surgical products, since 1983.
   U.S. Surgical has been a target of protests by animal-rights
groups for years, but the dispute drew national attention in
November, when an animal activist allegedly planted a
remote-controlled bomb outside the company's headquarters.
   Authorities said animal activist Fran Trutt of New York City
intended to detonate the bomb and kill U.S. Surgical Chairman Leon
Hirsch. No one was injured in the incident. Trutt is awaiting trial
on a charge of attempted murder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     04-17 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>1st-Qtr Profit Rises at Tribune, McGraw-Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tribune Co. said Monday its first-quarter earnings rose 14
percent from a year ago, while another media concern, McGraw-Hill
Inc., said an accounting change turned what would have been an
earnings decline into a 15.6 percent increase.
   The Chicago-based Tribune Co. said it earned $36.8 million, or
49 cents a share, in the three months ended March 26 compared with
$32.2 million, or 42 cents a share, in the same 1988 period.
   First-quarter revenue rose 6 percent to $553 million from $522
million in 1988.
   Tribune said its operating profit from newspapers including the
Chicago Tribune rose 19 percent to $61.6 million as revenue rose 5
percent to $394 million.
   Its broadcasting and entertainment group had an operating loss
of $1.4 million in contrast with a loss of $3.5 million in the same
quarter in 1988 despite a 15 percent rise in revenue to $105
million.
   The division includes six TV stations, five radio stations, a
syndicated TV news program and the Chicago Cubs baseball team.
   Operating profit from its newsprint operations fell 27 percent
to $16.7 million on steady revenue of $109 million.
   McGraw-Hill, based in New York, said its profit rose to $31.2
million, or 64 cents a share, in the three months ended March 31
compared $27 million, or 56 cents a share, a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue rose 5.2 percent to $416 million from $396
million a year earlier.
   The publishing and information services concern said an
accounting change involving income taxes boosted its first-quarter
profit by $8 million, the cumulative effect of the accounting
change in previous years.
   It said without the change, made in accordance with Financial
Accounting Standards Board standards, the company's profit would
have fallen 14 percent.
   McGraw-Hill said its pre-tax income tumbled 27.8 percent,
reflecting sale of assets including a professional training system,
healthcare publications and an accounting software business. That
was partially offset by tax benefits from those sales, the company
said.
   Its publishing division which includes Business Week magazine,
four television stations and its educational publishing business
had an operating loss of $8.1 million in contrast with a loss of
$3.3 million a year earlier.
   The wider operating loss reflected costs of starting a new
reading series and the acquisition of Random House's college and
school divisions for $200 million last December.
   The operating profit at its information services division fell
13.2 percent to $28.8 million. That division provides data in a
variety of forms to the construction, legal, aerospace and energy
markets among others.
   McGraw-Hill's financial services unit had an operating profit of
$28.2 million, up 34.3 percent from a year earlier. That division
includes the Standard &amp; Poor's debt ratings as well as equity and
commodity information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
