<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Banks     04-17 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chase, Hanover Report Earnings Drop; Security Pacific Has Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chase Manhattan Corp. and Manufacturers Hanover Corp. reported
Monday that their first-quarter profit fell sharply over a year
ago, while another large banking concern, Security Pacific Corp.
posted a healthy gain in earnings.
   Chase, the nation's second largest bank holding company, based
in New York, said it netted $132 million, or $1.27 a share, for the
three months ended March 31, a 52 percent drop from earnings of
$277 million, or $3.09 a share, in 1988.
   The company said last year's income included $161 million from
asset sales and income tax benefits.
   No. 5 Security Pacific, based in Los Angeles, said it earned
$179.3 million, or $1.54 a share, in the quarter, up 22 percent
from $147.2 million, or $1.30 a share, in the first quarter of 1988.
   Manufacturers Hanover, ranked seventh and based in New York,
posted a 27 percent decline in its quarterly profit, to $103
million, or $1.84 a share, from $141 million, or $2.56 a share.
   The 1988 quarter included $40 million from tax benefits and the
sale of one of its subsidaries.
   Chase said it had higher net interest income and an increase in
fees but they were partly offset by lower income from foreign
exchange and other trading activities. The company's provision for
credit losses stood at $150 million in the quarter, the same as a
year ago.
   First-quarter net interest income totaled $797.04 million, up 9
percent from $732.34 million last year.
   Non-interest income fell 34 percent to $420.24 million from
$633.42 million, while non-interest expenses rose 2 percent to
$876.01 million from $$855.74 million.
   Security Pacific said its net interest income totaled $733.8
million, up from $631.4 million a year earlier. Non-interest income
was $431.6 million, up from $421 million in the first quarter of
last year. Non-interest expense totaled $755.4 million, vs. $730.0
million last year.
   Manufacturers Hanover said its net interest income totaled $466
million, compared with $495 million a year ago. Non-interest income
fell to $317 million from $375 million, while non-interest expenses
fell 4 percent to $509 million from $528 million.
</TEXT>
