<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     04-17 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0263</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed narrowly mixed in light,
featureless trading today, as investors turned cautious ahead of
Tuesday's consumer price report.
   The market opened lower, rebounded briefly then edged downward
through the remainder of the session as many participants retreated
to await the latest economic data.
   Analysts said the market is expecing a rise of between 0.4
percent and 0.6 percent in the consumer price index, which is a
gauge of the cost of living. In February, consumer prices rose 0.4
percent.
   ``The whole world revolved around that number today,'' said Jack
Baker, analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``People were
reluctant to take positions pending the outcome.''
   On Friday, the market had rallied sharply after the government
reported that the producer price index rose 0.4 percent in March.
The market interpreted the data as good news after rises of 1
percent in each of the previous two months.
   Economists said the PPI, a measure of inflation at the wholesale
level, was in line with other data that suggested the economy is
slowing and that the Federal Reserve probably would not be pushing
interest rates up in the immediate future.
   ``People realized that Friday might have been too much too
soon,'' said Philip Puccio, senior vice president at Dillon, Read &amp;
Co.
   Even before trading activity slowed, analysts said volume was
fairly light with many players taking the week off in preparation
for the Jewish holiday of Passover on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
