<FIRST>r f AM-OilPrices     04-17 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gasoline Futures Prices Soar</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Spill-Gasoline Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline prices soared to three-year highs
Monday amid continued worries about supplies following the Alaskan
oil spill.
   The gasoline rally, which included a 2-cent-a-gallon increase,
helped push up prices of crude oil and other refined petroleum
products traded on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Andrew Lebow, a senior energy analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man
International Futures Inc., said the rise in gasoline futures
largely reflects concern about whether supply will meet growing
demand as the summer driving season approaches.
   ``Those concerns are globally,'' Lebow said.
   Supply worries escalated after an Exxon oil tanker spilled 10
million gallons of oil in Valdez, Alaska, last month, temporarily
choking off crucial oil shipping lanes.
   In the three weeks following the March 24 spill, gasoline prices
on the retail level jumped 10 to 30 cents a gallon across the
country.
   On the New York Merc, the May contract for wholesale unleaded
gasoline jumped 2.06 cents to 72.08 cents a gallon Monday, after
rising 1.21 cents on Friday.
   Lebow said Monday's closing price was the highest since the
first quarter of 1986.
   The May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 53 cents to $21.22 a 42-gallon
barrel, after a 40-cent increase on Friday.
   May wholesale home heating oil settled at 53.76 cents a gallon,
up 0.85 cent. The contract had risen 0.77 cent Friday.
</TEXT>
