<FIRST>r f AM-Soviet-Computers     04-17 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Computers,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Reporters To Use Computers Sold By U.S. Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMPBELL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. marketing firm said Monday it
will sell 1,500 laptop computers made in Hong Kong to the Soviet
Union for use by reporters for Tass News Service.
   Holographic Systems Inc. said the Defense Department tried to
block the $2.1 million sale of computers with Cyrillic keyboards
but received Commerce Department approval.
   The computers, made by Bondwell International of Hong Kong and
Fremont, Calif., use Intel Corp.'s 80286 chip and are more powerful
than the laptops most commonly used by American reporters.
   The Defense Department initially objected to the sale, citing
the quantity of computers and complaining they were ``ruggedized''
for possible use in military situations.
   Glenn G. Smith, president of Holographic Systems, denied the
charge. He said the deal went through recently after the Defense
Department failed to file a further objection following a
recommendation for approval by Commerce.
   Smith, who also is negotiating a joint venture with the Soviet
Ministry of Railways for a $20 million executive center and health
fitness club for foreign executives, said the laptop sale took
three months to get an export license.
   ``The government ought to find a way to expedite the licensing
and get the Defense Department out of some of these non-strategic
items, like (personal computers),'' Smith said. ``The Soviets can
go to Singapore and get a license in seven days.''
</TEXT>
