<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-17 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost ground Monday against most other
major currencies in worldwide foreign exchange trading tempered by
anticipation of yet another report due Tuesday on U.S. inflation.
   Gold prices edged up in New York trading after falling overseas.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted an after-hours bid for
gold at $385.30 a troy ounce, up 30 cents from Friday's late bid.
   Traders have grown increasingly uncertain about the prospects
for the dollar as recent U.S. economic reports provided an
inconclusive view of the economy. The U.S. trade deficit widened in
February, but the growth in producer prices slowed in March and the
level of industrial production held steady.
   Traders were looking to Tuesday's scheduled release on the
consumer price index for March to see if inflation is slowing.
   ``We won't see any major direction until we see the CPI
number,'' said Jack Barbanel, manager of futures trading at Gruntal
&amp; Co. in New York.
   He said trading was relatively quiet and there was no sign of
central bank intervention in the currency markets.
   ``Foreign currencies are begining to generate an upswing and we
may see a little bit of correction against the dollar in the short
term. But in the long term, we still see the dollar relatively
strong,'' he said.
   Barbanel said he did not think the Federal Reserve would tighten
credit conditions on the basis of a strong consumer price rise
alone because the producer price figure showed slower growth in
March.
   ``That gives short-term rates a respite for a while,'' he said.
   Rising U.S. interest rates usually give the dollar a lift.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to 131.83 Japanese yen from 132.55 yen
on Friday. In London, the dollar was quoted at 131.70 yen. In New
York, the dollar edged up to 132.155 yen from 132.05 yen late
Friday.
   But the dollar finished lower against most other major
currencies.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7095 Monday from $1.7000
late Friday. In New York, the pound rose to $1.7133 from $1.7055
late Friday.
   Other dollar rates as of 4 p.m. in New York, compared with late
rates Friday, included: 1.8605 West German marks, down from
1.86525; 6.3005 French francs, down from 6.3090; 1.6405 Swiss
francs, 1.6465; 1,366.35 Italian lire, down from 1,368.63; and
1.18495, down from 1.18605.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with Friday's late
rates, included: 1.8565 West German marks, down from 1.8725; 1.6385
Swiss francs, down from 1.6510; 6.2825 French francs, down from
6.3350; 2.0953 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1145; 1,364.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,374.25; 1.1855 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1875.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
edged up 20 cents a troy ounce to close at $386.20 an ounce.
   Earlier, gold traded at $385.00 a troy ounce in London, down
from $386.50 late Friday. The late bid in Zurich was $384.50 an
ounce, down from $387.00 on Friday. In Hong Kong, gold closed at
$385.65 an ounce, down from $382.65.
   Silver for current delivery rose to close at $5.811 an ounce on
the Comex in New York, up from $5.805 late Friday. Silver bullion
traded late in London at a bid $5.80 a troy ounce, down from $5.89
late Friday.
</TEXT>
