<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     04-17 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palladium Prices Tumble; Profit-Taking Cited</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Palladium futures prices came crashing down Monday from 8-year
highs as speculators took profits and lowered their expectations
that nuclear fusion research would lead to explosive demand for the
metal.
   Platinum futures also declined sharply while gold and silver
advanced.
   On other markets, petroleum futures soared; grains and soybeans
were sharply higher; and most livestock and meat futures also
advanced.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, all palladium contracts
except the spot April contract fell the permitted daily limit of $6
a troy ounce. The April contract, which has no limit pending its
upcoming expiration, plunged $12.30 to $168.35 an ounce.
   Platinum settled $18 to $18.50 lower with July at $550.70 a troy
ounce.
   Both metals were components in a University of Utah chemistry
experiment, announced on March 23, in which researchers claimed to
have recreated in a bottle the elusive nuclear reaction that powers
the sun and stars.
   The discovery raised hopes that nuclear fusion could become a
major energy source.
   Last Thursday, palladium rocketed to an 8-year-high and platinum
surged to its highest price in four months as other scientists
replicated the Utah experiment.
   But the speculative fever began cooling Friday and disappeared
Monday morning amid media reports that the fusion research was not
likely to create significantly stronger demand for palladium and
platinum.
   Fred Demler, metals economist with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
in New York, said both markets had become ``sorely overbought and
due for a correction.''
   Gold and silver futures inched higher on New York's Commodity
Exchange in light, cautious trading ahead of Tuesday's government
report on consumer price movement during April.
   Gold settled 20 cents to 30 cents higher with June at $390.10 a
troy ounce; silver was 0.5 cent to 0.6 cent higher with May at
$5.83 a troy ounce.
   Crude oil prices spurted above $21 a barrel on the New York Merc
for the first time in 20 months.
   Analysts said the buying was inspired by chart signals rather
than new supply-and-demand developments. The rally was led by the
unleaded gasoline market, which has been moving higher since
mid-February.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 8 cents to 53 cents
higher with May at $21.22 a barrel; heating oil was .85 cent to
1.19 cents higher with May at 53.76 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1.05 cents to 2.06 cents higher with May at 72.08
cents a gallon.
   Corn and soybean futures surged on the Chicago Board of Trade
amid forecasts for dry and much warmer weather in the western Corn
Belt later this week.
   Many traders remember the dramatic price increases for corn and
soybeans that accompanied last summer's drought, and each day
without rain in the Midwest bolsters the bullish trend despite the
fact that farmers in the region have barely begun their spring
planting.
   ``This is awfully early to be having a weather rally,'' said
Susan Leighty, a grain-market analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in Chicago.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents lower to 3{ cents higher with May at
$4.10\ a bushel; corn was 5{ cents to 6{ cents higher with May at
$2.76} a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 7\ cents higher with May at
$1.99 a bushel; soybeans were 10 cents to 15{ cents higher with May
at $7.47\ a bushel.
   Higher cash prices for fed cattle fueled a moderate rally in
cattle futures prices on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and helped
lift pork futures prices.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to .62 cent higher with June at
71.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .18 cent to .65 cent higher
with May at 76.45 cents a pound; live hogs were .03 cent lower to
.55 cent higher with June at 46.62 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .32 cent to 1.20 cents higher with May at 33.62 cents
a pound.
</TEXT>
