<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MustangAnniversary Bjt   04-17 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mustang Anniversary, Bjt,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford's Mustang Turns 25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With fanfare and a closed-circuit
broadcast, Ford Motor Co. patted itself on the back Monday for the
Mustang, introduced 25 years ago as an inexpensive sporty car that
took the country by storm.
   ``It spawned a whole new class of cars,'' said Michael Marsden,
a professor of pop culture at Bowling Green State University who
was on hand for the birthday party. ``The (Chevrolet) Camaro
wouldn't exist if the Mustang hadn't come along.''
   On April 17, 1964, about five weeks after the first one rolled
off the line at the Dearborn assembly plant, the Mustang was
introduced formally. Living up to the executives' promises, it
weighed 2,570 pounds and cost $2,368.
   Since that day, Ford has built and sold more than 5.7 million
Mustangs, making millions of dollars off the cars. Its best sales
year was in 1966, when 549,000 of the cars were sold. Its worst
sales year was 1983, when 117,000 Mustangs were driven off dealers'
lots.
   The first Mustang, now in the Henry Ford Museum in Dearborn, was
sold to an airplane pilot in St. Johns, Newfoundland, in April
1964. The pilot, Stanley Tucker now of Montreal, was convinced by
Ford to trade in Job 1 for Job 1,000,001 two years later, so that
the original could be preserved.
   On Monday, Ford rolled out a vintage Mustang as officials and
workers gathered to cut a cake in the shape of a Ford oval and
topped by an edible model of a Mustang. Behind the ceremony,
Mustangs continued to be assembled, at a rate of 52 an hour.
   The executives were brought to the plant's finishing area in
Mustangs, of course, to the beat of Wilson Pickett's tune ``Mustang
Sally.'' The ceremony was telecast live to all Ford plants in the
United States and Canada through an in-house broadcast system.
   Plant Manager Lou Callaway, who began his Ford career at the
Dearborn assembly plant and got a rousing cheer Monday when he
stepped from a new Mustang, said in an interview before the
birthday party there was a feeling that the car would do well even
before it was introduced.
   ``You can always tell when a car is going to be successful,'' he
said, ``because the employees are excited about it.''
   One of the employees there when the first Mustang rolled off the
line, and who is still working at the plant is Milton Bevins, 62,
whose enthusiasm for the car continues.
   ``We make the best cars in America,'' said Bevins, whose family
has had three Mustangs _ a blue 1966, a blue '78 and a brown '80.
They were all driven by other members of his family.
   ``I have a '77 (Ford) Grenada,'' he said. ``I refer to it as my
truck.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
