<DOCNO> AP890417-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1822EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Apple-Sculley Bjt   04-17 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apple-Sculley, Bjt,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sculley Says Apple Will Stick To Its Knitting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. will stick to making
personal computers for the mass market rather than going upscale in
the battle against invaders like Sun Microsystems Inc., Chairman
John Sculley said Monday.
   Sculley said some hot new technologies are too expensive and
untried to be offered by Apple itself, although other companies may
offer them as add-ons to the popular Apple Macintosh.
   Apple will offer the new technologies on the Macintosh once they
become cheaper and better accepted, he said.
   As examples he cited artificial intelligence and digital signal
processing chips, which take voices and video signals and turn them
into code that can be acted on by a computer.
   Sculley appeared to be staking out the middle ground of the
personal computer market as Apple's own, putting less emphasis on
the high ground where Apple faces its sternest competition.
   Sun Microsystems last week unveiled a family of low-priced
Sparcstation computers that can zoom through more than 12 million
instructions per second.
   Steve Jobs, who co-founded Apple and went on to create Next
Inc., is pitching a speedy Next workstation that comes in an
elegant black magnesium box.
   Sculley said he does not foresee a collision between personal
computers and workstations, which are cousins of PCs that cost
more, run faster and have superior graphics.
   ``There are a lot of things you have to do to be successful in
the personal computer industry beyond offering hardware under
$10,000,'' Sculley said in a news conference.
   Sun's compact Sparcstation starts at less than $9,000. But
Sculley said it is still about twice the price of the new Macintosh
IIcx, which he described in an earlier speech as possibly the
company's best computer ever. And he said software for the Sun
machine is much more expensive than Macintosh software.
   Still, analysts say the Sun and Next machines are tough
competition for the most expensive Apple models, such as the
Macintosh IIx, which sells for $10,000 to $12,000.
   ``That's one of the reasons they want to emphasize the mid-range
of the products. The competition is getting pretty fierce at the
high end,'' said Laura Lederman, an analyst at Duff &amp; Phelps Inc.
   She said she was concerned that waiting too long to put new
technologies into the Macintosh could leave Apple playing catch-up.
``I don't think they're really any longer at the forefront of
technology.''
   Sculley gave the keynote address at the Macintosh Business
Conference and Exposition, which was billed as the biggest
Macintosh event ever in New York. He followed the speech with a
news conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
