<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0202 04-17 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0202,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Grants More Time In Eastern Bankruptcy Case; Texas Air Says
No Sale</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf pvs, ``This airline ...,'' to
UPDATE with pilots' attorney's statement; picks up 5th graf pvs, `Lifland
held ...'; INSERTS 1 new graf after 7th graf pvs, `After the ...,' to UPDATE
with description of fourth bidder; picks up 8th graf pvs, `The judge's
...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge gave Eastern Airlines
and its creditors an extra week Monday to invite buyers and explore
a possible breakup, but parent Texas Air Corp. said the
strike-strapped airline wasn't for sale.
   The developments added a new twist to the Miami-based airline's
tortuous labor crisis, now in its seventh week, and suggested a
solution was growing more elusive.
   ``As time goes by there are fewer alternatives to explore,''
U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland told a Manhattan courtroom
crammed with about 50 uniformed pilots and lawyers for Texas Air,
creditors and the unions.
   ``This airline is hemorrhaging,'' he said. ``It is not tolerable
that this process be so lengthy that the parties have nothing left
to consider.''
   Bruce Simon, an attorney for the pilots union, told a news
conference that Texas Air ``appears to be in an especial state of
disarray,'' with the company and its lawyers giving conflicting
signals about their planned course of action.
   Lifland held a hearing to determine why he shouldn't put the
entire airline up for sale, including assets held by Eastern before
Texas Air acquired it three years ago for about $676 million.
   Lawyers for Eastern and its creditors talked him into giving
them an extra week to study alternatives, over the objection of
attorneys for the unions and a dissident creditor, Atlanta attorney
Moreton Rolleston, Jr. They have been pushing for more aggressive
court action to get Eastern flying again, either through a sale or
the appointment of an outside trustee to run the airline.
   After the hearing, lawyers for Eastern and the pilots union said
there was another possible bidder besides the three previously
known: ex-baseball boss Peter Ueberroth, hotelier Jay Pritzker and
takeover investor Carl Icahn. They wouldn't identify the fourth
bidder.
   Simon said David I. Shapiro, the bankruptcy examiner for
Eastern, described the fourth bidder to the lawyers involved as ``a
group of substantial capital willing and able to do the
transaction.'' Shapiro told the lawyers Monday he had been in
contact with all four potential suitors, Simon said.
   The judge's order meant that during the week, potential buyers
would gain access to confidential financial data concerning Eastern
in exchange for their pledge to keep the information secret,
participants in the case said.
   Joel Zweibel, the lead attorney for the 15-member committee
representing Eastern's creditors, said the Miami-based airline has
agreed to provide the necessary financial documents.
   ``There might be someone who's interested at the right price,''
said Eastern attorney Harvey Miller.
   Texas Air, however, said its directors had decided not to pursue
the sale of Eastern but will consider selling ``a substantial part
of the company's assets'' to pay down debts.
   The Texas Air board's statement essentially sanctioned Eastern
management's decision announnced last Wednesday, after a deal with
Ueberroth collapsed, to reduce Eastern to about 60 percent of its
pre-strike size. Texas Air spokesman Art Kent said the statement
was unrelated to Lifland's hearing.
   Eastern workers have been on strike since March 4, charging
Texas Air boss Frank Lorenzo has butchered it and plotted to
destroy their unions by transferring valuable assets to sister
carrier Continental Airlines.
   Lorenzo put Eastern into bankruptcy court refuge March 9 and
sought a buyer. Ueberroth nearly completed a $464 million deal to
buy Eastern but the sale flopped over a dispute between the unions
and Lorenzo over who would run the airline until Ueberroth's
investor group could assume control.
   Sources familiar with the Eastern situation have said Ueberroth
remains interested in making a new offer. Pritzker, owner of the
Hyatt hotel chain, and Icahn, owner and chairman of Trans World
Airlines Inc., also have been lurking in the background as possible
buyers.
   The Lifland hearing was jammed with interested bystanders. Among
them was former Pan Am Corp. chairman Ed Acker, who declined to say
why he was there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilAntitrust     04-17 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Antitrust,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Court Revives Suit Against Oil Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Monday allowed
the state of California to go to trial with claims that six major
oil companies conspired to depress the price of oil they pumped
from state-owned tidelands in Long Beach.
   The suits in federal and state court claim losses to the state
and the city of Long Beach totaling $789 million in 1971-77 and
1980-85. Damages tripled under antitrust law would exceed $2.3
billion, and could be increased further by $2,500-a-day penalties
sought under state unfair-competition laws.
   Most of the claimed losses were to the state, which uses
tidelands oil money for school construction. The city of Long Beach
gets a small fraction of the oil money.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals voted 3-0 to reinstate the
suits, which had been dismissed by U.S. District Judge William Gray
of Los Angeles.
   The suits accuse the six companies _ Standard Oil Co. of
California, Texaco Inc., Union Oil, Mobil Corp., Shell Oil Co. and
Exxon Corp. _ of holding down the prices they paid for heavy crude
oil while agreeing secretly to exchange oil among themselves at
higher prices. A seventh defendant, Atlantic Richfield Co., settled
in 1984 by paying $22.5 million.
   Still pending before the appellate court is an appeal by
California and four other states from a ruling by Gray dismissing a
separate antitrust suit against the same seven oil companies, which
accuses them of conspiring to create a gasoline shortage and fix
gasoline prices in the early 1970s.
   In Monday's ruling, the court said the state and city had
presented enough evidence to proceed to trial with claims that the
oil companies conspired to keep artificially low the prices they
paid to Long Beach for heavy crude oil.
   Royce Schulz, a lawyer for the city, said retail prices for oil
products in California were about the same as those elsewhere in
the period, an indication that the companies' actions didn't help
consumers.
   ``Refiners simply pocketed that profit,'' he said.
   The suits contend the companies agreed secretly in the early
1960s, at meetings involving all of them except Exxon, to keep the
posted price for heavy crude below its real value, while exchanging
different grades of oil among themselves at higher rates.
   Lawyers for Long Beach said the elaborate exchange procedure,
unique to California, was disclosed by a state auditor in 1973 but
was being used as late as 1984.
   Types of oil ``were used as a currency _ a medium of exchange
and a new value system _ reserved to the majors (oil companies) and
kept secret from the state and the city,'' Schulz said in a
``background paper'' on the case.
   Gary Halling, another partner in Schulz's firm, said the secrecy
of the exchange system let the oil companies evade a provision of
their contract with Long Beach that required them to pay the city
the highest price they paid any other seller of oil.
   But David Destino, a lawyer for Exxon, said the exchange system
simply allowed oil companies to move their product to market while
guaranteeing that they would get equal value when trading the same
grade of oil from different sources.
   The appeals court said the exchange system did not amount to
price-fixing by itself but could point to the existence of a
conspiracy.
   ``At various times, market conditions should have caused some of
the companies to post higher crude prices,'' said the opinion by
Judge Jerome Farris. ``Posted prices did not correspond to market
value.''
   Farris also rejected Gray's conclusion that federal price
controls and other regulations during the 1971-77 period made it
impossible for the city and state to show any damages, even if they
could prove a price-fixing conspiracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HollyFarms 1stLd-Writethru f0213 04-17 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0213,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Cancels Merger Agreement With ConAgra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Holly Farms-ConAgra merger
canceled, ConAgra reax. Picks up 9th graf, `Tyson is ...'. ^By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp., trying to block a $1.15
billion takeover by a rival poultry processor, said Monday it
failed to convince its stockholders to approve a merger Holly
managers proposed with ConAgra Inc. and would abandon the idea.
   Holly Farms said a preliminary count showed that only 32.5
percent of its stock was voted in favor of the merger with ConAgra
and 47.8 percent against it. The tally was taken Friday with a
two-thirds affirmative vote required.
   Ted Bailey, a Holly Farms vice president, said Holly notified
ConAgra on Monday that the merger was off.
   Holly Farms directors announced the proposed merger with Omaha,
Neb.-based ConAgra last November to ward off a takeover by Tyson
Foods Inc. of Springdale, Ark.
   ``They had to have a two-thirds vote and they didn't even get
one-third,'' Jim Blair, general counsel for Tyson, said of the
shareholder voting. ``I would hope the Holly board would start
paying a little attention to the wishes of their shareholders. I
think this is a mandate to take our deal.''
   The merger agreement included a provision aimed at allowing
ConAgra to purchase key Holly assets in the event the merger
failed. The ``asset-option agreement'' remains in effect, though it
has been temporarily blocked by Delaware Chancery Court on a
challenge by Tyson, Bailey said.
   The court also blocked another provision of the merger proposal
requiring Holly Farms to pay ConAgra $15 million, plus expenses, if
the deal failed.
   Walt Casey, a ConAgra vice president, said his company's
expenses for the merger attempt total $5 million.
   Casey said ConAgra still is interested in Holly Farms, but he
declined to say if his company will make a higher offer to counter
Tyson.
   Tyson is offering Holly stockholders $63.50 a share in cash for
their 18.1 million shares.
   The offer is contingent, however, on removal of the asset-option
agreement between ConAgra and Holly Farms.
   The ConAgra merger, which would have made Holly Farms a ConAgra
subsidiary, called for a $1.1 billion stock swap worth about $61 a
share.
   ``The board will be meeting and reviewing alternatives available
to shareolders and will be asking that the shareholders do nothing
in respect to their stock until they hear from the board,'' Bailey
said.
   Tyson Foods is the nation's largest poultry processor and Holly
Farms, a diversified company, is heavily involved in fresh poultry
sales. ConAgra is one of the largest food companies in the country
with revenues of $9.4 billion last year.
   The asset-option agreement between ConAgra and Holly Farms
allows ConAgra to purchase about one-third of Holly's assets at
prices already negotiated if the Memphis company is bought by
anyone else within the next nine months.
   Tyson contends the asset agreement was an illegal attempt to
make Holly Farms unattractive to any buyer other than ConAgra.
   The Delaware judge hearing Tyson's suit has blocked any
execution of the asset agreement until the legal disputes
surrounding it are settled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0277 </DOCNO>
