experiment was chalked up as a costly failure as the company
scrapped its ETA Systems subsidiary and announced other changes
that will cost about $490 million and leave 3,100 people without
jobs.
   Control Data Chairman Robert Price said Monday that ETA was a
technological success, but lost $100 million in 1988 and never made
money for the company.
