<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate opened debate on President Bush's
slightly altered plan for bailing out savings and loan depositors.
   Sen. Jake Garn of Utah, the ranking Republican on the Senate
Banking Committee, said Monday the bailout costs _ estimated at a
minimum of $157 billion over the next 10 years _ would be only half
as much if in 1986, the Democratic-controlled House had gone along
with a Senate-approved measure to pump $15 billion into the S&amp;L
insurance funds to close insolvent thrifts then.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. will hire 4,000 people to
scrub 305 miles of shoreline fouled by America's worst oil spill,
and says the job can be finished by the third week in August,
according to a new plan.
   The cleanup can be be completed by August if a
``steam-cleaning'' method is used aggressively, or by mid-September
if environmentally safer methods play a larger role, according to
the plan obtained Monday by The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Exxon Corp. vice president told Congress
the Alaskan tanker accident had minimal impact on gasoline prices,
which in recent weeks showed the single largest jump in the history
of the American market.
   J.T. McMillan, senior vice president of Exxon, said Monday the
Valdez, Alaska, oil spill temporarily affected the price of crude
oil to the West Coast, but added He said the onset of the summer
driving season traditionally causes price hikes. Increased
regulations, higher cost imports and added excise taxes were other
contributors to higher prices, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States' link to the burgeoning
economies of the Far East will tighten Tuesday when a fiber-optic
phone cable the size of a garden hose goes into service across the
Pacific Ocean.
   The Pacific Link cable stretches 8,271 miles from California,
through Hawaii, to Guam and Japan. It will vastly increase the
capacity for communication across the Pacific.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. patted itself on the back
for the Mustang, introduced 25 years ago as an inexpensive sporty
car that took the country by storm.
   ``It spawned a whole new class of cars,'' said Michael Marsden,
a professor of pop culture at Bowling Green State University who
was on hand for the car's birthday party Monday.
   The Mustang was formally introduced on April 17, 1964, and Ford
has built and sold more than 5.7 million Mustangs since then.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed mixed Monday in one of the slowest
trading days of the year. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
rose 0.73 point to 2,337.79.
   Most bond prices stagnated or dropped slightly.
   The dollar fell in foreign exchange trading.
   Palladium and platinum futures fell sharply; gold and silver
futures advanced; petroleum futures soared; grains and soybeans
were sharply higher; and most livestock and meat futures also
advanced.

