<FIRST>r f AM-IncomeTaxesRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0161 04-17 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Income Taxes Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0161,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last-Minute Deluge Of Tax Returns In Mail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 9-10, `Actually...' with 6 to add other events and
CORRECT that Conn. and part of N.Y. also affected by Mass. holiday. Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Monday's midnight deadline for filing federal income tax returns
brought the usual deluge of last-minute mailings as people held
onto their money as long as possible, or procrastinated until time
ran out.
   The Postal Service took a tip from the fast food industry in
Columbus, Ohio, where traffic was directed through the front
parking lot of the city's main post office so people could drive
through and hand their completed returns to postal workers
stationed outside.
   ``Any returns we get by midnight, we'll make sure they get
postmarked on the 17th,'' said Debbie Rinehart, a mail processing
clerk at the Columbus main post office.
   People making the mad dash to beat the mailing deadline were
offered entertainment or moral support to improve their mood in
some cities.
   At Lawrence, Kan., the Lawrence Barnstorm Cloggers band was to
perform at the post office from 10 p.m. until midnight, said
spokeswoman Laurie Mackey.
   ``We just want to lift people's spirits,'' Mackey said.
   In Los Angeles, rock station KLSX-FM offered coffee and donuts
at the downtown Terminal Annex, the city's main mail processing
center, which posted buckets at curbside until midnight.
   ``We want to add some merriment and not make the people feel bad
that they're procrastinators,'' said KLSX disc jockey Peter Tilden.
   In Kansas City, Mo., a performance art group called The Stimulus
&amp; Response Co. prepared a show for its fourth annual Tax-a-thon
outside the city's main post office.
   ``At midnight, we release balloons and scream `It's too late!'
'' said Eric George, one of the participants. ``It's a touching
moment. The feeling that they've got your money and there's nothing
you can do about it.''
   In some cities, protesters used the day to demonstrate against
the use of income tax money for military purposes.
   Members of the Northern California War Tax Resistance, based in
Berkeley, distributed $6,000 to various charities, saying the money
came from people who refuse to pay all or part of their federal
taxes because the money is used for ``war and war preparations.''
   Actually, not everyone had to have their returns in the mail by
midnight Monday.
   Residents of Rhode Island, New Hampshire, Maine, Connecticut,
upstate New York and Massachusetts got an extra day this year
because Monday was a holiday, Patriots' Day, in Massachusetts.
Residents of those states mail their returns to the Internal
Revenue Service office at Andover, Mass.
   But for the rest of the country, April 17 was the deadline
because April 15 fell on the weekend.
   Brooks Drake, a district manager who oversees 18 H&amp;R Block Inc.
offices in Dayton, Ohio, said that when he assured worried clients
that they had not missed the filing deadline, ``it was like people
on death row finding out they had gotten a reprieve.''
   Whatever the deadline, IRS Form 4868 _ request for a filing
extension _ is the most-requested form this late in the season,
said Roslyn Russell of the IRS office in South Bend, Ind.
   Officials of the IRS center at Fresno, Calif., said they
expected to receive the majority of the 11.4 million returns from
central and southern California and Hawaii regions by Wednesday. As
of last week, the center had received 5.9 million returns.
   But the deluge of work doesn't mean IRS workers don't have time
for an occasional smile.
   In the IRS Arkansas offices, laughs have sprung from requests
for Form 911, which is reserved for taxpayers who cite unusual
circumstances in requesting a speedy refund or relief from paying
taxes, said IRS spokesman Ken Hubenak in Little Rock.
   ``One person in particular was trying to get us to speed up the
refund check because he had pawned his tools, and wanted us to call
the pawnbroker and explain it to him,'' Hubenak said. ``Another
asked that they call a grocery store and say the check was on the
way.''
</TEXT>
