<DOCNO> AP890417-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 2338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru f0181 04-17 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0181,0884</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Ecologist Says Just Half of Crucial Beaches Can Be Cleaned
by Winter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with state officials demanding
more beaches added to list, better water clean-up, amount of oil on beaches,
other details; CORRECT cleaning method is `hot-water' rather than `steam'
and that Haavig made estimate after reading plan. Picks up 12th graf, `Meanwhile,
wildlife...' ADDS 1 graf with Exxon Valdez deemed sound enough to travel
to Oregon. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos VDX1,2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon will hire 4,000 people to scrub at
least 305 miles of shoreline fouled by America's worst oil spill,
and says the job can be finished by the third week in August,
according to a plan released Monday.
   The cleanup can be be completed by August if a hot-water
cleaning method that can damge beach life is used aggressively, or
by mid-September if environmentally safer methods play a larger
role, the draft plan says.
   Those projections were disputed by a state ecologist, who said
after reviewing the plan that only about 150 miles could be cleaned
before winter. And the top state environmental official called for
the plan to be broadened to include areas where the oil has spread
outside Prince William Sound.
   ``It's a start,'' said Department of Environmental Conservation
chief Dennis Kelso. ``It needs more work.''
   The plan estimates that by June 1 the company will have 2,500
Alaskans working on the shoreline, with 1,500 other people in
support roles. It says 11 barges, 28 landing vessels, 150 utility
ships, and six wash-vacuum ships will be used.
   According to the plan, the total shoreline in Prince William
Sound affected by the March 24 Exxon Valdez wreck is 366 miles _
about the distance from New York City to Norfolk, Va., or Los
Angeles to Phoenix, Ariz.
   Concentration of oil on the beach runs from 1,260 gallons to
12,600 gallons per mile, with an average of 4,200 gallons per mile,
the oil company said. The plan said Exxon so far has recovered
924,000 gallons, or 9 percent, of the spilled oil.
   The plan proposes to clean up 305 miles. It estimates that 54
miles are heavily oiled, 86 moderately oiled and 165 lightly oiled.
It assumes that needed permits will be promptly issued and that no
additional oil will wash ashore.
   But Steve Haavig of the Department of Environmental Conservation
estimated after reviewing the plan that crews would be able to
scrape and spray greasy black sludge from only about one mile of
beach per day.
   ``A mile a day is optimistic,'' Haavig said.
   At most, there are 150 days from the time workers and gear are
mobilized, two or three weeks from now, until winter descends in
September.
   Haavig said crews might make good time on lightly oiled beaches,
but the more heavily polluted stretches will slow them.
   Asked for comment, Exxon spokesman Dennis Stanczuk said the
company wanted to confer first with the Coast Guard commandant,
Adm. Paul Yost, who was sent by President Bush to hasten the
cleanup.
   Kelso, in a letter to Yost, demanded that Exxon improve its
cleanup of oil still in the water.
   He said the company should come up with a plan by April 25 to
clean beaches beyond Prince William Sound in the Gulf of Alaska,
where the oil has spread. He said he also wants data on how to
manage and dispose of wastes.
   Meanwhile, wildlife officials brought grim reports from the Nuka
Island and Nuka Bay area on the Kenai Peninsula, about 175 miles
southwest of where the Exxon Valdez smashed into Bligh Reef.
   ``They found a lot of dead birds and a lot of live, oiled
birds,'' Glenn Seaman of the Alaska Department of Fish and Game
said in Homer. ``There's otter tracks on every beach.''
   Part of the herring grounds at the north end of the Kodiak
Islands remained closed Monday because of oil sightings. It was
feared the more important herring fishery at Kamishak Bay might not
be able to begin as scheduled later this week.
   Prince William Sound lies south of Valdez, the seaport where the
trans-Alaska oil pipeline ends. Until the spill, its waters and
islands had been among the most scenic in the nation, and few
places in the world are richer in wildlife and fish.
   Yost spent part of Sunday at Block Island in the sound, where
muck was puddled ankle-deep in places. Exxon had assembled state
and federal officials and reporters for a demonstration of cleanup
methods, including an environmentally risky steam-cleaning
technique that sterilizes the shore.
   Haavig also was on Block Island, checking the depth of the beach
contamination. In some places, the oil had soaked in only an inch.
In others, it was found several inches deep. ``They're never going
to get it all,'' he said.
   In Portland, Ore., meanwhile, state environmental chief Fred
Hansen said the crippled Exxon Valdez appeared sound enough to make
it to the Port of Portland for evaluation. He said he expected
Exxon to agree to several conditions before officials allow the
tanker to travel up the Columbia River.
</TEXT>
