<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0276 04-17 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0276,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Morning Nikkei, comments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar traded higher against the Japanese
yen at midday Tuesday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange posted a moderate loss.
   The dollar, which opened at 132.23 yen, up 0.40 yen from
Monday's 131.83-yen finish, was quoted at 132.20 yen at midday. The
currency moved in a narrow range of 132.10-132.27 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
157.89 points to close at a record-high 33,308.33 Monday, ended the
morning session at 33,254.49, down 53.84 points or 0.16 percent.
   The index rose marginally in early morning trading but began
falling as investors sold for profit taking, said Tsuneo Ishii with
Nomura Securities.
   ``That's mainly because participants were concerned about the
U.S. consumer price index report to be released later tonight and
avoided buying,'' he said.
   Later Tuesday, Washington was to announce the March U.S.
consumer price index, which measures changes in the retail prices
of a constant market basket of goods and services.
   Investors also were discouraged by concerns over the Recruit
bribery scandal, dealers said. Prosecutors are expected to make
more arrests this week in connection with the affair.
   So far, prosecutors have arrested 14 people in connection with
stock profiteering and suspected bribery linked to a major
information services firm, Recruit Co.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate was moving little as
market players avoided making major moves ahead of the U.S. CPI
announcement, traders said.
</TEXT>
